{"title_page": "George Edwards (writer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{cleanup rewrite|date = February 2011}}\n'''George Edwards''', (1752\u201317 February 1823) was a Scottish physician and writer.\n\n==Life==\nEdwards took his degree at the [[University of Edinburgh]] in 1772, and appears to have practised as a physician in London, and latterly at [[Barnard Castle]], Durham. He was an untiring propounder of political and social schemes between 1779 and 1819. It does not appear that Edwards attracted any attention, and he may not have been entirely sane. He died in London on 17 February 1823, aged 77.\n\n==Works==\nThe [[British Museum]] contained 42  of his books; the following titles are representative: 'A certain Way to save our Country, and make us a more happy and flourishing people than at any former period of our history ' (1807); 'The Practical System of Human Economy, or the New Era at length fully ascertained, whereby we are able in one immediate simple undertaking to remove the distress, burdens, and grievances of the times, and to bring all our interests, public, private, and commercial, to their intended perfection' (1816).\n\nEdwards's writings abound in the unconscious humour of the egotist deeply persuaded of his mission. He gives notice that 'the Almighty has destined that I should discover his true system of human economy.' In a petition to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] (1816?) he prays that the house should carry out the schemes which were the fruits of 'almost half a century's attention.' Among his proposals were the removal of taxes hurtful to industry, economy and reduction of public expenditure, the sale of certain national properties, particularly [[Gibraltar]], the extension of the income tax to all orders, and forbearance for any requisite period to pay off the national debt as 'altogether superfluous with the accession of the new and happy era of mankind.' Government boards were to superintend all the interests of mankind, and everybody was to be actuated by truly Christian principles.\n\nHe published an address 'aux citoyens Fran\u00e7ais sur la Nouvelle Constitution,' and 'Id\u00e9es pour former une Nouvelle Constitution, et pour assurer la prosp\u00e9rit\u00e9 et le bonheur de la France et d'autres nations' (Paris, 1793).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DNB|wstitle=Edwards, George (1752-1823)}}\n{{One source|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, George}}\n[[Category:1752 births]]\n[[Category:1823 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:19th-century English medical doctors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{cleanup-rewrite|date = February 2011}}\n'''George Edwards''', (1752\u201317 February 1823) was a Scottish physician and writer.\n\n==Life==\nEdwards took his degree at the [[University of Edinburgh]] in 1772, and appears to have practised as a physician in London, and latterly at [[Barnard Castle]], Durham. He was an untiring propounder of political and social schemes between 1779 and 1819. It does not appear that Edwards attracted any attention, and he may not have been entirely sane. He died in London on 17 February 1823, aged 77.\n\n==Works==\nThe [[British Museum]] contained 42  of his books; the following titles are representative: 'A certain Way to save our Country, and make us a more happy and flourishing people than at any former period of our history ' (1807); 'The Practical System of Human Economy, or the New Era at length fully ascertained, whereby we are able in one immediate simple undertaking to remove the distress, burdens, and grievances of the times, and to bring all our interests, public, private, and commercial, to their intended perfection' (1816).\n\nEdwards's writings abound in the unconscious humour of the egotist deeply persuaded of his mission. He gives notice that 'the Almighty has destined that I should discover his true system of human economy.' In a petition to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] (1816?) he prays that the house should carry out the schemes which were the fruits of 'almost half a century's attention.' Among his proposals were the removal of taxes hurtful to industry, economy and reduction of public expenditure, the sale of certain national properties, particularly [[Gibraltar]], the extension of the income tax to all orders, and forbearance for any requisite period to pay off the national debt as 'altogether superfluous with the accession of the new and happy era of mankind.' Government boards were to superintend all the interests of mankind, and everybody was to be actuated by truly Christian principles.\n\nHe published an address 'aux citoyens Fran\u00e7ais sur la Nouvelle Constitution,' and 'Id\u00e9es pour former une Nouvelle Constitution, et pour assurer la prosp\u00e9rit\u00e9 et le bonheur de la France et d'autres nations' (Paris, 1793).\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DNB|wstitle=Edwards, George (1752-1823)}}\n{{One source|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, George}}\n[[Category:1752 births]]\n[[Category:1823 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:19th-century English medical doctors]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Edwards_(writer)"}
{"title_page": "Juice Wrld", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American rapper, singer, and songwriter from Illinois}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Juice Wrld\n| image              = Juice Wrld Interview.png\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = A photograph of Juice Wrld talking into a microphone during an interview\n| caption            = Higgins during an interview in July 2018\n| birth_name         = Jarad Anthony Higgins\n| alias              = JuiceTheKidd\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1998|12|02}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2019|12|08|1998|12|02}}\n| death_place        = [[Oak Lawn, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Seizure]] induced by acute [[oxycodone]] and  [[codeine]] [[substance intoxication|intoxication]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter}}<!--Please do not add any more occupations to the list, it is long enough already-->\n| awards             = \n| website            = {{URL|juicewrld999.com/}}\n| signature          = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| instrument      = Vocals<!--If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first-->\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = <!--These music genres are all sourced under the section #Musical themes and genres-->{{hlist||[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Trap music|trap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/10/25/660628679/could-future-juice-wrld-be-traps-trojan-horse-advocates-for-drug-policy-reform|title=Could Future & Juice WRLD Be Trap's Trojan-Horse Advocates For Drug Policy Reform?|publisher=NPR|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>|[[emo rap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/juice-wrld-interview-lucid-dreams-2374917/amp|title=Juice WRLD: the emo rapper on his surprise hit 'Lucid Dreams'|website=NME|accessdate=March 15, 2019|date=September 18, 2018}}</ref>|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[SoundCloud rap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/.amp/features/2018-07-26-juice-wrld-on-soundcloud-rapper-title|title=Juice WRLD on SoundCloud Rapper Title: \"It's Just Not What People Think It Is\" \u2013 DJBooth|website=djbooth.net|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>|[[alternative R&B]]}}\n| years_active    = 2015\u20132019\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Lil Bibby|Grade A]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| associated_acts = <!--These associated acts are all sourced under #Discography-->{{flatlist|\n* [[Future (rapper)|Future]]\n* [[Lil Bibby]]\n* [[Nick Mira]]\n* [[Ski Mask the Slump God]]\n* [[Trippie Redd]]\n* [[YNW Melly]]\n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Jarad Anthony Higgins''' (December 2, 1998 \u2013 December 8, 2019), known professionally as '''Juice Wrld''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d\u0292|u|s|_|\u02c8|w|\u025c|r|l|d}}; stylized as '''Juice WRLD'''), was an American rapper, singer, and songwriter, born in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. He is known mostly for his single \"[[Lucid Dreams (Juice Wrld song)|Lucid Dreams]]\", which has been played on the music streaming platform [[Spotify]] over one billion times. His posthumous feature on his idol, American rapper [[Eminem]]'s January 2020 single, \"[[Godzilla (Eminem song)|Godzilla]]\", has also contributed to the rapper's meteoric rise in popularity following his tragic death. \"Lucid Dreams\" and his other hit single \"[[All Girls Are the Same]]\" helped him gain a recording contract with [[Lil Bibby]]'s [[Lil Bibby|Grade A Productions]] and [[Interscope Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=311520&title=JUICE-WRLD-GOES-VIRAL-AT-SPOTIFY&redirect=mobile|title=HITS Daily Double : Rumor Mill \u2013 JUICE WRLD GOES VIRAL AT SPOTIFY|website=HITS Daily Double|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"All Girls Are the Same\" and \"Lucid Dreams\" acted as singles for Juice Wrld's debut studio album ''[[Goodbye & Good Riddance]]'', which was released in May 2018, which became certified [[Music recording certification|Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). The album enjoyed positive critical reception, and contained three other singles: \"[[Armed and Dangerous (song)|Armed and Dangerous]]\", \"[[Lean wit Me]]\" and \"[[Wasted (Juice Wrld song)|Wasted]]\", featuring [[Lil Uzi Vert]], all of which charted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. After collaborating with [[Future (rapper)|Future]] on the mixtape ''[[Wrld on Drugs]]'' (2018), Juice Wrld released his second studio album ''[[Death Race for Love]]'' in March 2019, which [[List of Billboard 200 number-one albums of 2019|went to number one]] on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].\n\n==Early life==\nJarad Higgins was born on December 2, 1998, in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].<ref name=\":2\" /> He moved to [[Homewood, Illinois]] in 1999 and attended [[Homewood-Flossmoor High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/Chicago-Area-Friends-Fans-Mourn-Accomplished-Artist-Juice-WRLD-565949501.html|title=Friends, Fans Mourn 'Accomplished' Chicago-Area Rapper Juice WRLD|publisher=[[NBC|NBC Chicago]]|date=December 8, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was three years old<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.gulf-times.com/story/601209/Juice-Wrld-s-music-is-confusing-but-popular|title=Juice Wrld's music is confusing but popular|date=July 30, 2018|work=Gulf Times|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> and his father left, leaving his mother to raise him as a [[single mother]] alongside one older brother.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X--KpcpzyzI|title=Juice Wrld Exposed!|author=No Jumper|date=March 7, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> Higgins' mother was very religious and conservative, and did not let him listen to [[hip hop]]. He was, however, allowed to listen to rock and pop music he found on video games such as ''[[Tony Hawk's Pro Skater]]'' and ''[[Guitar Hero]]'', which introduced him to artists such as [[Billy Idol]], [[Blink-182]], [[Black Sabbath]], [[Fall Out Boy]], [[Megadeth]], and [[Panic! at the Disco]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://radiomilwaukee.org/discover-music/music-news/juice-wrld-concert-review-impact-emo-rap/|title=Juice WRLD and the evolution of 'emo-rap'|work=88Nine Radio Milwaukee|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Citation|last=Durtty Daily|title=Juice Wrld Shares Some of His Biggest Influences in Music & His Name Before He Was Juice Wrld.|date=July 18, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J_Fl4hMIrso|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHiggins was a heavy [[Substance abuse|drug user]] during his childhood and teens. He began drinking [[Purple drank|lean]] in sixth grade and using [[Oxycodone/paracetamol|percocets]] and [[Alprazolam|xanax]] in 2013. Higgins also smoked cigarettes, quitting in his last year of high school due to health issues.<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|last=HOTSPOTATL|title=Juice Wrld Shares What His Favorite Class in Grade School Is|date=July 19, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gTH3AYUP9sE|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe first learned to play the piano at four years old, having been inspired by his mother, who later began paying for lessons, followed by guitar and drums. Higgins also played trumpet for band class.<ref name=\":1\" /> In his sophomore year of high school, he started posting songs to his [[SoundCloud]] which he recorded on his cell phone.<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/arts/music/juice-wrld-goodbye-good-riddance.html|title=The Chart-Topping Deep Feelings of Juice WRLD|last1=Caramanica|first1=Jon|date=July 25, 2018|work=The New York Times|accessdate=December 8, 2019}}</ref> Around this time, Higgins began to take rapping more seriously.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/06/juice-wrld-interview-exclusive|title=How 19-Year-Old Juice WRLD Scored a $3 Million Record Deal Without a Plan|website=Complex|accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Elevator\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elevatormag.com/juicewrld-interview/|title=An Interview with Juice Wrld|work=Elevator|last=Ware|first=Tajah|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nHiggins began to develop himself as an artist in his first year of high school. His first track, \"Forever\", was released on [[SoundCloud]] in 2015 under the name JuicetheKidd. Higgins recorded a majority of his first tracks on a cellphone, uploading them to SoundCloud in his sophomore year.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /> His name changed from JuicetheKidd, a name inspired by his affection for rapper [[Tupac Shakur]] and his part in the film ''[[Juice (film)|Juice]]'', to Juice Wrld because it \"represents taking over the world.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nHis first track produced by his main producer [[Nick Mira]], \"Too Much Cash\", was released in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/uiceheidd/too-much-cash|title=Too Much Cash (Prod. Nick Mira)|website=[[SoundCloud]]|accessdate=April 20, 2018}}</ref> While releasing projects and songs on SoundCloud, Higgins worked in a factory, but was fired within two weeks after finding himself dissatisfied with the job.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/interviews/2018/04/juice-wrld-interview|title=It's All Authentic: An Interview With Juice WRLD|work=Pigeons & Planes|last=Ison|first=Eric|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> After joining the internet collective Internet Money, Higgins released his debut full-length EP, ''9 9 9'', on June 15, 2017, with the song \"[[Lucid Dreams (Juice WRLD song)|Lucid Dreams]]\" breaking out and growing his following.<ref name=\"ChicagoReader\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2018/03/19/tracking-the-astronomical-rise-of-chicagoland-rapper-juice-wrld|title=Tracking the astronomical rise of Chicagoland rapper Juice Wrld|work=[[Chicago Reader]]|last=Galil|first=Leor|date=March 19, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Elevator\" />\n\nIn mid-2017, the artist began to receive attention from artists such as [[Waka Flocka Flame]] and [[Southside (record producer)|Southside]], as well as fellow Chicago artists [[G Herbo]] and [[Lil Bibby]]. He  subsequently signed with the latter's co-owned record label, Grade A Productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2018-07-26-juice-wrld-on-soundcloud-rapper-title|title=Juice WRLD on SoundCloud Rapper Title: \"It's Just Not What People Think It Is\"|first=Donna-Claire|last=Chesman|website=DJBooth|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132018: ''Goodbye & Good Riddance''===\nIn December 2017, Higgins released the three-song EP ''Nothings Different''. It was featured on numerous hip-hop blogs, such as Lyrical Lemonade,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lyricallemonade.com/nothings-different-juice-wrld/|title=Nothings Different \u2013 [Juice WRLD]|website=Lyrical Lemonade|last=Martinez|first=Elliot|date=February 5, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> which helped Higgins's track \"[[All Girls Are the Same]]\" gain popularity. In February 2018, a music video directed by [[Cole Bennett]] was released.<ref name=\"ChicagoReader\"/> Following the video's release, Higgins was signed to Interscope Records for $3,000,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8244598/juice-wrld-signs-interscope-3-million-joint-venture|title=Juice WRLD Signs With Interscope|work=Billboard|last=Stutz|first=Colin|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> and a remix featuring [[Lil Yachty]] was previewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/juice-wrld-previews-remix-lucid-dreams-lil-uzi-vert|title=Juice WRLD Previews a Remix of 'Lucid Dreams' With Lil Uzi Vert|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Margaritoff|first=Marco|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> \"All Girls Are the Same\" was critically praised, receiving a \"Best New Music\" designation from ''Pitchfork''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/juice-wrld-all-girls-are-the-same/|title=\"All Girls Are the Same\" by Juice WRLD Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Pearce|first=Sheldon|date=March 5, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> This song and \"Lucid Dreams\" were Higgins's first entries on a ''Billboard'' chart, debuting at number 92 and 74 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 respectively.<ref name=\"Hot100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-debuts-two-songs-on-billboard-hot-100-chart-news.50815.html|title=Juice WRLD Debuts Two Songs on Billboard Hot 100 Chart|work=HotNewHipHop|last=Parizot|first=Matthew|date=May 22, 2018|accessdate=May 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, \"Lucid Dreams\" was officially released as a single and given a video.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-returns-with-clip-for-lucid-dreams-new-video.43715.html|title=Juice WRLD Returns With Clip For 'Lucid Dreams'|work=HotNewHipHop|last=P.|first=Milca|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> It then went on to peak at number two on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"Lucid Dreams peak\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8463605/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny|title=Cardi B Becomes First Female Rapper With Two Billboard Hot 100 No. 1s, as 'I Like It', With Bad Bunny & J Balvin, Follows 'Bodak Yellow' to the Top|work=Billboard}}</ref> and quickly became one of the biggest streaming songs of 2018.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /> Higgins released his first studio album, ''[[Goodbye & Good Riddance]]'', on May 23, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2018/05/juice-wrld-goodbye-good-riddance|title=Juice WRLD's 'Goodbye & Good Riddance' Project Has Arrived|work=PigeonsandPlanes|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> On June 19, 2018, he released a two-song EP, ''Too Soon..'', in remembrance of and dedicated to deceased rappers [[Lil Peep]] and [[XXXTentacion]], the latter of whom was [[Murder of XXXTentacion|killed in a homicide case relating to robbery]] a day earlier. The song \"[[Legends (Juice Wrld song)|Legends]]\" from the EP charted under its debut at number 65.\n\nHiggins' first single featuring a collaboration was released on July 10, 2018, titled \"[[Wasted (Juice Wrld song)|Wasted]]\" featuring Lil Uzi Vert. The song was added to ''Goodbye & Good Riddance'' and debuted at number 67 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/07/juice-wrld-lil-uzi-vert-wasted-listen/|title=Juice WRLD \u2013 \"Wasted\" ft. Lil Uzi Vert: Listen|date=July 10, 2018|work=Spin|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> The next day, Higgins announced he was working on his next album.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8464961/juice-wrld-teases-more-projects-2018-tweets|title=Juice WRLD Hints at Releasing More Projects in 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> Following a series of leaks, Higgins' producer Danny Wolf released \"Motions\" on SoundCloud, giving the song an official release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.47803/title.juice-wrlds-motions-gets-soundcloud-release-after-leak#|title=Juice WRLD's \"Motions\" Gets SoundCloud Release After Leak|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> On July 20, 2018, Higgins announced his first tour, \"WRLD Domination\" with additional acts [[YBN Cordae]] and [[Lil Mosey]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-announces-wrld-domination-tour-dates-news.54241.html|title=Juice WRLD Announces 'WRLD Domination' Tour Dates|work=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u20132020: ''Wrld on Drugs'', ''Death Race for Love'' and death===\n[[File:Juice Wrld VMAs.png|thumb|left|Higgins at the [[2018 MTV Video Music Awards]] in August 2018]]\nHiggins was featured alongside [[Sheck Wes]] on [[Travis Scott]]'s song \"No Bystanders\", from Scott's third studio album, ''[[Astroworld (album)|Astroworld]]''. The song peaked at number 31 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/travis-scott-astroworld-tracklist-features-stream-drake-frank-ocean-the-weeknd-a8475551.html|title=Travis Scott releases ASTROWORLD: From Frank Ocean to The Weeknd, who features on his new album?|work=The Independent|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/08/03/everyone-features-travis-scotts-new-album-astroworld-7793625/|title=Everyone who features on Travis Scott's new album Astroworld|date=August 3, 2018|work=Metro|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/travis-scott/chart-history/hot-100|title=Travis Scott Chart History|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> He also made his late night television debut performing the song \"Lucid Dreams\" on [[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]] on August 8, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8469296/juice-wrld-lucid-dreams-performance-jimmy-kimmel-video|title=Juice WRLD Makes Late Night Television Debut With Starry 'Lucid Dreams' Performance On 'Kimmel': Watch|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> On October 15, 2018, the music video for the song \"[[Armed and Dangerous (song)|Armed and Dangerous]]\" was released<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/juice-wrld-armed-and-dangerous/|title=Juice WRLD's \"Armed & Dangerous\": Listen to It Here|date=October 17, 2018|work=Highsnobiety|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> and the lead single for the collaborative mixtape, ''[[Wrld on Drugs]]'' with [[Future (rapper)|Future]] was also released, called \"[[Fine China (Future and Juice Wrld song)|Fine China]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/10/future-and-juice-wrld-link-up-fine-china|title=Future and Juice WRLD Link Up for 'Fine China'|website=Complex|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> The mixtape was released on October 19, 2018, via [[Epic Records]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/future-and-juice-wrld-share-album-cover-and-release-date-for-wrld-on-drugs-news.62472.html |title=Future & Juice WRLD Share Album Cover & Release Date For \"WRLD on Drugs\" |website=HotNewHipHop |accessdate=October 18, 2018}}</ref> He also contributed to the [[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] for ''[[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse]]'' in December 2018, with a song from the soundtrack, titled \"Hide\", featuring American singer Seezyn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/spider-man-soundtrack-tracklisting/|title=Nicki Minaj, Lil Wayne And Others Appear On Spider-Man Soundtrack|last=Stavropoulos|first=Laura|date=December 10, 2018|website=uDiscover Music|publisher=[[Universal Music Group]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, [[Ski Mask the Slump God]] confirmed that he and Higgins would release a joint mixtape called ''Evil Twins'' in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/12/ski-mask-slump-god-juice-wrld-evil-twins-project/|title=SKI MASK THE SLUMP GOD AND JUICE WRLD'S 'EVIL TWINS' PROJECT TO ARRIVE IN 2019|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]}}</ref> The pair also announced a 2019 tour featuring 30 concerts across North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/juice-wrld-north-american-tour-796938/|title=Juice WRLD Lines Up North American Tour|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=February 21, 2019}}</ref> Higgins' second studio album, ''[[Death Race for Love]]'', was released on March 8, 2019.<ref name=\"deathrace\">{{cite web |last1=Bloom |first1=Madison |title=Juice WRLD Announces New Album A Deathrace for Love |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/juice-wrld-announces-new-album-a-deathrace-for-love/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=February 8, 2019|date=February 8, 2019}}</ref> The album topped the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart. He then embarked on [[The Nicki Wrld Tour]], alongside Trinidadian-American rapper [[Nicki Minaj]].<ref name=\"Nicki\">{{cite web |last1=Renshaw |first1=David |title=Nicki Minaj confirms Juice WRLD will replace Future on her European tour |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/12/21/nicki-minaj-future-juice-wrld-european-tour |website=The fader |publisher=Andy Cohn |accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref> Higgins released the music video for the song \"Fast\" from the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/04/juice-wrld-fast-video|title=Juice WRLD Releases New Video for \"Fast\"|website=Complex|accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref> Later that year, he released other singles: \"[[All Night (BTS and Juice Wrld song)|All Night]]\", with [[RM (rapper)|RM]] and [[Suga (rapper)|Suga]] of [[BTS (band)|BTS]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bts/8516964/bts-juice-wrld-all-night|title=BTS' RM and Suga Team Up With Juice WRLD For 'All Night': Listen|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=June 21, 2019|website=Billboard|url-status=live|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> \"[[Hate Me (Ellie Goulding and Juice Wrld song)|Hate Me]]\", with [[Ellie Goulding]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.much.com/ellie-goulding-juice-wrld-hate-me/|title=Ellie Goulding And Juice WRLD Get Angry On 'Hate Me'|date=June 27, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|publisher=Much|last=Gao|first=Stephanie}}</ref> \"Run\";<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8518901/juice-wrld-run|title=Juice Wrld Drops Melancholic New Track 'Run': Listen|date=July 8, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Saponara|first=Michael}}</ref> \"[[Graduation (Benny Blanco and Juice Wrld song)|Graduation]]\", with [[Benny Blanco]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-and-benny-blanco-serenade-high-school-crushes-on-graduation-new-song.1984327.html|title=Juice WRLD & Benny Blanco Serenade High School Crushes On \"Graduation\"|date=August 29, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|publisher=HotNewHipHop|last=Findlay|first=Mitch}}</ref> and \"[[Bandit (song)|Bandit]]\" with [[YoungBoy Never Broke Again|NBA YoungBoy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/10/03/listen-to-juice-wrld-nba-youngboy-new-track-bandit-2019|title=Listen to Juice WRLD and NBA YoungBoy's new track \"Bandit\"|website=[[The Fader]]|last=D'Souza|first=Shaad|date=October 3, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/videos/Juice-wrld-nba-youngboys-bandit-explained|title=Juice WRLD Reunites With Cole Bennett On Video For YoungBoy Never Broke Again-Assisted \"Bandit\"|date=October 5, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|publisher=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]}}</ref> \n\nOn December 8, 2019, Higgins collapsed and died from a suspected drug-induced [[seizure]] at [[Midway International Airport]] in Chicago, after landing at Midway on a [[private jet]] from [[Van Nuys Airport]] in [[Los Angeles]]. His death provoked an outpouring of grief across social media and the music industry. Higgins' [[funeral]] was held in [[Harvey, Illinois]] on five days later, on December 13, 2019. \n\nHiggins' first posthumous appearance was on [[Eminem]]'s surprise eleventh studio album, ''[[Music to Be Murdered By]],'' on the track, \"[[Godzilla (Eminem song)|Godzilla]]\", released in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/music/eminem-drops-surprise-album-featuring-ed-sheeran-and-late-rapper-juice-wrld/|title=Eminem Drops Surprise Album Featuring Ed Sheeran and Late Rapper Juice WRLD|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/01/eminem-music-to-be-murdered-by-stream|title=Stream Eminem's Surprise Album 'Music to Be Murdered By' f/ Juice WRLD, Ed Sheeran, Royce da 5'9\", and More|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Musical style===\n\nHiggins stated his musical influences as being genre-wide going from rock music to rap music. Higgins stated that his biggest influences were rappers [[Travis Scott]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-says-travis-scott-is-his-biggest-inspiration-wants-to-collaborate-news.53595.html|title=Juice WRLD Says Travis Scott Is His Biggest Inspiration, Wants To Collaborate|work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref> [[Chief Keef]],<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Kanye West]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/04/juice-wrld-interview|title=It's All Authentic: An Interview With Juice WRLD|website=Complex|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.themodernlifemag.com/music/2018/3/7/juice-wrld-talks-about-his-influences-being-inspired-by-rock-and-more-on-no-jumper-exposed|title=JUICE WRLD talks about his influences, being inspired by rock, and more on No Jumper \"Exposed\"|magazine=Modern Life Mag|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref> and British rock singer [[Billy Idol]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Why Does Juice WLRD Want To Collab With Billy Idol? {{!}} Exclusive Interview|work=iHeartRadio|date=July 30, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W53VFda4mlA|accessdate=August 20, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nardwuar vs. Juice WRLD|work=NardwuarServiette|date=June 11, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kN7NfAj5pKY|accessdate=August 20, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> Juice Wlrd was among the ranks of openly vulnerable artists born from the [[emo rap]] scene inspired by West's influential fourth album, ''[[808s & Heartbreak]]'' (2008).<ref name=\"Saponara\"/> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' writer Michael Saponara claimed, \"If West and his sparse ''[[808s and Heartbreak|808s]]'' were a tree, it would have grown another branch with the blossoming art displayed by fellow Chicago native Juice WRLD in 2018.\"<ref name=\"Saponara\"/> During an interview with All Def Music, Juice Wrld imparted, \"I was singing '[[Street Lights (Kanye West song)|Street Lights]]' like I had shit to be sad about. Kanye is a time traveler. That n---a went to damn near 2015 and came back with some sauce.\"<ref name=\"Saponara\">{{cite web|author=Saponara, Michael|title=Kanye West's 808s & Heartbreak Turns 10: Engineer Anthony Kilhoffer Revisits the Influential Album|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8485555/kanye-west-808-and-heartbreak-10-year-anniversary|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=November 24, 2018|accessdate=November 26, 2018}}</ref> His other influences included [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Fall Out Boy]], [[Black Sabbath]], [[Megadeth]], [[2Pac]], [[Eminem]], [[Kid Cudi]] and [[Escape the Fate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-reveals-the-origin-of-his-name-and-his-major-influences-news.50999.html|title=Juice WRLD Reveals The Origin of His Name & His Major Influences|work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Juice WRLD Breaks Down Tupac & Eminem's Influence on His Music|date=July 23, 2018|work=TRL|publisher=MTV|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fsaolirWIKQ|access-date=August 20, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Juice WRLD lists his Top 5 favorite artist {{!}} Interview|website=Genius|date=September 10, 2019|url=https://genius.com/a/juice-wrld-lists-his-top-5-favorite-artists|access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> \n{{Listen|pos = right\n|filename=Lucid Dreams.ogg\n|title=\"Lucid Dreams\"\n|description=\"Lucid Dreams\" is a piercing [[Melody|melodic]] rap song.<ref name=\"Williams\">{{cite web |author=Williams, Aaron |url=https://uproxx.com/hiphop/juice-wrld-lean-wit-me-video/|title=Juice Wrld Delivers A Harrowing Statement On Substance Abuse In His 'Lean Wit Me' Video|work=[[Uproxx]] |publisher=[[Uproxx Media Group|Uproxx Media Group, Inc]] | date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018}}</ref> It features emotionally vulnerable lyrics imbued with teenage angst. The song contains a sample of \"[[Shape of My Heart (Sting song)|Shape of My Heart]]\" by [[Sting (musician)|Sting]].<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |last1=Caramanica |first1=Jon |title=The Chart-Topping Deep Feelings of Juice WRLD |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/arts/music/juice-wrld-goodbye-good-riddance.html |accessdate=January 9, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102040036/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/arts/music/juice-wrld-goodbye-good-riddance.html |archivedate=January 2, 2019 |date=July 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|format=[[Ogg]]\n|filename2=Lean Wit Me.ogg\n|title2=\"Lean Wit Me\"\n|description2=\"Lean Wit Me\" harbors dark lyrical themes.<ref name=\"Williams\" /> It bears a strong fixation on addiction as well as contemplations of mortality. The song's lyrics are laced with references to narcotics and [[binge drinking|binging]]. They serve to impart on the consequences of [[substance abuse]] and overindulgence.<ref name=\"Burks\">{{cite web|author=Burks, Tosten |title=Juice Wrld Attends Group Therapy in New 'Lean Wit Me' Video|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/video/2018/08/juice-wrld-lean-wit-me-video/|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|publisher=[[Harris Publications|Harris Publications Inc.]]|date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018}}</ref> Juice Wrld's melodic vocal style veers on melancholic [[Crooner|crooning]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Lamarre, Carl|title=Juice WRLD Shrugs Off Michael Jackson Comparison, Calls Working With Future 'A Blessing': Exclusive|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8482112/juice-wrld-future-wrld-on-drugs-michael-jackson-interview|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 29, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|format2=[[Ogg]]\n | type = music\n}}\n\nHiggins' music has been branded as \"emo\" and \"rock\" leaning, \"genre-bending\"<ref name=\"auto1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> with music focusing on \"every broken heart, every wounded feeling.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2001216/juice-wrld-toxic-masculinity/franchises/status-aint-hood/|title=Juice WRLD And SoundCloud Rap's Toxic Masculinity|date=June 13, 2018|work=Stereogum|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref> With a penchant for short, [[hook]]-heavy songs, Juice Wrld seemed a leading figure for the current era of hip-hop. In 2018, the streaming platform [[Spotify]] named \"[[emo rap]]\" its fastest growing genre. Juice Wrld achieved arguably the most mainstream success of any artist in the sub-genre. This was boosted by his collaboration with [[Panic! At the Disco]] frontman [[Brendon Urie]].<ref name=\"Rindner\">{{cite web|author=Rindner, Grant|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2018/12/juice-wrld-freestyle-interview|title=Juice WRLD is Setting Himself Apart by Embracing Rap's Trends and Traditions|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]| publisher=Complex Media, LLC|date=December 11, 2018}}</ref> Juice Wrld himself considered the [[emo]] label to be both negative and positive. He felt that music sometimes has to be a bit dark to reflect his belief that the world is not really a light or a happy place.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/>\n\nHiggins said that \"Lucid Dreams\" was the only track from ''[[Goodbye & Good Riddance]]'' that he actually wrote, while the rest was done [[impromptu]]. Rather than write down his rhymes, Juice Wrld crafted whole songs in a few minutes by way of off-the-cuff rhyming.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> His songwriting process most of the time involved freestyling lyrics in lieu of writing them down. When he did write songs, it usually began with hearing a beat and instantaneously conceiving an idea.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/> Higgins sometimes found himself alone with an idea for a song and afraid that he wasn't going to remember it hours later when arriving at the studio. For this reason, he sometimes took a voice memo or simply just ended up writing the whole song if it was something he desired to dive deeper into.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\">{{cite web | author=Maduakolam, Emmanuel| title=Juice WRLD Talks &quot;Lucid Dreams&quot; and Emo Rap| url=https://hypebeast.com/2018/7/juice-wrld-interview-goodbye-and-good-riddance|work=Hypebeast|publisher=Hypebeast Limited| date=July 31, 2018| accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Lyrical themes===\nHiggins saw the value in his position as one of very few contemporary [[SoundCloud]] artists who could compose soul-bearing [[ballad]]s and [[ode]]s but remain comfortable [[freestyle rap]]ping over classic hip hop beats.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> Rather than eschewing it, his freestyles emphasize [[wordplay]] and feel indebted to the art form's tradition.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> He was asked for his opinion on why freestyles no longer are considered the [[rite of passage]] in [[hip hop culture]] as they once were. He replied, \"Stuff is just changing, that's all. We're moving into a new era of music. I feel like it's not necessarily a good thing to forget where shit started, but shit is changing.\"<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> Though his songs do not always feature very technical lyricism, intricate [[Flow (music)|flow]]s or tongue-twisting wordplay, Higgins managed to deliver inventive flows and memorable bars during his freestyles.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/>\n\nHiggins' most successful singles express melodic, [[emo]]-inspired compositions that exhibit his songwriting skill.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> His songs harbor melodic [[Flow (music)|flow]]s to complement their melancholic subject matter.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> Higgins claimed he talked about things others are thinking about but afraid to speak on, such as being vulnerable and hurt.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/> Having built a following through [[emo rap]], Higgins offered lyrics that touch on heartbreak and fragmented feelings.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/> Though not entirely groundbreaking, his musical approach provided a sense of familiarity that heartbroken adolescents of the current generation could gravitate towards.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/> Higgins maintained that he only wrote from personal experience, and found strength in his pain and vulnerability.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\" /> While the lyrical content of his songs often centered around heartache and bitterness, there are occasionally more boastful lines and creative references.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHiggins had a history of drug abuse and spoke openly about his experiences.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last1=Coscarelli |first1=Joe |last2=Garcia |first2=Sandra E. |title=Juice WRLD, Rising Rap Artist, Dies at 21 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/08/arts/music/juice-wrld-dead.html |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=December 8, 2019 }}</ref> He was living in Los Angeles with his girlfriend, Ally, at the time of his death.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes\" /> The two started dating in early 2019.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Death ==\nOn December 8, 2019, Higgins was aboard a private [[Gulfstream Aerospace|Gulfstream]] jet flying from [[Van Nuys Airport]] in Los Angeles to [[Midway International Airport]] in Chicago, where law enforcement officers were waiting for the jet to arrive, as they had been notified by federal agents while the flight was en route that the jet was suspected to be carrying guns and drugs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/ct-juice-wrld-guards-arrested-20191209-sfhqe3cns5hsffhxskrhqfagl4-story.html|title=Federal agents and Chicago police were confiscating drugs and guns from luggage when rapper Juice Wrld suffered seizure at Midway, officials say|last=Crepeau|first=Rosemary Sobol, Megan|website=Chicago Tribune|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Law enforcement later revealed they found three handguns and {{convert|70|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] on the aircraft.<ref name=\"TMZ\" /> They also stated several members of Higgins' management team aboard the flight attested that Higgins had taken \"several unknown pills\",<ref name=\"TMZ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/12/09/juice-wrld-private-jet-drugs-70-pounds-marijuana-arrests-feds/|title=Juice WRLD Allegedly Popped Pills on Private Jet, 70 lbs. Marijuana Seized|website=TMZ|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> including allegedly swallowing multiple [[Percocet]] pills in an attempt to hide them while police were on board the plane searching the luggage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/juice-wrld-allegedly-swallowed-percocets-hide-from-feds|title=Juice WRLD Allegedly Swallowed Percocets to Hide From Feds When Jet Landed|author=FNR Tigg|date=December 9, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]}}</ref> \n \nHiggins then began convulsing and seizing, after which two doses of the emergency medication [[Naloxone|Narcan]] were administered as an opioid overdose was suspected.<ref>{{cite news | last = Sobol | first = Rosemary | date = December 9, 2019 | title = Federal Agents and Chicago Police were Confiscating Drugs and Guns from Luggage when Rapper Juice Wrld Suffered Seizure at Midway, Officials Say | url = https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/ct-juice-wrld-guards-arrested-20191209-sfhqe3cns5hsffhxskrhqfagl4-story.html | work = Chicago Tribune}}</ref> Higgins was transported to the nearby Advocate Christ Medical Center in [[Oak Lawn, Illinois|Oak Lawn]], where he was pronounced dead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2019/12/juice-wrld-dead/|title=Juice Wrld Dead at 21 After Suffering Seizure|last=Coleman II|first=C. Vernon|date=December 8, 2019|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/juice-wrld-death-age-cause-seizure-lucid-dreams-a9238041.html|title=Juice Wrld death: Chicago-born rapper dies aged 21|last=White|first=Adam|date=December 8, 2019|work=Independent|access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHiggins' funeral was held on December 13, 2019, at the Holy Temple Cathedral Church of God in Christ in [[Harvey, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/12/13/juice-wrld-family-friends-gather-funeral-illinois/|title=Juice WRLD's Family, Friends Gather for Funeral in Illinois|website=TMZ|access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> Friends and family were in attendance, including collaborators [[Ski Mask the Slump God]] and [[Young Thug]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sohh.com/young-thug-cant-believe-juice-wrlds-gone-fk-this-st/|title=Young Thug Can't Believe Juice WRLD's Gone: \"F**k This S**t\"|last=Langhorne|first=Cyrus|date=December 13, 2019|website=sohh.com|access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2020, the Cook County Medical Examiner stated that Higgins died as a result of toxic levels of [[oxycodone]] and [[codeine]] present in his system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2020/01/22/juice-wrld-cause-of-death-overdose-oxycodone-codeine-percocet/|title=Juice WRLD Died from Accidental OD of Oxycodone and Codeine|website=TMZ|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n===Reaction===\n\nFellow artist [[Boosie Badazz]] suggested that the pilot of the plane was ultimately responsible for Higgins' death, referring to him as a [[Informant|snitch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revolt.tv/news/2019/12/18/21028628/boosie-badazz-snitching-pilot-juice-wrld |title=Boosie Badazz blames \u201csnitching\u201d pilot for Juice WRLD\u2019s death - REVOLT |publisher=Revolt.tv |date=2019-12-18 |accessdate=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ivey |first=Justin |url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.53879/title.boosie-badazz-blames-snitchin-ass-ho-pilot-for-juice-wrlds-death |title=Boosie Badazz Blames \"Snitchin' Ass Ho\" Pilot For Juice Wrld's Death |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2019-12-18 |accessdate=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=christina@theshaderoom.com |url=https://theshaderoom.com/lil-boosie-blames-juice-wrlds-death-on-pilot-alleges-he-was-the-one-who-snitched-to-the-feds/ |title=Lil Boosie Blames Juice Wrld\u00e2\u20ac\u2122s Death On Pilot, Alleges He Was The One Who Snitched To The Feds |publisher=The Shade Room |date= |accessdate=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=0/1000CLOSE |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/boosie-badazz-blames-pilot-for-juice-wrlds-death-f-ckin-snitch-news.98524.html |title=Boosie Badazz Blames Pilot For Juice WRLD's Death: \"F*ckin' Snitch\" |publisher=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=2019-12-18 |accessdate=2020-01-03}}</ref> Rapper [[Ski Mask the Slump God]], who collaborated with Higgins on the hit song [[Nuketown|\"Nuketown\"]], said on [[Twitter]] \"They keep taking my brothers from me\", referring also to longtime collaborator [[XXXTentacion]], who [[Murder of XXXTentacion|was shot and killed]] in June of 2018. [[Lil Yachty]], who remixed Higgins' song \"All Girls Are the Same\" mourned his death along with [[Lil Uzi Vert]], [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]], [[The Weeknd]] and others.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mahadevan |first1=Tara |title=Ski Mask the Slump God, Drake, Lil Uzi Vert, Lil Yachty, and More Mourn the Death of Juice WRLD |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/juice-wrld-death-reactions |website=Complex |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHiggins' mother Carmella Wallace expressed her hope that her son's legacy will help others in their battle with addictions saying, \"Addiction knows no boundaries, and its impact goes beyond the person fighting it. We hope the conversations he started in his music and his legacy will help others win their battles, as that is what he wanted more than anything. We know that Jarad\u2019s legacy of love, joy and emotional honesty will live on.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6451036/juice-wrld-cause-of-death-drug-overdose/ |title=Juice WRLD died of accidental drug overdose, medical examiner says \u2013 National |publisher=Globalnews.ca |date=2020-01-23 |accessdate=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\nThe coincidence between Higgins' young death and the lyrics of his song [[Legends (Juice Wrld song)|\"Legends\"]] \u2013 which was dedicated to [[XXXTentacion]], who was murdered in mid 2018, and [[Lil Peep]], who overdosed in late 2017 \u2013 was raised by many. In it, he raps \"What's the [[27 Club]]? / We ain't making it past 21\"; he died days after his 21st birthday.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mamo |first1=Heran |title=Here Are the Lyrics to Juice WRLD's 'Legends' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lyrics/8546749/juice-wrld-legends-lyrics |website=Billboard |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Juice Wrld discography}}\n*''[[Goodbye & Good Riddance]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Death Race for Love]]'' (2019)\n\n==Concert tours==\n* [[The Nicki Wrld Tour]]<ref name=\"Nicki\"/>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n===MTV Video Music Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| \"Lucid Dreams\"\n| Song of Summer\n| {{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/vma/vote/|title=Vote Now: MTV Video Music Awards 2018|publisher=MTV}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===BET Hip-Hop Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| |[[2018 BET Hip Hop Awards|2018]]|| Juice Wrld || Best New Hip Hop Artist || {{nominated}} || <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bet.com/shows/hip-hop-awards/2018/photos/nominees/hip-hop-awards-18-nominees.html|title=Hip Hop Awards 18 Nominees|work=BET.com|access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref> \n|}\n\n===Billboard Music Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| [[2019 Billboard Music Awards|2019]]\n| Juice Wrld\n| [[Billboard Music Award for Top New Artist|Top New Artist]]\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9N3oIhKPsBs |title=Juice WRLD Wins Top New Artist \u2013 BBMAs 2019 |date=May 1, 2019 |type=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8509655/billboard-music-awards-2019-winners-list |title=Billboard Music Awards Winners 2019: The Complete List |date=May 1, 2019 |website=Billboard}}</ref>\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{SoundCloud|uiceheidd|Juice WRLD}}\n* {{IMDb name|9954423|Juice WRLD}}\n* {{Instagram|juicewrld999}}\n{{Juice Wrld}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Juice Wrld}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Drug-related deaths in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Emo rap musicians]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Homewood, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Chicago]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American rapper, singer, and songwriter from Illinois}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Juice Wrld\n| image              = Juice Wrld Interview.png\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = A photograph of Juice Wrld talking into a microphone during an interview\n| caption            = Higgins during an interview in July 2018\n| birth_name         = Jarad Anthony Higgins\n| alias              = JuiceTheKidd\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1998|12|02}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2019|12|08|1998|12|02}}\n| death_place        = [[Oak Lawn, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Seizure]] induced by acute [[oxycodone]] and  [[codeine]] [[substance intoxication|intoxication]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter}}<!--Please do not add any more occupations to the list, it is long enough already-->\n| awards             = \n| website            = {{URL|juicewrld999.com/}}\n| signature          = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| instrument      = Vocals<!--If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first-->\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = <!--These music genres are all sourced under the section #Musical themes and genres-->{{hlist||[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Trap music|trap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/10/25/660628679/could-future-juice-wrld-be-traps-trojan-horse-advocates-for-drug-policy-reform|title=Could Future & Juice WRLD Be Trap's Trojan-Horse Advocates For Drug Policy Reform?|publisher=NPR|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>|[[emo rap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/juice-wrld-interview-lucid-dreams-2374917/amp|title=Juice WRLD: the emo rapper on his surprise hit 'Lucid Dreams'|website=NME|accessdate=March 15, 2019|date=September 18, 2018}}</ref>|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[SoundCloud rap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/.amp/features/2018-07-26-juice-wrld-on-soundcloud-rapper-title|title=Juice WRLD on SoundCloud Rapper Title: \"It's Just Not What People Think It Is\" \u2013 DJBooth|website=djbooth.net|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>|[[alternative R&B]]}}\n| years_active    = 2015\u20132019\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Lil Bibby|Grade A]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| associated_acts = <!--These associated acts are all sourced under #Discography-->{{flatlist|\n* [[Future (rapper)|Future]]\n* [[Lil Bibby]]\n* [[Nick Mira]]\n* [[Ski Mask the Slump God]]\n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Jarad Anthony Higgins''' (December 2, 1998 \u2013 December 8, 2019), known professionally as '''Juice Wrld''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d\u0292|u|s|_|\u02c8|w|\u025c|r|l|d}}; stylized as '''Juice WRLD'''), was an American rapper, singer, and songwriter, born in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. He is known mostly for his single \"[[Lucid Dreams (Juice Wrld song)|Lucid Dreams]]\", which has been played on the music streaming platform [[Spotify]] over one billion times. His posthumous feature on his idol, American rapper [[Eminem]]'s January 2020 single, \"[[Godzilla (Eminem song)|Godzilla]]\", has also contributed to the rapper's meteoric rise in popularity following his tragic death. \"Lucid Dreams\" and his other hit single \"[[All Girls Are the Same]]\" helped him gain a recording contract with [[Lil Bibby]]'s [[Lil Bibby|Grade A Productions]] and [[Interscope Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=311520&title=JUICE-WRLD-GOES-VIRAL-AT-SPOTIFY&redirect=mobile|title=HITS Daily Double : Rumor Mill \u2013 JUICE WRLD GOES VIRAL AT SPOTIFY|website=HITS Daily Double|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"All Girls Are the Same\" and \"Lucid Dreams\" acted as singles for Juice Wrld's debut studio album ''[[Goodbye & Good Riddance]]'', which was released in May 2018, which became certified [[Music recording certification|Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). The album enjoyed positive critical reception, and contained three other singles: \"[[Armed and Dangerous (song)|Armed and Dangerous]]\", \"[[Lean wit Me]]\" and \"[[Wasted (Juice Wrld song)|Wasted]]\", featuring [[Lil Uzi Vert]], all of which charted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. After collaborating with [[Future (rapper)|Future]] on the mixtape ''[[Wrld on Drugs]]'' (2018), Juice Wrld released his second studio album ''[[Death Race for Love]]'' in March 2019, which [[List of Billboard 200 number-one albums of 2019|went to number one]] on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].\n\n==Early life==\nJarad Higgins was born on December 2, 1998, in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].<ref name=\":2\" /> He moved to [[Homewood, Illinois]] in 1999 and attended [[Homewood-Flossmoor High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/Chicago-Area-Friends-Fans-Mourn-Accomplished-Artist-Juice-WRLD-565949501.html|title=Friends, Fans Mourn 'Accomplished' Chicago-Area Rapper Juice WRLD|publisher=[[NBC|NBC Chicago]]|date=December 8, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was three years old<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.gulf-times.com/story/601209/Juice-Wrld-s-music-is-confusing-but-popular|title=Juice Wrld's music is confusing but popular|date=July 30, 2018|work=Gulf Times|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> and his father left, leaving his mother to raise him as a [[single mother]] alongside one older brother.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X--KpcpzyzI|title=Juice Wrld Exposed!|author=No Jumper|date=March 7, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> Higgins' mother was very religious and conservative, and did not let him listen to [[hip hop]]. He was, however, allowed to listen to rock and pop music he found on video games such as ''[[Tony Hawk's Pro Skater]]'' and ''[[Guitar Hero]]'', which introduced him to artists such as [[Billy Idol]], [[Blink-182]], [[Black Sabbath]], [[Fall Out Boy]], [[Megadeth]], and [[Panic! at the Disco]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://radiomilwaukee.org/discover-music/music-news/juice-wrld-concert-review-impact-emo-rap/|title=Juice WRLD and the evolution of 'emo-rap'|work=88Nine Radio Milwaukee|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Citation|last=Durtty Daily|title=Juice Wrld Shares Some of His Biggest Influences in Music & His Name Before He Was Juice Wrld.|date=July 18, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J_Fl4hMIrso|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHiggins was a heavy [[Substance abuse|drug user]] during his childhood and teens. He began drinking [[Purple drank|lean]] in sixth grade and using [[Oxycodone/paracetamol|percocets]] and [[Alprazolam|xanax]] in 2013. Higgins also smoked cigarettes, quitting in his last year of high school due to health issues.<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|last=HOTSPOTATL|title=Juice Wrld Shares What His Favorite Class in Grade School Is|date=July 19, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gTH3AYUP9sE|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe first learned to play the piano at four years old, having been inspired by his mother, who later began paying for lessons, followed by guitar and drums. Higgins also played trumpet for band class.<ref name=\":1\" /> In his sophomore year of high school, he started posting songs to his [[SoundCloud]] which he recorded on his cell phone.<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/arts/music/juice-wrld-goodbye-good-riddance.html|title=The Chart-Topping Deep Feelings of Juice WRLD|last1=Caramanica|first1=Jon|date=July 25, 2018|work=The New York Times|accessdate=December 8, 2019}}</ref> Around this time, Higgins began to take rapping more seriously.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/06/juice-wrld-interview-exclusive|title=How 19-Year-Old Juice WRLD Scored a $3 Million Record Deal Without a Plan|website=Complex|accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Elevator\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elevatormag.com/juicewrld-interview/|title=An Interview with Juice Wrld|work=Elevator|last=Ware|first=Tajah|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nHiggins began to develop himself as an artist in his first year of high school. His first track, \"Forever\", was released on [[SoundCloud]] in 2015 under the name JuicetheKidd. Higgins recorded a majority of his first tracks on a cellphone, uploading them to SoundCloud in his sophomore year.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /> His name changed from JuicetheKidd, a name inspired by his affection for rapper [[Tupac Shakur]] and his part in the film ''[[Juice (film)|Juice]]'', to Juice Wrld because it \"represents taking over the world.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nHis first track produced by his main producer [[Nick Mira]], \"Too Much Cash\", was released in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/uiceheidd/too-much-cash|title=Too Much Cash (Prod. Nick Mira)|website=[[SoundCloud]]|accessdate=April 20, 2018}}</ref> While releasing projects and songs on SoundCloud, Higgins worked in a factory, but was fired within two weeks after finding himself dissatisfied with the job.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/interviews/2018/04/juice-wrld-interview|title=It's All Authentic: An Interview With Juice WRLD|work=Pigeons & Planes|last=Ison|first=Eric|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> After joining the internet collective Internet Money, Higgins released his debut full-length EP, ''9 9 9'', on June 15, 2017, with the song \"[[Lucid Dreams (Juice WRLD song)|Lucid Dreams]]\" breaking out and growing his following.<ref name=\"ChicagoReader\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2018/03/19/tracking-the-astronomical-rise-of-chicagoland-rapper-juice-wrld|title=Tracking the astronomical rise of Chicagoland rapper Juice Wrld|work=[[Chicago Reader]]|last=Galil|first=Leor|date=March 19, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Elevator\" />\n\nIn mid-2017, the artist began to receive attention from artists such as [[Waka Flocka Flame]] and [[Southside (record producer)|Southside]], as well as fellow Chicago artists [[G Herbo]] and [[Lil Bibby]]. He  subsequently signed with the latter's co-owned record label, Grade A Productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2018-07-26-juice-wrld-on-soundcloud-rapper-title|title=Juice WRLD on SoundCloud Rapper Title: \"It's Just Not What People Think It Is\"|first=Donna-Claire|last=Chesman|website=DJBooth|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132018: ''Goodbye & Good Riddance''===\nIn December 2017, Higgins released the three-song EP ''Nothings Different''. It was featured on numerous hip-hop blogs, such as Lyrical Lemonade,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lyricallemonade.com/nothings-different-juice-wrld/|title=Nothings Different \u2013 [Juice WRLD]|website=Lyrical Lemonade|last=Martinez|first=Elliot|date=February 5, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> which helped Higgins's track \"[[All Girls Are the Same]]\" gain popularity. In February 2018, a music video directed by [[Cole Bennett]] was released.<ref name=\"ChicagoReader\"/> Following the video's release, Higgins was signed to Interscope Records for $3,000,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8244598/juice-wrld-signs-interscope-3-million-joint-venture|title=Juice WRLD Signs With Interscope|work=Billboard|last=Stutz|first=Colin|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> and a remix featuring [[Lil Yachty]] was previewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/juice-wrld-previews-remix-lucid-dreams-lil-uzi-vert|title=Juice WRLD Previews a Remix of 'Lucid Dreams' With Lil Uzi Vert|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Margaritoff|first=Marco|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> \"All Girls Are the Same\" was critically praised, receiving a \"Best New Music\" designation from ''Pitchfork''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/juice-wrld-all-girls-are-the-same/|title=\"All Girls Are the Same\" by Juice WRLD Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Pearce|first=Sheldon|date=March 5, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> This song and \"Lucid Dreams\" were Higgins's first entries on a ''Billboard'' chart, debuting at number 92 and 74 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 respectively.<ref name=\"Hot100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-debuts-two-songs-on-billboard-hot-100-chart-news.50815.html|title=Juice WRLD Debuts Two Songs on Billboard Hot 100 Chart|work=HotNewHipHop|last=Parizot|first=Matthew|date=May 22, 2018|accessdate=May 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, \"Lucid Dreams\" was officially released as a single and given a video.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-returns-with-clip-for-lucid-dreams-new-video.43715.html|title=Juice WRLD Returns With Clip For 'Lucid Dreams'|work=HotNewHipHop|last=P.|first=Milca|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> It then went on to peak at number two on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"Lucid Dreams peak\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8463605/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny|title=Cardi B Becomes First Female Rapper With Two Billboard Hot 100 No. 1s, as 'I Like It', With Bad Bunny & J Balvin, Follows 'Bodak Yellow' to the Top|work=Billboard}}</ref> and quickly became one of the biggest streaming songs of 2018.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /> Higgins released his first studio album, ''[[Goodbye & Good Riddance]]'', on May 23, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2018/05/juice-wrld-goodbye-good-riddance|title=Juice WRLD's 'Goodbye & Good Riddance' Project Has Arrived|work=PigeonsandPlanes|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> On June 19, 2018, he released a two-song EP, ''Too Soon..'', in remembrance of and dedicated to deceased rappers [[Lil Peep]] and [[XXXTentacion]], the latter of whom was [[Murder of XXXTentacion|killed in a homicide case relating to robbery]] a day earlier. The song \"[[Legends (Juice Wrld song)|Legends]]\" from the EP charted under its debut at number 65.\n\nHiggins' first single featuring a collaboration was released on July 10, 2018, titled \"[[Wasted (Juice Wrld song)|Wasted]]\" featuring Lil Uzi Vert. The song was added to ''Goodbye & Good Riddance'' and debuted at number 67 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/07/juice-wrld-lil-uzi-vert-wasted-listen/|title=Juice WRLD \u2013 \"Wasted\" ft. Lil Uzi Vert: Listen|date=July 10, 2018|work=Spin|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> The next day, Higgins announced he was working on his next album.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8464961/juice-wrld-teases-more-projects-2018-tweets|title=Juice WRLD Hints at Releasing More Projects in 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> Following a series of leaks, Higgins' producer Danny Wolf released \"Motions\" on SoundCloud, giving the song an official release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.47803/title.juice-wrlds-motions-gets-soundcloud-release-after-leak#|title=Juice WRLD's \"Motions\" Gets SoundCloud Release After Leak|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> On July 20, 2018, Higgins announced his first tour, \"WRLD Domination\" with additional acts [[YBN Cordae]] and [[Lil Mosey]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-announces-wrld-domination-tour-dates-news.54241.html|title=Juice WRLD Announces 'WRLD Domination' Tour Dates|work=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u20132020: ''Wrld on Drugs'', ''Death Race for Love'' and death===\n[[File:Juice Wrld VMAs.png|thumb|left|Higgins at the [[2018 MTV Video Music Awards]] in August 2018]]\nHiggins was featured alongside [[Sheck Wes]] on [[Travis Scott]]'s song \"No Bystanders\", from Scott's third studio album, ''[[Astroworld (album)|Astroworld]]''. The song peaked at number 31 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/travis-scott-astroworld-tracklist-features-stream-drake-frank-ocean-the-weeknd-a8475551.html|title=Travis Scott releases ASTROWORLD: From Frank Ocean to The Weeknd, who features on his new album?|work=The Independent|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/08/03/everyone-features-travis-scotts-new-album-astroworld-7793625/|title=Everyone who features on Travis Scott's new album Astroworld|date=August 3, 2018|work=Metro|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/travis-scott/chart-history/hot-100|title=Travis Scott Chart History|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> He also made his late night television debut performing the song \"Lucid Dreams\" on [[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]] on August 8, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8469296/juice-wrld-lucid-dreams-performance-jimmy-kimmel-video|title=Juice WRLD Makes Late Night Television Debut With Starry 'Lucid Dreams' Performance On 'Kimmel': Watch|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> On October 15, 2018, the music video for the song \"[[Armed and Dangerous (song)|Armed and Dangerous]]\" was released<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/juice-wrld-armed-and-dangerous/|title=Juice WRLD's \"Armed & Dangerous\": Listen to It Here|date=October 17, 2018|work=Highsnobiety|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> and the lead single for the collaborative mixtape, ''[[Wrld on Drugs]]'' with [[Future (rapper)|Future]] was also released, called \"[[Fine China (Future and Juice Wrld song)|Fine China]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/10/future-and-juice-wrld-link-up-fine-china|title=Future and Juice WRLD Link Up for 'Fine China'|website=Complex|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> The mixtape was released on October 19, 2018, via [[Epic Records]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/future-and-juice-wrld-share-album-cover-and-release-date-for-wrld-on-drugs-news.62472.html |title=Future & Juice WRLD Share Album Cover & Release Date For \"WRLD on Drugs\" |website=HotNewHipHop |accessdate=October 18, 2018}}</ref> He also contributed to the [[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] for ''[[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse]]'' in December 2018, with a song from the soundtrack, titled \"Hide\", featuring American singer Seezyn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/spider-man-soundtrack-tracklisting/|title=Nicki Minaj, Lil Wayne And Others Appear On Spider-Man Soundtrack|last=Stavropoulos|first=Laura|date=December 10, 2018|website=uDiscover Music|publisher=[[Universal Music Group]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, [[Ski Mask the Slump God]] confirmed that he and Higgins would release a joint mixtape called ''Evil Twins'' in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/12/ski-mask-slump-god-juice-wrld-evil-twins-project/|title=SKI MASK THE SLUMP GOD AND JUICE WRLD'S 'EVIL TWINS' PROJECT TO ARRIVE IN 2019|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]}}</ref> The pair also announced a 2019 tour featuring 30 concerts across North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/juice-wrld-north-american-tour-796938/|title=Juice WRLD Lines Up North American Tour|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=February 21, 2019}}</ref> Higgins' second studio album, ''[[Death Race for Love]]'', was released on March 8, 2019.<ref name=\"deathrace\">{{cite web |last1=Bloom |first1=Madison |title=Juice WRLD Announces New Album A Deathrace for Love |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/juice-wrld-announces-new-album-a-deathrace-for-love/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=February 8, 2019|date=February 8, 2019}}</ref> The album topped the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart. He then embarked on [[The Nicki Wrld Tour]], alongside Trinidadian-American rapper [[Nicki Minaj]].<ref name=\"Nicki\">{{cite web |last1=Renshaw |first1=David |title=Nicki Minaj confirms Juice WRLD will replace Future on her European tour |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/12/21/nicki-minaj-future-juice-wrld-european-tour |website=The fader |publisher=Andy Cohn |accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref> Higgins released the music video for the song \"Fast\" from the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/04/juice-wrld-fast-video|title=Juice WRLD Releases New Video for \"Fast\"|website=Complex|accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref> Later that year, he released other singles: \"[[All Night (BTS and Juice Wrld song)|All Night]]\", with [[RM (rapper)|RM]] and [[Suga (rapper)|Suga]] of [[BTS (band)|BTS]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bts/8516964/bts-juice-wrld-all-night|title=BTS' RM and Suga Team Up With Juice WRLD For 'All Night': Listen|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=June 21, 2019|website=Billboard|url-status=live|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> \"[[Hate Me (Ellie Goulding and Juice Wrld song)|Hate Me]]\", with [[Ellie Goulding]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.much.com/ellie-goulding-juice-wrld-hate-me/|title=Ellie Goulding And Juice WRLD Get Angry On 'Hate Me'|date=June 27, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|publisher=Much|last=Gao|first=Stephanie}}</ref> \"Run\";<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8518901/juice-wrld-run|title=Juice Wrld Drops Melancholic New Track 'Run': Listen|date=July 8, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Saponara|first=Michael}}</ref> \"[[Graduation (Benny Blanco and Juice Wrld song)|Graduation]]\", with [[Benny Blanco]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-and-benny-blanco-serenade-high-school-crushes-on-graduation-new-song.1984327.html|title=Juice WRLD & Benny Blanco Serenade High School Crushes On \"Graduation\"|date=August 29, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|publisher=HotNewHipHop|last=Findlay|first=Mitch}}</ref> and \"[[Bandit (song)|Bandit]]\" with [[YoungBoy Never Broke Again|NBA YoungBoy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/10/03/listen-to-juice-wrld-nba-youngboy-new-track-bandit-2019|title=Listen to Juice WRLD and NBA YoungBoy's new track \"Bandit\"|website=[[The Fader]]|last=D'Souza|first=Shaad|date=October 3, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/videos/Juice-wrld-nba-youngboys-bandit-explained|title=Juice WRLD Reunites With Cole Bennett On Video For YoungBoy Never Broke Again-Assisted \"Bandit\"|date=October 5, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|publisher=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]}}</ref> \n\nOn December 8, 2019, Higgins collapsed and died from a suspected drug-induced [[seizure]] at [[Midway International Airport]] in Chicago, after landing at Midway on a [[private jet]] from [[Van Nuys Airport]] in [[Los Angeles]]. His death provoked an outpouring of grief across social media and the music industry. Higgins' [[funeral]] was held in [[Harvey, Illinois]] on five days later, on December 13, 2019. \n\nHiggins' first posthumous appearance was on [[Eminem]]'s surprise eleventh studio album, ''[[Music to Be Murdered By]],'' on the track, \"[[Godzilla (Eminem song)|Godzilla]]\", released in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/music/eminem-drops-surprise-album-featuring-ed-sheeran-and-late-rapper-juice-wrld/|title=Eminem Drops Surprise Album Featuring Ed Sheeran and Late Rapper Juice WRLD|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/01/eminem-music-to-be-murdered-by-stream|title=Stream Eminem's Surprise Album 'Music to Be Murdered By' f/ Juice WRLD, Ed Sheeran, Royce da 5'9\", and More|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Musical style===\n\nHiggins stated his musical influences as being genre-wide going from rock music to rap music. Higgins stated that his biggest influences were rappers [[Travis Scott]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-says-travis-scott-is-his-biggest-inspiration-wants-to-collaborate-news.53595.html|title=Juice WRLD Says Travis Scott Is His Biggest Inspiration, Wants To Collaborate|work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref> [[Chief Keef]],<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Kanye West]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/04/juice-wrld-interview|title=It's All Authentic: An Interview With Juice WRLD|website=Complex|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.themodernlifemag.com/music/2018/3/7/juice-wrld-talks-about-his-influences-being-inspired-by-rock-and-more-on-no-jumper-exposed|title=JUICE WRLD talks about his influences, being inspired by rock, and more on No Jumper \"Exposed\"|magazine=Modern Life Mag|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref> and British rock singer [[Billy Idol]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Why Does Juice WLRD Want To Collab With Billy Idol? {{!}} Exclusive Interview|work=iHeartRadio|date=July 30, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W53VFda4mlA|accessdate=August 20, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nardwuar vs. Juice WRLD|work=NardwuarServiette|date=June 11, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kN7NfAj5pKY|accessdate=August 20, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> Juice Wlrd was among the ranks of openly vulnerable artists born from the [[emo rap]] scene inspired by West's influential fourth album, ''[[808s & Heartbreak]]'' (2008).<ref name=\"Saponara\"/> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' writer Michael Saponara claimed, \"If West and his sparse ''[[808s and Heartbreak|808s]]'' were a tree, it would have grown another branch with the blossoming art displayed by fellow Chicago native Juice WRLD in 2018.\"<ref name=\"Saponara\"/> During an interview with All Def Music, Juice Wrld imparted, \"I was singing '[[Street Lights (Kanye West song)|Street Lights]]' like I had shit to be sad about. Kanye is a time traveler. That n---a went to damn near 2015 and came back with some sauce.\"<ref name=\"Saponara\">{{cite web|author=Saponara, Michael|title=Kanye West's 808s & Heartbreak Turns 10: Engineer Anthony Kilhoffer Revisits the Influential Album|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8485555/kanye-west-808-and-heartbreak-10-year-anniversary|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=November 24, 2018|accessdate=November 26, 2018}}</ref> His other influences included [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Fall Out Boy]], [[Black Sabbath]], [[Megadeth]], [[2Pac]], [[Eminem]], [[Kid Cudi]] and [[Escape the Fate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/juice-wrld-reveals-the-origin-of-his-name-and-his-major-influences-news.50999.html|title=Juice WRLD Reveals The Origin of His Name & His Major Influences|work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Juice WRLD Breaks Down Tupac & Eminem's Influence on His Music|date=July 23, 2018|work=TRL|publisher=MTV|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fsaolirWIKQ|access-date=August 20, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Juice WRLD lists his Top 5 favorite artist {{!}} Interview|website=Genius|date=September 10, 2019|url=https://genius.com/a/juice-wrld-lists-his-top-5-favorite-artists|access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> \n{{Listen|pos = right\n|filename=Lucid Dreams.ogg\n|title=\"Lucid Dreams\"\n|description=\"Lucid Dreams\" is a piercing [[Melody|melodic]] rap song.<ref name=\"Williams\">{{cite web |author=Williams, Aaron |url=https://uproxx.com/hiphop/juice-wrld-lean-wit-me-video/|title=Juice Wrld Delivers A Harrowing Statement On Substance Abuse In His 'Lean Wit Me' Video|work=[[Uproxx]] |publisher=[[Uproxx Media Group|Uproxx Media Group, Inc]] | date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018}}</ref> It features emotionally vulnerable lyrics imbued with teenage angst. The song contains a sample of \"[[Shape of My Heart (Sting song)|Shape of My Heart]]\" by [[Sting (musician)|Sting]].<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |last1=Caramanica |first1=Jon |title=The Chart-Topping Deep Feelings of Juice WRLD |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/arts/music/juice-wrld-goodbye-good-riddance.html |accessdate=January 9, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102040036/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/arts/music/juice-wrld-goodbye-good-riddance.html |archivedate=January 2, 2019 |date=July 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|format=[[Ogg]]\n|filename2=Lean Wit Me.ogg\n|title2=\"Lean Wit Me\"\n|description2=\"Lean Wit Me\" harbors dark lyrical themes.<ref name=\"Williams\" /> It bears a strong fixation on addiction as well as contemplations of mortality. The song's lyrics are laced with references to narcotics and [[binge drinking|binging]]. They serve to impart on the consequences of [[substance abuse]] and overindulgence.<ref name=\"Burks\">{{cite web|author=Burks, Tosten |title=Juice Wrld Attends Group Therapy in New 'Lean Wit Me' Video|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/video/2018/08/juice-wrld-lean-wit-me-video/|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|publisher=[[Harris Publications|Harris Publications Inc.]]|date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018}}</ref> Juice Wrld's melodic vocal style veers on melancholic [[Crooner|crooning]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Lamarre, Carl|title=Juice WRLD Shrugs Off Michael Jackson Comparison, Calls Working With Future 'A Blessing': Exclusive|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8482112/juice-wrld-future-wrld-on-drugs-michael-jackson-interview|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 29, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|format2=[[Ogg]]\n | type = music\n}}\n\nHiggins' music has been branded as \"emo\" and \"rock\" leaning, \"genre-bending\"<ref name=\"auto1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> with music focusing on \"every broken heart, every wounded feeling.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2001216/juice-wrld-toxic-masculinity/franchises/status-aint-hood/|title=Juice WRLD And SoundCloud Rap's Toxic Masculinity|date=June 13, 2018|work=Stereogum|access-date=August 20, 2018}}</ref> With a penchant for short, [[hook]]-heavy songs, Juice Wrld seemed a leading figure for the current era of hip-hop. In 2018, the streaming platform [[Spotify]] named \"[[emo rap]]\" its fastest growing genre. Juice Wrld achieved arguably the most mainstream success of any artist in the sub-genre. This was boosted by his collaboration with [[Panic! At the Disco]] frontman [[Brendon Urie]].<ref name=\"Rindner\">{{cite web|author=Rindner, Grant|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2018/12/juice-wrld-freestyle-interview|title=Juice WRLD is Setting Himself Apart by Embracing Rap's Trends and Traditions|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]| publisher=Complex Media, LLC|date=December 11, 2018}}</ref> Juice Wrld himself considered the [[emo]] label to be both negative and positive. He felt that music sometimes has to be a bit dark to reflect his belief that the world is not really a light or a happy place.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/>\n\nHiggins said that \"Lucid Dreams\" was the only track from ''[[Goodbye & Good Riddance]]'' that he actually wrote, while the rest was done [[impromptu]]. Rather than write down his rhymes, Juice Wrld crafted whole songs in a few minutes by way of off-the-cuff rhyming.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> His songwriting process most of the time involved freestyling lyrics in lieu of writing them down. When he did write songs, it usually began with hearing a beat and instantaneously conceiving an idea.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/> Higgins sometimes found himself alone with an idea for a song and afraid that he wasn't going to remember it hours later when arriving at the studio. For this reason, he sometimes took a voice memo or simply just ended up writing the whole song if it was something he desired to dive deeper into.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\">{{cite web | author=Maduakolam, Emmanuel| title=Juice WRLD Talks &quot;Lucid Dreams&quot; and Emo Rap| url=https://hypebeast.com/2018/7/juice-wrld-interview-goodbye-and-good-riddance|work=Hypebeast|publisher=Hypebeast Limited| date=July 31, 2018| accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Lyrical themes===\nHiggins saw the value in his position as one of very few contemporary [[SoundCloud]] artists who could compose soul-bearing [[ballad]]s and [[ode]]s but remain comfortable [[freestyle rap]]ping over classic hip hop beats.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> Rather than eschewing it, his freestyles emphasize [[wordplay]] and feel indebted to the art form's tradition.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> He was asked for his opinion on why freestyles no longer are considered the [[rite of passage]] in [[hip hop culture]] as they once were. He replied, \"Stuff is just changing, that's all. We're moving into a new era of music. I feel like it's not necessarily a good thing to forget where shit started, but shit is changing.\"<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> Though his songs do not always feature very technical lyricism, intricate [[Flow (music)|flow]]s or tongue-twisting wordplay, Higgins managed to deliver inventive flows and memorable bars during his freestyles.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/>\n\nHiggins' most successful singles express melodic, [[emo]]-inspired compositions that exhibit his songwriting skill.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> His songs harbor melodic [[Flow (music)|flow]]s to complement their melancholic subject matter.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/> Higgins claimed he talked about things others are thinking about but afraid to speak on, such as being vulnerable and hurt.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/> Having built a following through [[emo rap]], Higgins offered lyrics that touch on heartbreak and fragmented feelings.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/> Though not entirely groundbreaking, his musical approach provided a sense of familiarity that heartbroken adolescents of the current generation could gravitate towards.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\"/> Higgins maintained that he only wrote from personal experience, and found strength in his pain and vulnerability.<ref name=\"Maduakolam\" /> While the lyrical content of his songs often centered around heartache and bitterness, there are occasionally more boastful lines and creative references.<ref name=\"Rindner\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHiggins had a history of drug abuse and spoke openly about his experiences.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last1=Coscarelli |first1=Joe |last2=Garcia |first2=Sandra E. |title=Juice WRLD, Rising Rap Artist, Dies at 21 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/08/arts/music/juice-wrld-dead.html |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=December 8, 2019 }}</ref> He was living in Los Angeles with his girlfriend, Ally, at the time of his death.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes\" /> The two started dating in early 2019.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Death ==\nOn December 8, 2019, Higgins was aboard a private [[Gulfstream Aerospace|Gulfstream]] jet flying from [[Van Nuys Airport]] in Los Angeles to [[Midway International Airport]] in Chicago, where law enforcement officers were waiting for the jet to arrive, as they had been notified by federal agents while the flight was en route that the jet was suspected to be carrying guns and drugs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/ct-juice-wrld-guards-arrested-20191209-sfhqe3cns5hsffhxskrhqfagl4-story.html|title=Federal agents and Chicago police were confiscating drugs and guns from luggage when rapper Juice Wrld suffered seizure at Midway, officials say|last=Crepeau|first=Rosemary Sobol, Megan|website=Chicago Tribune|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Law enforcement later revealed they found three handguns and {{convert|70|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] on the aircraft.<ref name=\"TMZ\" /> They also stated several members of Higgins' management team aboard the flight attested that Higgins had taken \"several unknown pills\",<ref name=\"TMZ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/12/09/juice-wrld-private-jet-drugs-70-pounds-marijuana-arrests-feds/|title=Juice WRLD Allegedly Popped Pills on Private Jet, 70 lbs. Marijuana Seized|website=TMZ|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> including allegedly swallowing multiple [[Percocet]] pills in an attempt to hide them while police were on board the plane searching the luggage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/juice-wrld-allegedly-swallowed-percocets-hide-from-feds|title=Juice WRLD Allegedly Swallowed Percocets to Hide From Feds When Jet Landed|author=FNR Tigg|date=December 9, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]}}</ref> \n \nHiggins then began convulsing and seizing, after which two doses of the emergency medication [[Naloxone|Narcan]] were administered as an opioid overdose was suspected.<ref>{{cite news | last = Sobol | first = Rosemary | date = December 9, 2019 | title = Federal Agents and Chicago Police were Confiscating Drugs and Guns from Luggage when Rapper Juice Wrld Suffered Seizure at Midway, Officials Say | url = https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/ct-juice-wrld-guards-arrested-20191209-sfhqe3cns5hsffhxskrhqfagl4-story.html | work = Chicago Tribune}}</ref> Higgins was transported to the nearby Advocate Christ Medical Center in [[Oak Lawn, Illinois|Oak Lawn]], where he was pronounced dead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2019/12/juice-wrld-dead/|title=Juice Wrld Dead at 21 After Suffering Seizure|last=Coleman II|first=C. Vernon|date=December 8, 2019|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/juice-wrld-death-age-cause-seizure-lucid-dreams-a9238041.html|title=Juice Wrld death: Chicago-born rapper dies aged 21|last=White|first=Adam|date=December 8, 2019|work=Independent|access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHiggins' funeral was held on December 13, 2019, at the Holy Temple Cathedral Church of God in Christ in [[Harvey, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/12/13/juice-wrld-family-friends-gather-funeral-illinois/|title=Juice WRLD's Family, Friends Gather for Funeral in Illinois|website=TMZ|access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> Friends and family were in attendance, including collaborators [[Ski Mask the Slump God]] and [[Young Thug]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sohh.com/young-thug-cant-believe-juice-wrlds-gone-fk-this-st/|title=Young Thug Can't Believe Juice WRLD's Gone: \"F**k This S**t\"|last=Langhorne|first=Cyrus|date=December 13, 2019|website=sohh.com|access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2020, the Cook County Medical Examiner stated that Higgins died as a result of toxic levels of [[oxycodone]] and [[codeine]] present in his system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2020/01/22/juice-wrld-cause-of-death-overdose-oxycodone-codeine-percocet/|title=Juice WRLD Died from Accidental OD of Oxycodone and Codeine|website=TMZ|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n===Reaction===\n\nFellow artist [[Boosie Badazz]] suggested that the pilot of the plane was ultimately responsible for Higgins' death, referring to him as a [[Informant|snitch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revolt.tv/news/2019/12/18/21028628/boosie-badazz-snitching-pilot-juice-wrld |title=Boosie Badazz blames \u201csnitching\u201d pilot for Juice WRLD\u2019s death - REVOLT |publisher=Revolt.tv |date=2019-12-18 |accessdate=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ivey |first=Justin |url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.53879/title.boosie-badazz-blames-snitchin-ass-ho-pilot-for-juice-wrlds-death |title=Boosie Badazz Blames \"Snitchin' Ass Ho\" Pilot For Juice Wrld's Death |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2019-12-18 |accessdate=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=christina@theshaderoom.com |url=https://theshaderoom.com/lil-boosie-blames-juice-wrlds-death-on-pilot-alleges-he-was-the-one-who-snitched-to-the-feds/ |title=Lil Boosie Blames Juice Wrld\u00e2\u20ac\u2122s Death On Pilot, Alleges He Was The One Who Snitched To The Feds |publisher=The Shade Room |date= |accessdate=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=0/1000CLOSE |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/boosie-badazz-blames-pilot-for-juice-wrlds-death-f-ckin-snitch-news.98524.html |title=Boosie Badazz Blames Pilot For Juice WRLD's Death: \"F*ckin' Snitch\" |publisher=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=2019-12-18 |accessdate=2020-01-03}}</ref> Rapper [[Ski Mask the Slump God]], who collaborated with Higgins on the hit song [[Nuketown|\"Nuketown\"]], said on [[Twitter]] \"They keep taking my brothers from me\", referring also to longtime collaborator [[XXXTentacion]], who [[Murder of XXXTentacion|was shot and killed]] in June of 2018. [[Lil Yachty]], who remixed Higgins' song \"All Girls Are the Same\" mourned his death along with [[Lil Uzi Vert]], [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]], [[The Weeknd]] and others.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mahadevan |first1=Tara |title=Ski Mask the Slump God, Drake, Lil Uzi Vert, Lil Yachty, and More Mourn the Death of Juice WRLD |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/juice-wrld-death-reactions |website=Complex |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHiggins' mother Carmella Wallace expressed her hope that her son's legacy will help others in their battle with addictions saying, \"Addiction knows no boundaries, and its impact goes beyond the person fighting it. We hope the conversations he started in his music and his legacy will help others win their battles, as that is what he wanted more than anything. We know that Jarad\u2019s legacy of love, joy and emotional honesty will live on.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6451036/juice-wrld-cause-of-death-drug-overdose/ |title=Juice WRLD died of accidental drug overdose, medical examiner says \u2013 National |publisher=Globalnews.ca |date=2020-01-23 |accessdate=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\nThe coincidence between Higgins' young death and the lyrics of his song [[Legends (Juice Wrld song)|\"Legends\"]] \u2013 which was dedicated to [[XXXTentacion]], who was murdered in mid 2018, and [[Lil Peep]], who overdosed in late 2017 \u2013 was raised by many. In it, he raps \"What's the [[27 Club]]? / We ain't making it past 21\"; he died days after his 21st birthday.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mamo |first1=Heran |title=Here Are the Lyrics to Juice WRLD's 'Legends' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lyrics/8546749/juice-wrld-legends-lyrics |website=Billboard |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Juice Wrld discography}}\n*''[[Goodbye & Good Riddance]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Death Race for Love]]'' (2019)\n\n==Concert tours==\n* [[The Nicki Wrld Tour]]<ref name=\"Nicki\"/>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n===MTV Video Music Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| \"Lucid Dreams\"\n| Song of Summer\n| {{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/vma/vote/|title=Vote Now: MTV Video Music Awards 2018|publisher=MTV}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===BET Hip-Hop Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| |[[2018 BET Hip Hop Awards|2018]]|| Juice Wrld || Best New Hip Hop Artist || {{nominated}} || <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bet.com/shows/hip-hop-awards/2018/photos/nominees/hip-hop-awards-18-nominees.html|title=Hip Hop Awards 18 Nominees|work=BET.com|access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref> \n|}\n\n===Billboard Music Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| [[2019 Billboard Music Awards|2019]]\n| Juice Wrld\n| [[Billboard Music Award for Top New Artist|Top New Artist]]\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9N3oIhKPsBs |title=Juice WRLD Wins Top New Artist \u2013 BBMAs 2019 |date=May 1, 2019 |type=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8509655/billboard-music-awards-2019-winners-list |title=Billboard Music Awards Winners 2019: The Complete List |date=May 1, 2019 |website=Billboard}}</ref>\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{SoundCloud|uiceheidd|Juice WRLD}}\n* {{IMDb name|9954423|Juice WRLD}}\n* {{Instagram|juicewrld999}}\n{{Juice Wrld}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Juice Wrld}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Drug-related deaths in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Emo rap musicians]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Homewood, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Chicago]]\n", "name_user": "Lukas4h", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding associated acts. Juice WRLD has collaborated with both Trippie Redd and YNW Melly on more than one song.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juice_Wrld"}
{"title_page": "George Edward Smith", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= George Edward Smith\n|birth_date= 1948\n|death_date= \n|birth_place= \n|death_place= \n|image= \n|caption= SSgt. George E. \"Smitty\" Smith\n|nickname= \"Smitty\"\n|allegiance= [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch= [[United States Army Special Forces]]\n|serviceyears= 19__ - 1966 \n|rank= [[File:Army-USA-OR-06.svg|20px]] [[Staff Sergeant#United States|Staff Sergeant]]\n|commands=\n|unit= Detachment A-21, Company B, 5th Special Forces Group\n|battles=\n|awards=   \n|laterwork= Author - [[P.O.W.:Two Years with the Vietcong]] \n}}\n\n'''George Edward \"Smitty\" Smith''' (born 1938) is a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] veteran of the [[Vietnam War]], former prisoner of war, and author.\n\nCaptured with other members of his squad on November 24, 1963, he was released two years later in Cambodia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pownetwork.org/bios/s/s169.htm|title=Bio, Smith, George E. \"Smitty\"|website=www.pownetwork.org}}</ref>\nHe later wrote about his experiences in a book titled ''[[P.O.W.:Two Years with the Vietcong]]'', published by Ramparts Press in 1971.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.librarything.com/tag/Viet%20Cong|title=Books tagged Viet Cong|website=www.librarything.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, George Edward}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Vietnam War prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n\n\n{{US-writer-stub}}\n{{US-army-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= George Edward Smith\n|birth_date= 1948\n|death_date= \n|birth_place= \n|death_place= \n|image= \n|caption= SSgt. George E. \"Smitty\" Smith\n|nickname= \"Smitty\"\n|allegiance= [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch= [[United States Army Special Forces]]\n|serviceyears= 19__ - 1966 \n|rank= [[File:Army-USA-OR-06.svg|20px]] [[Staff Sergeant#United States|Staff Sergeant]]\n|commands=\n|unit= Detachment A-21, Company B, 5th Special Forces Group\n|battles=\n|awards=   \n|laterwork= Author - [[P.O.W.:Two Years with the Vietcong]] \n}}\n\n'''George Edward \"Smitty\" Smith''' (born 1938) is a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] veteran of the [[Vietnam War]], former prisoner of war, and author.  \n\nCaptured with other members of his squad on November 24, 1963, he was released two years later in Cambodia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pownetwork.org/bios/s/s169.htm|title=Bio, Smith, George E. \"Smitty\"|website=www.pownetwork.org}}</ref>\nHe later wrote about his experiences in a book titled ''[[P.O.W.:Two Years with the Vietcong]]'', published by Ramparts Press in 1971.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.librarything.com/tag/Viet%20Cong|title=Books tagged Viet Cong|website=www.librarything.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, George Edward}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Vietnam War prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n\n\n{{US-writer-stub}}\n{{US-army-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Edward_Smith"}
{"title_page": "Sood", "text_new": "{{about|the surname|the village in India|Sood, Arunachal Pradesh}}\n\n{{wiktionary|Sood}}\n\n'''Sood''' or '''Sud''' is a Rajput community (Descendents of Sodha Rajputs) mainly centered in the plains of [[Sirhind]] and [[Punjab]] and hills of [[Kangra, Himachal Pradesh|Kangra]], [[Kashmir]], and [[Himachal Pradesh]].<ref>Mondays on the Dark Night of the Moon: Himalayan Foothill Folktales (Exeter Studies in History), Kirin Narayan, Oxford University Press, June 19, 1997)</ref><ref>Origin and History of Soods, 1975, Madan Mohan Sood, Sood Sabha Chandigarh)</ref><ref>[https://m.divyahimachal.com/article/14-%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B-%E0%A4%A7%E0%A5%82%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%A7%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AE-%E0%A4%B8%E0%A5%87-%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE-%E0%A4%9C%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%8F%E0%A4%97%E0%A4%BE/1813828 14 \u0915\u094b \u0927\u0942\u092e\u0927\u093e\u092e \u0938\u0947 \u092e\u0928\u093e\u092f\u093e \u091c\u093e\u090f\u0917\u093e \u2018\u0938\u0942\u0926 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0928 \u092e\u0947\u0932\u093e\u2019, October 4, 2018]</ref> \n\n==Origin and History==\nThe word '''\"Sood\"''' or '''\"Sud\"''' is of Sanskrit origin and according to Amar Kosh (an authoritative Hindi Dictionary) it means a \"''courageous and a brave person or a victor of his enemies''\". The word ''''Sood'''' finds a mention in the Vedas at 23 places (15 places in the Rig Ved, 6 places in the Yajur Ved and twice in the Atharva Ved). Interestingly, Lord Krishna is also known as 'Madhusudan' \u2013 (Sudan means 'sanharak' \u2013 killer of demon Madhu). The Sood community is a very ancient fraternity and some Sood/Sud gotras are merchants as well. \n\nIn the 3rd century BCE, the Brahmin Rishis were perturbed by the spread of Buddhism across India, because the old Vedic Hindu Dharma was getting a great set back. Hence, the Rishis performed a sacred Yajna at Mount Abu to revive old Hindu Dharma based on the Vedic traditions. The sacred flames of this Agni Kund, incarnated and baptised four Kshatriyas namely \u2013 the Parmar, the Parihar, the Solanki and the Chouhan. These four took a holy vow to re-establish the ancient glory of Hindu Dharma by fighting against the mass change of faith from Hinduism to Buddhism. These four Kshatriyas spread four new branches of Hinduism all over the country. The second son born to Parmar was named Sood and his descendents formed the Sood community. A reference of 44 descendants of Parmar is also available. These sood descendents formed the Sood Dynasty and the capital city of the Sood Dynasty for eight generations was Patten in Sind, now in Pakistan. The capital was later shifted to Alwar and finally King Jai Singh, (son of King Dahar) shifted his capital to Amar Kot, now in Pakistan. There is a reference of 101 Sood Kings or Rajas ruling in different parts of India. The Soods established themselves in the North and later got concentrated at Soodpur, now renamed Sirhind.  \n\nDue to the seven invasions of India by Ahmed Shah Abdali between 1748 and 1757 A.D., at Soodpur and gradually into Rajasthan and later of entire India, the Soods fled to different villages and towns in Punjab and Himachal Pradesh.<ref name=\"originHistory\">{{cite book|title=Origin And History Of Soods (A community in India)|first1=Yaman|last1=Sood|year=1975|publisher=Sood Sabha Chandigarh|url=http://soodsabhachandigarh.org/history.html#2|accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Gotras or Sub Castes==\nBoth the Punjab section and the Hill section of the Sood community have 52 Gotras or Sub Castes each, many of which are named after the villages they settled in. <ref name=\"Gotras or Sub Castes\">{{cite book|title=Origin And History Of Soods (A community in India)|first1=Yaman|last1=Sood|year=1975|publisher=Sood Sabha Chandigarh|url=http://soodsabhachandigarh.org/history.html#8|accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nThe Punjab section Gotras or Sub Castes are : Badhoo, Balgan, Baranwal, Behal, Beri, Bharak, Bhokaha (or Bhokhi), Bhola, Bodhi, Bourie, Brahmi, Dadan, Dauli (or Deli), Dhalli (or Dhati), Dhanda, Dhaunchak, Dhiri, Dhookhi, Dhoop, Dosaj, Gajri, Gajja (or Gajjey), Gondal (Gandel), Gopal, Goyal, Jandpal (or Janpal), Jari, Kajla (or Kajley), Lau, Mahidhar, Mahiyar (or Mayor), Makaura (or Makaurey), Mandal, Mohindra, Mohni, Mukandi, Momman, Nandoo, Nehra, Paal, Phakka, Pharwaha, Phassi, Poora, Rora, Rohnir, Rodher, Sanwal, Sulhan, Tagaley, Teji, Udhar, Ugal-Virk or Virk and Vassan.\n\nThe Hill section Gotras or Sub Castes are : Bahil, Bajwaria, Banta, Bhagley, Bhagra, Basohal, Basalia, Butail, Chakahria, Chakaseday, Chamib, Chaudhri, Chaukand, Chaujar, Chehray, Chimia, Cheemrey, Chhabb, Chonolia, Dagan, Didi, Dhophmal, Doddal, Dogan, Dorela, Dunyal, Indoria, Harail, Haraloo, Indoria, Jallundhroo, Jaiswal, Jandranglu, Jhalya, Jhangra, Jehelghat, Kalandar, Kandal, Karol, Kataway, Kaunsal, Kutharia, Kuthiala, Lahespar, Lakhanty, Lamsay, Lama, Langey, Lasaria, Laserday, Lauriya, Ling, Mahdoodia, Mangwalich, Mariya, Mand, Masoob, Mehtay, Mithoo, Naggal, Nehdal, Pabba, Panbalia, Paptopay, Patopa, Pulkaha, Phagdey, Phalkolia, Sabloria, Sah, Saraup, Sawali, Shall, Takalo and Udhwal.\n\nThe Soods are organized into city specific chapters of their organization in many countries. These are called the Sood Sabhas and these elect their leaders.<ref>[https://www.bhaskar.com/himachal/shimla/news/latest-shimla-news-020502-1814699.html  \u0938\u0942\u0926 \u0938\u092d\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u091a\u0941\u0928\u093e\u0935 \u092e\u0947\u0902 1134 \u0928\u0947 \u0915\u093f\u092f\u093e \u092e\u0924\u0926\u093e\u0928, Dainik Bhaskar, May 28, 2018]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oMciiRUfpB0 Sood Community Meeting of the Dharamsala in Sirhind, Hamdard Media, September 8, 2016 ]</ref>\n\n==Surname==\nNotable persons from the '''Sood''' or '''Sud''' community include:\n*[[Arun Sood]], Indian politician from Bharatiya Janata Party, Chandigarh\n*[[Ajay K. Sood]], (born 1951), Physicist\n*[[Amita Emmanuelle Dhiri]], (born 1965), British Actor\n*[[Anish Sood]], (born 1980), Indian Musician\n*[[Anita Sood]], Indian Swimmer\n*[[Anjli Mohindra]], (born 1990) Indian British Stage and Screen Actor\n*[[Anupam Sud]], Award winning Indian Artist and Printmaker\n*[[Asmita Sood]], (born 1989), Indian model\n*[[Atul Mohindra]], (born 1966) Indian Cricketer\n*[[Bimla Kashyap Sood]], (born 1942), Indian politician from Shimla and member of Rajya Sabha\n*[[Brahm Mohindra]], Indian politician from Patiala\n*[[Chandril Sood]], (born 1991), Indian Tennis player\n*[[Gagan Mohindra]], Indian British Member of Parliament for South West Hertfordshire, UK\n*[[Kamini Kaushal]], (born 1927), Indian Actor\n*[[Manjula Sood]], British politician from Leicester and first Asian female Lord Mayor in the United Kingdom\n*[[Manoj Sood]], (born 1962), Canadian actor\n*[[Neeraj Sood]], (born 1969), Indian actor\n*[[Rakesh Sood]], IFS 1976, former Indian Ambassador and Special Envoy for Disarmament and Non-proliferation\n*[[Rahul Sood]], Founder of VooDoo PC\n*[[Randhir Sud]], Indian Gastroenterologist and [[Padma Shri]]\n*[[Ritu Beri]], Indian fashion designer and head of the French fashion house, Jean Louis Scherrer\n*[[Ruhila Adatia-Sood]], (1982\u20132013), Kenyan radio host\n*[[Sonu Sood]], Indian actor\n*[[Varun Sood]], India actor, VJ\n*[[Varun Sood (cricketer)|Varun Sood]], Indian cricketer\n*[[Veena Cabreros Sud]], Canadian-born, Indian American Television Writer, Director, and Producer\n*[[Vijat Mohindra]], Indian American fashion Photographer\n*[[Vikram Sood]], former head of the Research and Analysis Wing (R&AW), and an advisor to the Observer Research Foundation\n*Salamat Dosaj\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{surname}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|the surname|the village in India|Sood, Arunachal Pradesh}}\n\n{{wiktionary|Sood}}\n\n'''Sood''' or '''Sud''' is a Rajput community (Descendents of Sodha Rajputs) mainly centered in the plains of [[Sirhind]] and [[Punjab]] and hills of [[Kangra, Himachal Pradesh|Kangra]], [[Kashmir]], and [[Himachal Pradesh]].<ref>Mondays on the Dark Night of the Moon: Himalayan Foothill Folktales (Exeter Studies in History), Kirin Narayan, Oxford University Press, June 19, 1997)</ref><ref>Origin and History of Soods, 1975, Madan Mohan Sood, Sood Sabha Chandigarh)</ref><ref>[https://m.divyahimachal.com/article/14-%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B-%E0%A4%A7%E0%A5%82%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%A7%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AE-%E0%A4%B8%E0%A5%87-%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE-%E0%A4%9C%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%8F%E0%A4%97%E0%A4%BE/1813828 14 \u0915\u094b \u0927\u0942\u092e\u0927\u093e\u092e \u0938\u0947 \u092e\u0928\u093e\u092f\u093e \u091c\u093e\u090f\u0917\u093e \u2018\u0938\u0942\u0926 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0928 \u092e\u0947\u0932\u093e\u2019, October 4, 2018]</ref> \n\n==Origin and History==\nThe word '''\"Sood\"''' or '''\"Sud\"''' is of Sanskrit origin and according to Amar Kosh (an authoritative Hindi Dictionary) it means a \"''courageous and a brave person or a victor of his enemies''\". The word ''''Sood'''' finds a mention in the Vedas at 23 places (15 places in the Rig Ved, 6 places in the Yajur Ved and twice in the Atharva Ved). Interestingly, Lord Krishna is also known as 'Madhusudan' \u2013 (Sudan means 'sanharak' \u2013 killer of demon Madhu). The Sood community is a very ancient fraternity and some Sood/Sud gotras are merchants as well. \n\nIn the 3rd century BCE, the Brahmin Rishis were perturbed by the spread of Buddhism across India, because the old Vedic Hindu Dharma was getting a great set back. Hence, the Rishis performed a sacred Yajna at Mount Abu to revive old Hindu Dharma based on the Vedic traditions. The sacred flames of this Agni Kund, incarnated and baptised four Kshatriyas namely \u2013 the Parmar, the Parihar, the Solanki and the Chouhan. These four took a holy vow to re-establish the ancient glory of Hindu Dharma by fighting against the mass change of faith from Hinduism to Buddhism. These four Kshatriyas spread four new branches of Hinduism all over the country. The second son born to Parmar was named Sood and his descendents formed the Sood community. A reference of 44 descendants of Parmar is also available. These sood descendents formed the Sood Dynasty and the capital city of the Sood Dynasty for eight generations was Patten in Sind, now in Pakistan. The capital was later shifted to Alwar and finally King Jai Singh, (son of King Dahar) shifted his capital to Amar Kot, now in Pakistan. There is a reference of 101 Sood Kings or Rajas ruling in different parts of India. The Soods established themselves in the North and later got concentrated at Soodpur, now renamed Sirhind.  \n\nDue to the seven invasions of India by Ahmed Shah Abdali between 1748 and 1757 A.D., at Soodpur and gradually into Rajasthan and later of entire India, the Soods fled to different villages and towns in Punjab and Himachal Pradesh.<ref name=\"originHistory\">{{cite book|title=Origin And History Of Soods (A community in India)|first1=Yaman|last1=Sood|year=1975|publisher=Sood Sabha Chandigarh|url=http://soodsabhachandigarh.org/history.html#2|accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Gotras or Sub Castes==\nBoth the Punjab section and the Hill section of the Sood community have 52 Gotras or Sub Castes each, many of which are named after the villages they settled in. <ref name=\"Gotras or Sub Castes\">{{cite book|title=Origin And History Of Soods (A community in India)|first1=Yaman|last1=Sood|year=1975|publisher=Sood Sabha Chandigarh|url=http://soodsabhachandigarh.org/history.html#8|accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nThe Punjab section Gotras or Sub Castes are : Badhoo, Balgan, Baranwal, Behal, Beri, Bharak, Bhokaha (or Bhokhi), Bhola, Bodhi, Bourie, Brahmi, Dadan, Dauli (or Deli), Dhalli (or Dhati), Dhanda, Dhaunchak, Dhiri, Dhookhi, Dhoop, Dosaj, Gajri, Gajja (or Gajjey), Gondal (Gandel), Gopal, Goyal, Jandpal (or Janpal), Jari, Kajla (or Kajley), Lau, Mahidhar, Mahiyar (or Mayor), Makaura (or Makaurey), Mandal, Mohindra, Mohni, Mukandi, Momman, Nandoo, Nehra, Paal, Phakka, Pharwaha, Phassi, Poora, Rora, Rohnir, Rodher, Sanwal, Sulhan, Tagaley, Teji, Udhar, Ugal-Virk or Virk and Vassan.\n\nThe Hill section Gotras or Sub Castes are : Bahil, Bajwaria, Banta, Bhagley, Bhagra, Basohal, Basalia, Butail, Chakahria, Chakaseday, Chamib, Chaudhri, Chaukand, Chaujar, Chehray, Chimia, Cheemrey, Chhabb, Chonolia, Dagan, Didi, Dhophmal, Doddal, Dogan, Dorela, Dunyal, Indoria, Harail, Haraloo, Indoria, Jallundhroo, Jaiswal, Jandranglu, Jhalya, Jhangra, Jehelghat, Kalandar, Kandal, Karol, Kataway, Kaunsal, Kutharia, Kuthiala, Lahespar, Lakhanty, Lamsay, Lama, Langey, Lasaria, Laserday, Lauriya, Ling, Mahdoodia, Mangwalich, Mariya, Mand, Masoob, Mehtay, Mithoo, Naggal, Nehdal, Pabba, Panbalia, Paptopay, Patopa, Pulkaha, Phagdey, Phalkolia, Sabloria, Sah, Saraup, Sawali, Shall, Takalo and Udhwal.\n\nThe Soods are organized into city specific chapters of their organization in many countries. These are called the Sood Sabhas and these elect their leaders.<ref>[https://www.bhaskar.com/himachal/shimla/news/latest-shimla-news-020502-1814699.html  \u0938\u0942\u0926 \u0938\u092d\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u091a\u0941\u0928\u093e\u0935 \u092e\u0947\u0902 1134 \u0928\u0947 \u0915\u093f\u092f\u093e \u092e\u0924\u0926\u093e\u0928, Dainik Bhaskar, May 28, 2018]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oMciiRUfpB0 Sood Community Meeting of the Dharamsala in Sirhind, Hamdard Media, September 8, 2016 ]</ref>\n\n==Surname==\nNotable persons from the '''Sood''' or '''Sud''' community include:\n*[[Arun Sood]], Indian politician from Bharatiya Janata Party, Chandigarh\n*[[Ajay K. Sood]], (born 1951), Physicist\n*[[Amita Emmanuelle Dhiri]], (born 1965), British Actor\n*[[Anish Sood]], (born 1980), Indian Musician\n*[[Anita Sood]], Indian Swimmer\n*[[Anjli Mohindra]], (born 1990) Indian British Stage and Screen Actor\n*[[Anupam Sud]], Award winning Indian Artist and Printmaker\n*[[Asmita Sood]], (born 1989), Indian model\n*[[Atul Mohindra]], (born 1966) Indian Cricketer\n*[[Bimla Kashyap Sood]], (born 1942), Indian politician from Shimla and member of Rajya Sabha\n*[[Brahm Mohindra]], Indian politician from Patiala\n*[[Chandril Sood]], (born 1991), Indian Tennis player\n*[[Gagan Mohindra]], Indian British Member of Parliament for South West Hertfordshire, UK\n*[[Kamini Kaushal]], (born 1927), Indian Actor\n*[[Manjula Sood]], British politician from Leicester and first Asian female Lord Mayor in the United Kingdom\n*[[Manoj Sood]], (born 1962), Canadian actor\n*[[Neeraj Sood]], (born 1969), Indian actor\n*[[Rakesh Sood]], IFS 1976, former Indian Ambassador and Special Envoy for Disarmament and Non-proliferation\n*[[Rahul Sood]], Founder of VooDoo PC\n*[[Randhir Sud]], Indian Gastroenterologist and [[Padma Shri]]\n*[[Ritu Beri]], Indian fashion designer and head of the French fashion house, Jean Louis Scherrer\n*[[Ruhila Adatia-Sood]], (1982\u20132013), Kenyan radio host\n*[[Sonu Sood]], Indian actor\n*[[Varun Sood]], India actor, VJ\n*[[Varun Sood (cricketer)|Varun Sood]], Indian cricketer\n*[[Veena Cabreros Sud]], Canadian-born, Indian American Television Writer, Director, and Producer\n*[[Vijat Mohindra]], Indian American fashion Photographer\n*[[Vikram Sood]], former head of the Research and Analysis Wing (R&AW), and an advisor to the Observer Research Foundation\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{surname}}\n", "name_user": "2601:40b:8404:1560:ed29:33dd:13a0:9a9b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sood"}
{"title_page": "Murinae", "text_new": "{{short description|Subfamily of rodents}}\n{{More footnotes|date=November 2009}}\n{{Automatic Taxobox\n| name = Old World rats and mice\n| fossil_range = Middle [[Miocene]] \u2013 recent\n| image = Mouse white background.jpg\n| image_caption = ''[[House mouse|Mus musculus]]'', the house mouse\n| taxon = Murinae\n| authority = [[Johann Karl Wilhelm Illiger|Illiger]], 1811\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Genus|Genera]]\n| subdivision = \n''[[Abditomys]]''<br>\n''[[Abeomelomys]]''<br>\n''[[Aethomys]]''<br>\n''[[Anisomys]]''<br>\n''[[Anonymomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Antemus]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Anthracomys]]''<br>\n''[[Apodemus]]''<br>\n''[[Apomys]]''<br>\n''[[Archboldomys]]''<br>\n''[[Arvicanthis]]''<br>\n''[[Baiyankamys]]''<br>\n''[[Bandicota]]''<br>\n''[[Batomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Beremendimys]]''<br>\n''[[Berylmys]]''<br>\n''[[Bullimus]]''<br>\n''[[Bunomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Canariomys]]''<br>\n''[[Carpomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Castillomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Castromys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Chardinomys]]''<br>\n''[[Chiromyscus]]''<br>\n''[[Chiropodomys]]''<br>\n''[[Chiruromys]]''<br>\n''[[Chrotomys]]''<br>\n''[[Coccymys]]''<br>\n''[[Colomys]]''<br>\n''[[Conilurus]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Coryphomys]]''<br>\n''[[Crateromys]]''<br>\n''[[Crossomys]]''<br>\n''[[Cremnomys]]''<br>\n''[[Crunomys]]''<br>\n''[[Dacnomys]]''<br>\n''[[Dasymys]]''<br>\n''[[Dephomys]]''<br>\n''[[Desmomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Dilatomys]]''<br>\n''[[Diomys]]''<br>\n''[[Diplothrix]]''<br>\n''[[Echiothrix]]''<br>\n''[[Eropeplus]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Euryotomys]]''<br>\n''[[Golunda]]''<br>\n''[[Gracilimus]]''<br>\n''[[Grammomys]]''<br>\n''[[Hadromys]]''<br>\n''[[Haeromys]]''<br>\n''[[Hapalomys]]''<br>\n''[[Heimyscus]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Hooijeromys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Huaxiamys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Huerzelerimys]]''<br>\n''[[Hybomys]]''<br>\n''[[Hydromys]]''<br>\n''[[Hylomyscus]]''<br>\n''[[Hyomys]]''<br>\n''[[Hyorhinomys]]''<br>\n''[[Kadarsanomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Karnimata]]''<br>\n''[[Komodomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Kritimys]]''<br>\n''[[Lamottemys]]''<br>\n''[[Leggadina]]''<br>\n''[[Lemniscomys]]''<br>\n''[[Lenomys]]''<br>\n''[[Lenothrix]]''<br>\n''[[Leopoldamys]]''<br>\n''[[Leporillus]]''<br>\n''[[Leptomys]]''<br>\n''[[Limnomys]]''<br>\n''[[Lorentzimys]]''<br>\n''[[Macruromys]]''<br>\n''[[Madromys]]''<br>\n''[[Malacomys]]''<br>\n''[[Mallomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Malpaisomys]]''<br>\n''[[Mammelomys]]''<br>\n''[[Margaretamys]]''<br>\n''[[Mastacomys]]''<br>\n''[[Mastomys]]''<br>\n''[[Maxomys]]''<br>\n''[[Melasmothrix]]''<br>\n''[[Melomys]]''<br>\n''[[Mesembriomys]]''<br>\n''[[Microhydromys]]''<br>\n''[[Micromys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Mikrotia]]''<br>\n''[[Millardia]]''<br>\n''[[Mirzamys]]''<br>\n''[[Muriculus]]''<br>\n''[[Musseromys]]''<br>\n''[[Mus (genus)|Mus]]''<br>\n''[[Mylomys]]''<br>\n''[[Myomyscus]]''<br>\n''[[Myotomys]]''<br>\n''[[Nesokia]]''<br>\n''[[Nesoromys]]''<br>\n''[[Nilopegamys]]''<br>\n''[[Niviventer]]''<br>\n''[[Notomys]]''<br>\n''[[Oenomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Orientalomys]]''<br>\n''[[Otomys]]''<br>\n''[[Palawanomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Paraethomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Parapodemus]]''<br>\n''[[Papagomys]]''<br>\n''[[Parahydromys]]''<br>\n''[[Paraleptomys]]''<br>\n''[[Paramelomys]]''<br>\n''[[Parotomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Parapelomys]]''<br>\n''[[Paucidentomys]]''<br>\n''[[Paruromys]]''<br>\n''[[Paulamys]]''<br>\n''[[Pelomys]]''<br>\n''[[Phloeomys]]''<br>\n''[[Pithecheir]]''<br>\n''[[Pithecheirops]]''<br>\n''[[Pogonomelomys]]''<br>\n''[[Pogonomys]]''<br>\n''[[Praomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Progonomys]]''<br>\n''[[Protochromys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Qianomys]]''<br>\n''[[Pseudohydromys]]''<br>\n''[[Pseudomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Ratchaburimys]]''<br>\n''[[Rattus]]''<br>\n''[[Rhabdomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Rhagamys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Rhagapodemus]]''<br>\n''[[Rhynchomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Saidomys]]''<br>\n''[[Saxatilomys]]''<br>\n''[[Solomys]]''<br>\n''[[Sommeromys]]''<br>\n''[[Soricomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Spelaeomys]]''<br>\n''[[Srilankamys]]''<br>\n''[[Stenocephalemys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Stephanomys]]''<br>\n''[[Stochomys]]''<br>\n''[[Sundamys]]''<br>\n''[[Taeromys]]''<br>\n''[[Tarsomys]]''<br>\n''[[Tateomys]]''<br>\n''[[Thallomys]]''<br>\n''[[Thamnomys]]''<br>\n''[[Tokudaia]]''<br>\n''[[Tonkinomys]]''<br>\n''[[Tryphomys]]''<br>\n''[[Uromys]]''<br>\n''[[Vandeleuria]]''<br>\n''[[Vernaya]]''<br>\n''[[Waiomys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Wushanomys]]''<br>\n''[[Xenuromys]]''<br>\n''[[Xeromys]]''<br>\n\u2020''[[Yunomys]]''<br>\n''[[Zelotomys]]''<br>\n''[[Zyzomys]]''\n}}\n\n{{Redirect-distinguish2|Murine|[[Murrine]] the art glass technique}}\n\nThe '''Old World rats and mice''', part of the [[subfamily]] '''Murinae''' in the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Muridae]], comprise at least 519 species. Members of this subfamily are called '''murines'''. This subfamily is larger than all [[mammal]] families except the [[Cricetidae]] and [[Muridae]], and is larger than all [[mammal]] [[order (biology)|order]]s except the [[bat]]s and the remainder of the [[rodent]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Mammal Species of the World: A Taxonomic and Geographic Reference, Volume 12|year = 2005|isbn = 9780801882210|location = |pages = 1191|url = https://books.google.com/?id=YnYED-YG0ZYC&pg=PA1191&lpg=PA1191&dq=mures+old-world#v=onepage&q=Mures&f=false|last1 = Wilson|first1 = Don E.|last2 = Reeder|first2 = Deeann M.}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe Murinae are native to [[Africa]], [[Europe]], [[Asia]], and [[Australia]].  They are the only [[terrestrial animal|terrestrial]] [[placental]] [[mammal]]s native to Australia.  They have also been [[invasive species|introduced]] to all continents except [[Antarctica]], and are serious pest animals.  This is particularly true in island communities where they have contributed to the [[endangered|endangerment]] and [[extinct]]ion of many native animals.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nTwo prominent murine human [[commensalism|commensal]]s have become vital [[laboratory animal]]s.  The [[brown rat]] and [[house mouse]] are both used as medical subjects.\n\nThe murines have a distinctive [[Molar (tooth)|molar]] pattern that involves three rows of cusps instead of two, the primitive pattern seen most frequently in [[muroid rodent]]s.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n==Fossils==\nThe first known appearance of the Murinae in the [[fossil]] record is about [[Miocene|14 million years ago]] with the fossil genus ''[[Antemus]]''. ''Antemus'' is thought to derive directly from ''[[Potwarmus]]'', which has a more primitive tooth pattern.  Likewise, two genera, ''[[Progonomys]]'' and ''[[Karnimata]]'', are thought to derive directly from ''Antemus''.  ''Progonomys'' is thought to be the ancestor of ''[[Mus (genus)|Mus]]'' and relatives, while ''Karnimata'' is thought to lead to ''[[Rattus]]'' and relatives.  All of these fossils are found in the well-preserved and easily dated [[Siwalik]] fossil beds of [[Pakistan]]. The transition from ''Potwarmus'' to ''Antemus'' to ''Progonomys'' and ''Karnimata'' is considered an excellent example of [[anagenesis|anagenic evolution]].{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n==Taxonomy==\nMost of the Murinae have been poorly studied.  Some genera have been grouped, such as the hydromyine water rats, conilurine or pseudomyine Australian mice, or the phloeomyine [[Southeast Asia]]n forms.  No [[tribe (biology)|tribal]] level [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]] has been attempted for the complete subfamily.  It appears as if genera from Southeast Asian islands and Australia may be early offshoots compared to mainland forms.  The [[vlei rat]]s in the genera ''[[Otomys]]'' and ''[[Parotomys]]'' are often placed in a separate subfamily, Otomyinae, but have been shown to be closely related to African murines in spite of their uniqueness.\n\nThree genera, ''[[Uranomys]]'', ''[[Lophuromys]]'', and ''[[Acomys]]'', were once considered to be murines, but were found to be more closely related to [[gerbil]]s through [[molecular phylogeny|molecular phylogenetics]].  They have been assigned a new subfamily status, [[Deomyinae]].\n\nMolecular phylogenetic studies of Murinae include Lecompte, et al. (2008),<ref>Emilie Lecompte, Ken Aplin, Christiane Denys, Fran\u00e7ois Catzeflis, Marion Chades and Pascale Chevret. 2008. Phylogeny and biogeography of African Murinae based on mitochondrial and nuclear gene sequences, with a new tribal classification of the subfamily. BMC Evolutionary Biology2008 8:199 DOI: 10.1186/1471-2148-8-199</ref> which analyzes African murine species based on the mitochondrial [[cytochrome b]] gene and two nuclear gene fragments. Lecompte, et al. (2008) estimates that African murines colonized Africa from Asia approximately 11 million years ago during the [[Miocene]].\n\nThe following [[phylogeny]] of 16 Murinae [[genus|genera]], based on [[molecular phylogenetic]] analysis of the [[RBP3|Interphotoreceptor Retinoid Binding Protein]] (IRBP) gene, is from Jansa & Weksler (2004: 264).<ref name=\"JansaWeksler2004\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.ympev.2003.07.002 | last1 = Jansa | first1 = S.A. | last2 = Weksler | first2 = M. | title = Phylogeny of muroid rodents: relationships within and among major lineages as determined by IRBP gene sequences | journal = Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume = 31 | issue = 1 | pages = 256\u2013276 | year = 2004 | pmid = 15019624| ref = harv}}</ref>\n{{clade| style=font-size:95%;line-height:90%\n|label1='''Murinae'''&nbsp;\n|1={{clade\n|1=''[[Phloeomys]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1={{clade\n|1=''[[Micromys]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Maxomys]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Niviventer]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Sundamys]]''\n|2=''[[Rattus]]''\n}}\n}}\n}}\n}}\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Rhynchomys]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Otomys]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Aethomys]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Rhabdomys]]''\n|2=''[[Grammomys]]''\n}}\n}}\n}}\n|3={{clade\n|1=''[[Tokudaia]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Mus (genus)|Mus]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Mastomys]]''\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Praomys]]''\n|2=''[[Hylomyscus]]''\n}}\n}}\n}}\n}}\n}}\n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n==Distribution==\nThe following is a list of Murinae genus divisions ordered by the continents that they are endemic to. Most of the diversity is located in [[Southeast Asia]] and [[Australasia]].\n\n*[[Africa]]\n**Aethomys division - 1 genus\n**Arvicanthis division - 6 genera\n**Colomys division - 3 genera\n**Dasymys division - 8 genera\n**Hybomys division - 3 genera\n**Malacomys division - 1 genus\n**Oenomys division - 5 genea\n**[[Otomyini]] division/tribe - 3 genera\n**[[Stenocephalomys]]{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n*[[Eurasia]]\n**Apodemus division - 2 genera\n**Micromys division - 6 genera\n**Genus ''[[Mus (genus)|Mus]]''\n*[[South Asia]]\n**Golunda division - 1 genus\n**Millardia division - 4 genera\n*[[Southeast Asia]]\n**Dacnomys division - 8 genera\n**Hadromys division - 1 genus\n**Maxomys division - 1 genus\n**Pithecheir division - 6 genera\n**Rattus division - 21 genera\n*[[Philippines]]\n**Chrotomys division - 5 genera\n**Crunomys division - 2 genera\n**Phloeomys division - 4 genera\n**Genus ''[[Musseromys]]''\n*[[Sulawesi]]\n**Crunomys division - 2 genera\n**Echiothrix division - 1 genus\n**Melasmothrix division - 2 genera\n*[[Moluccas]]\n**Halmaheramys division - 1 genus\n*[[New Guinea]]\n**Hydromys division  - 6 genera\n**Lorentzimys division - 1 genus\n**Pogonomys division - 11 genera\n**Uromys division - 5 genera\n**Xeromys division - 3 genera\n**Genus ''[[Mirzamys]]''\n*[[Australia]]\n**Pseudomys division - 8 genera\n\n==List of species==\nAs of 2005, the Murinae contained 129 genera in 584 species.  Musser and Carleton (2005) divided the Murinae into 29 genus divisions.  They treated the [[Otomyinae]] as a separate subfamily, but all molecular analyses conducted to date have supported their inclusion in the Murinae as relatives of African genera .{{sfn|Michaux|2001}}{{sfn|Jansa|Weksler|2004}}{{sfn|Steppan|Adkins|Anderson|2004}}{{sfn|Jansa|Barker|Heaney|2006}} In a recent expedition in the Philippines, seven more ''[[Apomys]]'' mice were added and the genus was proposed to split into two subgenera - ''Apomys'' and ''Megapomys'', based on morphological and [[cytochrome b]] DNA sequences.{{sfn|Heaney|Balete|Rickart|Alviola|2011}}\n\n'''SUBFAMILY MURINAE''' - Old World rats and mice\n*'''[[Aethomys]] division'''\n**Genus ''[[Aethomys]]'' - bush rats\n***[[Bocage's rock rat]], ''Aethomys bocagei''\n***[[Red rock rat]], ''Aethomys chrysophilus''\n***[[Grant's rock rat]], ''Aethomys (Micaelamys) granti''\n***[[Hinde's rock rat]], ''Aethomys hindei''\n***[[Tete veld aethomys]], ''Aethomys ineptus''\n***[[Kaiser's rock rat]], ''Aethomys kaiseri''\n***[[Namaqua rock rat]], ''Aethomys (Micaelamys) namaquensis''\n***[[Nyika rock rat]], ''Aethomys nyikae''\n***[[Silinda rock rat]], ''Aethomys silindensis''\n***[[Tinfields rock rat]], ''Aethomys stannarius''\n***[[Thomas's rock rat]], ''Aethomys thomasi''\n*'''[[Apodemus]] division'''\n**Genus ''[[Apodemus]]'' - Old World field mice\n***[[Striped field mouse]], ''Apodemus agrarius''\n***[[Alpine field mouse]], ''Apodemus alpicola''\n***[[Small Japanese field mouse]], ''Apodemus argenteus''\n***[[Chevrier's field mouse]], ''Apodemus chevrieri''\n***[[South China field mouse]], ''Apodemus draco''\n***[[Yellow-necked mouse]], ''Apodemus flavicollis'' \u2013 includes ''A. arianus''\n***[[Himalayan field mouse]], ''Apodemus gurkha''\n***[[Caucasus field mouse]], ''Apodemus hyrcanicus''\n***[[Sichuan field mouse]], ''Apodemus latronum''\n***[[Pygmy field mouse]], ''Apodemus microps''\n***[[Eastern broad-toothed field mouse]], ''Apodemus mystacinus''\n***[[Western broad-toothed field mouse]], ''Apodemus epimelas''\n***[[Ward's field mouse]], ''Apodemus pallipes''\n***[[Korean field mouse]], ''Apodemus peninsulae''\n***[[Black Sea field mouse]], ''Apodemus ponticus''\n***[[Kashmir field mouse]], ''Apodemus rusiges''\n***[[Taiwan field mouse]], ''Apodemus semotus''\n***[[Large Japanese field mouse]], ''Apodemus speciosus''\n***[[Wood mouse]], 