{"title_page": "FIFA 20", "text_new": "{{redirect|Piemonte Calcio|a defunct Italian football club|Piemonte F.C.|the club Piemonte Calcio is based on|Juventus}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Fix Career Mode!\n| image = FIFA 20 Standard Edition Cover.jpg\n| caption = {{Nowrap|[[PS4]] cover art featuring [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid\u2019s]] [[Eden Hazard]]}}\n| developer = [[EA Vancouver]]<br/>[[Electronic Arts#Studios|EA Romania]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.ea.com/games/fifa/fifa-20 | title=FIFA 20 - Soccer Video Game | website=EA.com | accessdate=2019-06-19| date=20 September 2018 }}</ref>\n| publisher = [[EA Sports]]\n| composer = Nafrom\n| series = [[FIFA (video game series)|''FIFA'']]\n| engine = [[Frostbite (game engine)|Frostbite 3]]\n| platforms = {{ubl|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| released = 27 September 2019\n| genre = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''FIFA 20''''' is a [[association football|football]] [[simulation video game|simulation]] [[video game]] published by [[Electronic Arts]] as part of the ''[[FIFA (video game series)|FIFA series]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/e3-2019-star-wars-jedi-fallen-order-apex-legends-fifa-20-the-sims-4-and-everything-announced-at-ea-play/|title=E3 2019: Star Wars Jedi: Fallen Order, Apex Legends, The Sims 4 and everything announced at EA Play|last=Sherr|first=Ian|date=8 June 2019|work=[[CNET]]|access-date=31 July 2019|last2=Serrels|first2=Mark}}</ref> It is the 27th installment in the ''FIFA'' series, and was released on 27 September 2019 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], and [[Nintendo Switch]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2019-fifa-20-announced-with-release-date-volta-/1100-6467435/|title=E3 2019: FIFA 20 Announced With Release Date, Volta Mode|last=Dayus|first=Oscar|date=12 June 2019|work=[[GameSpot]]|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>    \n\n[[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] winger [[Eden Hazard]] was named the new cover star of the Regular Edition, with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] defender [[Virgil van Dijk]] on the cover of the Champions Edition.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/fifa-20-cover-stars-are-eden-hazard-and-virgil-van-dijk|title=FIFA 20 cover stars are Eden Hazard and Virgil Van Dijk|last=Donovan|first=Imogen|date=29 July 2019|work=VideoGamer|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> Former [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] and Real Madrid midfielder [[Zinedine Zidane]] was later named as the cover star for the Ultimate Edition.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/7/fifa-20-zinedine-zidane-ultimate-edition-cover-fut-icon|title=Zinedine Zidane to Cover 'FIFA 20 Ultimate Edition'|last=Stanley|first=Jack|date=30 July 2019|work=HYPEBEAST|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe game features ''VOLTA'' ''Football'' for the first time, a new mode that provides a variance on the traditional 11v11 gameplay and focuses on small-sided [[Street football|street]] and [[futsal]] games.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-06-08-confirmed-fifa-20-has-a-fifa-street-mode-called-volta-football|title=Confirmed: FIFA 20 has a FIFA Street mode called Volta Football|last=Yin-Poole|first=Wesley|date=8 June 2019|work=[[Eurogamer]]|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> The mode is believed to be focused on the former [[FIFA Street (2005 video game)|''FIFA Street'']] series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/fifa-20-has-a-fifa-street-style-mode-called-volta-ea-confirms/|title=FIFA 20 has a FIFA Street-style mode called Volta, EA confirms|last=Horti|first=Samuel|date=8 June 2019|work=[[PC Gamer]]|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Features == \nGameplay changes to ''FIFA 20'' focus primarily on a new feature titled ''VOLTA Football''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gfinityesports.com/article/2057/fifa-20-volta-football-gameplay-information-volta-story-mode-customisation-and-more-from-ea-sports-new-game|title=FIFA 20: VOLTA Football Gameplay Information, Volta Story Mode, Customisation And More From EA Sports New Game|last=Trout|first=Chris|date=8 August 2019|work=[[Gfinity|Gfinity Esports]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> The mode, which translates to 'return' in Portuguese, focuses on street football rather than the traditional matches associated with the FIFA series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/volta-the-return-of-fifa-street-why-ea-is-bringing-back/ex4l81kxxtc412dv0sqc5e70q|title=Volta: The return of FIFA Street & why EA is bringing back iconic game mode for FIFA 20|last=Thomas|first=Josh|date=6 August 2019|work=[[Goal (website)|Goal.com]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> It includes several options to play in three versus three, four versus four and five versus five matches, as well as with professional [[futsal]] rules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.futsalfocus.net/volta-football-futsal-ea-sports/|title=Futsal included in the new Volta Football by EA Sports|date=9 June 2019|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref> The mode will incorporate the same engine, but places emphasis on skill and independent play rather than tactical or team play.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/fifa-20-street-mode-volta-football-ps4-xbox-features-update-latest-a9047101.html|title=Fifa Street is back \u2013 here\u2019s what it looks like|date=8 August 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, players have the option to customise their player by gender, clothing, shoes, hats and tattoos.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.futuregamereleases.com/2019/06/fifa-20-volta-football-is-taking-the-fun-to-the-streets/|title=FIFA 20 Volta Football is taking the fun to the streets|last=Goodwin|first=David|date=8 June 2019|work=Future Game Releases|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Following the completion of the three-part series ''\"The Journey\"'' in ''[[FIFA 19]]'', players can now have a similar storyline mode in ''VOLTA Football'', which would be played with the player's own character.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nChanges were also made to the traditional 11 versus 11 mode to encourage more one-on-ones and off-the-ball space creation. New penalty and free-kick mechanics were implemented and updates were made to the ball physics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2019/06/fifa-20-trailer-volta-football-street|title=Here's the First FIFA 20 Trailer and Details on 'Volta Football' Street Mode|last=Segev|first=Tom|date=10 June 2019|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nVOLTA Football includes 17 locations, with each providing a unique experience. As well as a generic warehouse and parking lot, players can also compete in [[Amsterdam]], [[Barcelona]], [[Berlin]], [[Buenos Aires]], [[Cape Town]], [[Lagos]], [[London]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Mexico City]], [[Miami]], [[New York City]], [[Paris]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Rome]] and [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/gaming/volta-football-fifa-20-news-16722870|title=Fifa 20: Volta Football latest including skill moves, story mode, locations and customisation|last=Bliss|first=Nathan|date=27 August 2019|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nCommentary is once again provided by [[Martin Tyler]] and [[Alan Smith (footballer, born 1962)|Alan Smith]] and alternating with [[Derek Rae]] and [[Lee Dixon]] for all competitions, with [[Alan McInally]] providing in-game score updates. \n\n=== Pro Clubs ===\n\nPro clubs is a game mode in FIFA 20 where players can create personalised pros and compete in a squad against other squads online. The objective is to rise up the Divisions, starting in Division 10 and climbing to compete for the Division 1 title.\n\n=== Ultimate Team ===\nUltimate Team features 88 icon players, including 15 new names. [[Carlos Alberto Torres|Carlos Alberto]], [[John Barnes (footballer)|John Barnes]], [[Kenny Dalglish]], [[Didier Drogba]], [[Michael Essien]], [[Garrincha]], [[Pep Guardiola]], [[Kak\u00e1]], [[Ronald Koeman]], [[Andrea Pirlo]], [[Ian Rush]], [[Hugo S\u00e1nchez]], [[Ian Wright]], [[Gianluca Zambrotta]] and [[Zinedine Zidane]] all feature as icons for the first time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6423022-fifa-20-ultimate-team-to-include-brand-new-icons-including-ian-wright-andrea-pirlo-didier-drogba|title=FIFA 20: Ultimate Team to Include Brand New Icons Including Ian Wright, Andrea Pirlo & Didier Drogba|last=Gott|first=Tom|date=31 July 2019|work=90min|access-date=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo new game modes \u2013 King of the Hill and Mystery Ball \u2013 are also incorporated in Ultimate Team following their previous inclusion in kick-off mode.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gfinityesports.com/article/2033/breaking-fifa-20-ultimate-team-new-house-rules-fut-friendlies-icons-king-of-the-hill-mystery-ball-and-more-revealed-by-ea|title=FIFA 20 Ultimate Team: New House rules, FUT Friendlies, ICONS, King of the Hill, Mystery Ball, and more revealed by EA|last=Pusinelli|first=Alastair|date=31 July 2019|work=[[Gfinity|Gfinity Esports]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Mystery Ball gives the attacking side boosts to passing, shooting, dribbling, speed or all attributes, adding unpredictability to every match.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://realsport101.com/fifa/fifa-20-ultimate-team-what-is-the-new-mystery-ball-mode-fut-friendlies-house-rules-kick-off-cover-star-release-demo/|title=FIFA 20 Ultimate Team: What is the new Mystery Ball mode?|last=Pusinelli|first=Alastair|date=1 August 2019|work=RealSport|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> King of the Hill sees players fight for possession in a randomly generated zone on the pitch to boost the amount the next goal is worth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://realsport101.com/fifa/fifa-20-ultimate-team-house-rules-fut-friendlies-king-of-the-hill-mysteryball/|title=FIFA 20 Ultimate Team: New House rules, FUT Friendlies, ICONS, King of the Hill, Mystery Ball, and more revealed by EA|last=Musa|first=Talal|date=31 July 2019|work=RealSport|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Ultimate Team also includes a new dedicated kit supporting Premier League's no room for racism campaign.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://copa90.com/en/fifa20/ea-launches-no-room-for-racism-kit|title=FIFA20: EA SPORTS Launches New No Room For Racism Kit |accessdate=23 October 2019|website=Copa90}}</ref>\n\n=== Career Mode ===\nCareer Mode, following feedback from the community, saw some major updates - mainly to the manager mode.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thesixthaxis.com/2019/08/07/fifa-20s-career-mode-football-manager/|title=FIFA 20's Career Mode will have some major changes|last=Suddi|first=Aran|date=7 August 2019|work=The Sixth Axis|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> New additions include fully interactive press conferences and player conversations, an improved player morale system which can affect the team or individual players stats, performance levels and stance with the manager. The ability to fully customise the manager\u2019s appearance and gender, a new dynamic player potential system, live news screenshots, league oriented UI and new negotiation environments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ea.com/en-gb/games/fifa/fifa-20/news/pitch-notes-fifa-20-career-mode-deep-dive|title=Pitch Notes \u2013 FIFA 20 Career Mode Deep Dive|last=|first=|date=10 July 2019|website=[[EA Sports|EA Sports FIFA]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Licenses ===\nThe game will feature more than 30 official leagues, over 700 clubs and over 17,000 players. Included for the first time is the Romanian [[Liga I]] and its 14 teams, as well as [[United Arab Emirates|Emirati]] club [[Al Ain FC|Al Ain]], who were added following extensive requests from the fans in the region.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://realsport101.com/fifa/fifa-20-new-league-finally-announced-as-ea-fight-back-at-pes-2020-release-date-demo-beta-career-mode-ultimate-team-fut-online-cover-star/|title=FIFA 20: New league finally announced as EA fight back at PES 2020|last=Pusinelli|first=Alastair|date=27 August 2019|work=RealSport|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395302780414|title=UAE's Al Ain FC sets sights on EA SPORTS FIFA 20 Debut|last=|first=|date=18 August 2019|work=Emirates News Agency|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nJuventus, Boca Juniors and River Plate are not featured after they signed exclusive partnership deals with ''[[eFootball Pro Evolution Soccer 2020|eFootball PES 2020]],'' and instead are known as Piemonte Calcio, Buenos Aires and N\u00fa\u00f1ez.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-49008496|title=Juventus to be called Piemonte Calcio in Fifa after PES deal|last=Gerken|first=Tom|date=16 July 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> The game would retain the players' likenesses, but the official badge and kits will be unavailable and instead feature custom designs produced by EA Sports and also lose their stadium licenses like the [[Juventus Stadium]], [[La Bombonera]] and [[El Monumental]]. [[Bayern Munich]] is featured in the game with their licensed players and kits but without their home stadium the [[Allianz Arena]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.futhead.com/news/fifa-20/2163/fut-20-juventus-pes-ea-loses-licensing/|title=Juventus is Piemonte Calcio: FIFA 20 won't have Juve's name, kit, badge|last=Zimmermann|first=Luke|date=16 July 2019|work=Futhead|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n''FIFA 20'' will retain the exclusive licenses to the [[UEFA Champions League]], [[UEFA Europa League]], and [[UEFA Super Cup]] first seen in ''FIFA 19''. The deal includes authentic broadcast packages, branding, and custom commentary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ea.com/games/fifa/fifa-20/leagues-and-clubs-authenticity|title=FIFA 20 Exclusive Licenses \u2013 All Leagues and Clubs|last=|first=|date=30 July 2019|website=[[EA Sports|EA Sports FIFA]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Additionally, the [[Copa Libertadores]], [[Copa Sudamericana]] and the [[Recopa Sudamericana]] is featured in the game via an update released on 13 March 2020.<ref> https://www.ea.com/games/fifa/fifa-20/conmebol-libertadores/</ref>\n\n=== Stadiums ===\nThere are 92 fully licensed stadiums from 15 countries in ''FIFA 20'', as well as 29 generic stadiums.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifauteam.com/fifa-20-stadiums/|title=FIFA 20 Stadiums|last=|first=|date=|website=FIFA U Team|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> [[Bramall Lane]] has been included following [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]'s promotion, ensuring that all [[Premier League]] teams have their respective stadiums.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/latest-blades-news/sheffield-united-this-is-what-bramall-lane-looks-like-on-fifa-20-as-blades-stadium-features-on-game-for-first-time-following-promotion-to-premier-league-492135|title=Sheffield United: THIS is what Bramall Lane looks like on FIFA 20 as Blades' stadium features on game for first time following promotion to Premier League|last=Hall|first=Danny|date=25 August 2019|work=[[Sheffield Star|The Star]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Three new Spanish stadiums have also been added \u2013 [[Estadio El Alcoraz]] (home of [[SD Huesca]]), [[Campo de F\u00fatbol de Vallecas|Estadio De Vallecas]] (home of [[Rayo Vallecano]]) and [[Estadio Jos\u00e9 Zorrilla]] (home of [[Real Valladolid]]).<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAs part of an extensive new licensing deal, 13 new stadiums across the [[Bundesliga]] and [[2. Bundesliga]] will be included. These include [[BayArena]] (home of [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen]]), [[Mercedes-Benz Arena (Stuttgart)|Mercedes-Benz Arena]] (home of [[VfB Stuttgart]]), [[Red Bull Arena (Leipzig)|Red Bull Arena]] (home of [[RB Leipzig]]) and [[Volkswagen Arena]] (home of [[VfL Wolfsburg]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/uk/fifa-20-bundesliga/|title=FIFA 20 Bundesliga tie-in adds 180 player faces and 13 new stadiums|last=Wilson|first=Ben|date=20 August 2019|work=[[GamesRadar+]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Also added into the game is the [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais|Groupama Stadium]], home of [[Olympique Lyonnais]] in [[Ligue 1]]; [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]], home of [[New York Red Bulls]] in [[Major League Soccer]]; as well as the [[2020 UEFA Champions League Final]] venue [[Atat\u00fcrk Olympic Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.vgr.com/new-fifa-20-stadiums-champions-league-venue-ataturk-olympic-stadium/4 |title= New FIFA 20 Stadiums Revealed Including Champions League Venue Ataturk Olympic Stadium |last= Couden |first= Matt |date= 18 September 2019 |website= VGR.com|access-date= 20 October 2019}}</ref>\n2 new stadiums were added in 2020 when the [[Copa Libertadores]] was released in March. The stadium [[Estadio Libertadores de Am\u00e9rica]] of the Argentinian club [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Independiente]] is now available, as well as the stadium [[Estadio Presidente Juan Domingo Per\u00f3n]] of the Argentinian club [[Racing Club de Avellaneda]]<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ea.com/en-gb/games/fifa/fifa-20/conmebol-libertadores?utm_campaign=fifa20_hd_ww_ic_soco_twt_fifa20-copa-tw-2192020&utm_source=twitter&utm_medium=social&cid=62570&ts=1582210710811 |title= CONMEBOL LIBERTADORES |website= EA.com|access-date= 3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n\n=== Demo/EA Access ===\nThe FIFA 20 demo was released on 10 September 2019 and includes 6 playable teams which can be played on the UEFA Champions League kick-off mode \u2013 [[Borussia Dortmund]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]],  [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]], [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/fifa-20-demo-release-date-time-and-how-to-play-now-on-ps4-pc-and-xbox-one|title=FIFA 20 demo: release date, time and how to play now on PS4, PC and Xbox One|last=Hood|first=Vic|date=10 September 2019|work=Techradar|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> and a demo of the new ''VOLTA Football'' mode.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportbible.com/football/gaming-news-take-a-bow-fifa-20-demo-to-be-released-on-september-12-teams-revealed-20190829|title=FIFA 20 Demo To Be Released On September 12: Game Modes, Playable Teams Leaked|last=Kenmare|first=Jack|date=29 August 2019|work=[[LADbible|Sport Bible]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> The demo is available for [[PS4]], [[Xbox One]] and PC.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.thesixthaxis.com/2019/09/10/fifa-20-demo-download-link-ps4-xb1-pc/|title=The FIFA 20 demo is now out, download link here|accessdate=10 September 2019|website=tsa}}</ref>\n\nThe game was released through the [[EA Access]] subscription on 24 September 2019, which also offers a free 10 hour trial.\n\n=== Covers ===\n''FIFA 20'' features three cover stars across all regional editions. [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] winger [[Eden Hazard]] was named the new cover star of the Regular Edition, with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] defender [[Virgil van Dijk]] on the cover of the Champions Edition.<ref name=\":1\" /> Former Real Madrid and  midfielder [[Zinedine Zidane]] was later named as the cover star for the Ultimate Edition.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Legacy Edition ===\nWhilst the Xbox One, PS4 and PC versions will have all of the new features, the Nintendo Switch version will instead be a ''Legacy Edition'', with updated kits, rosters and minor updates, but without the new ''VOLTA Football'' mode or any of the other new features.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-06-09-ea-explains-fifa-2020s-legacy-version-for-nintendo-switch|title=EA explains FIFA 2020's \"Legacy\" version for Nintendo Switch|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=9 June 2019|website=[[Eurogamer]]|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> ''FIFA 20'' was not released on [[Xbox 360]] or [[PlayStation 3]], making ''[[FIFA 19]]'' the final game in the series to be released on those platforms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/fifa-20-release-dates-price-new-features-pre-order-news/1ad4wgp9n4xw21c7fgyuqg3dmr|title=FIFA 20: Release dates, price, new features & pre-order news|last=|first=|date=30 July 2019|work=[[Goal (website)|Goal.com]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = XONE: 79/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |title=FIFA 20 for Xbox One Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/fifa-20 |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref><br />PS4: 79/100<ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web  |title=FIFA 20 for PlayStation 4 Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/fifa-20|website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref><br />NS: 43/100<ref name=\"MCNS\">{{cite web |title=FIFA 20: Legacy Edition for Switch Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/fifa-20-legacy-edition |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n| GI = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Matthew Kato |title=FIFA 20 Review \u2013 A Well-Worn Institution |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/review/fifa-20/fifa-20-review-a-well-worn-institution |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Oscar Dayus |title=FIFA 20 Review |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/fifa-20-review-premier-league/1900-6417313/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.8/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Simon Cardy |title=FIFA 20 Review |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/09/19/fifa-20-review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=26 November 2019 |date=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n| NLife = {{Rating|4|10}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Chris Scullion |title=FIFA 20 review |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/nintendo-switch/fifa_20 |website=[[Nintendo Life]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Goal (website)|Goal]]''\n| rev1Score = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Ronan Murphy |title=FIFA 20 review: Flawed release but dependable fun for football fans |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/fifa-20-review-flawed-release-but-dependable-fun-for/1rm4tkqr1o55210wxuld7t75y1 |website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Our Culture Mag]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Modestas Mankus |title=Review: FIFA 20 |url=https://ourculturemag.com/2019/10/06/review-fifa-20/ |website=[[Our Culture Mag]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Gamer Network|Push Square]]''\n| rev3Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Robert Ramsey |title=FIFA 20 Review (PS4) |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/reviews/ps4/fifa_20 |website=Push Square |accessdate=19 October 2019 |date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Talksport]]''\n| rev4Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Oliver Dawnay  |title=FIFA 20 review |url=https://talksport.com/football/608862/fifa-20-gameplay-volta-ultimate-team/ |website=[[Talksport]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[TechRadar]]''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Jordan Oloman  |title=FIFA 20 review |url=https://www.techradar.com/uk/reviews/fifa-20-review |website=[[TechRadar]] |accessdate=24 September 2019 |date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news |author=David Gorman |title=Fifa 20: Intriguing new game modes marred by shallow gameplay |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/games/game-reviews/fifa-20-intriguing-new-game-modes-marred-by-shallow-gameplay-1.4039019 |newspaper=[[The Irish Times]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''FIFA 20'' received \"generally favourable\" reviews for the PS4<ref name=\"MCPS4\"/> and Xbox One<ref name=\"MCXONE\"/> versions of the game from critics, while the Nintendo Switch version received \"generally unfavorable\" reviews from critics,<ref name=\"MCNS\"/> according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].\n\nDespite changing some of the mode's features, upon release, the game's Career Mode was criticised for being riddled with bugs including computer-controlled opposition managers picking unusually weak teams,<ref>{{cite news |author=Andrew Griffin |title=FIFA 20 PLAYERS COMPLAIN THAT MAJOR \u2018BUG\u2019 RUINS CAREER MODE |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/fifa-20-bug-career-mode-patch-feature-teams-update-a9121571.html |newspaper=[[The Independent (newspaper)|The Independent]] |accessdate=2 October 2019 |date=26 September 2019}}</ref> players changing positions seemingly at random, and unexplained ratings changes.<ref>{{cite web |author=Christopher Groux |title='FIFA 20' #FIXCAREERMODE TRENDS AMIDST BUGS & EA'S RESPONSE DISAPPOINTS |url=https://www.newsweek.com/fifa-20-fixcareermode-trend-bugs-glitch-ea-response-disappoints-1461941 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=2 October 2019 |date=28 September 2019}}</ref> The criticism has been described as \"issues that either turn its take on realism into a bit of a joke or break the game entirely\", with claims that EA is attempting to cover up or downplay the game's flaws.<ref>{{cite web |author=Liam Croft |title=EA Tries to Cover Up FIFA 20's Broken Career Mode by Deleting Forum Posts |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/ea_tries_to_cover_up_fifa_20s_broken_career_mode_by_deleting_forum_posts |website=Push Square |accessdate=5 October 2019 |date=27 September 2019}}</ref> The \"#FixCareerMode\" hashtag trended for several days on [[Twitter]] in the [[United Kingdom]], with fans hoping to draw attention to the issues in the mode.<ref>{{cite web |author=Wesley Yin-Poole |title=Why FIFA 20 #FixCareerMode is trending |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-09-27-why-fifa-20-fixcareermode-is-trending |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=2 October 2019 |date=27 September 2019}}</ref> On 16 October 2019, EA responded by releasing a new patch for the game which fixed various issues that were reported to be present.\nIn a re-review of the game by the Bleacher Report, (it originally awarded the game a 7.5/10 rating), it was described as a 'defensive borefest', going on to criticise the game as frustrating and unbalanced; citing server issues, frustrating game mechanics such as the slow communication between players and the overpowering of AI defending mechanic (a criticism shared by various players online), as well as a general lack of 'fun challenges and rewards' in the popular 'Ultimate Team' mode. Bleacher Report then gave an updated score of 6/10. This view was even shared by former world No. 1 FIFA player 'Fnatic Tekzz', who said a pro event, \"Nobody enjoys playing it.\" Many professional players online have deemed FIFA 20 as one of the most frustrating editions in the history of the franchise, citing the clunky gameplay and balancing issues. \n<ref>https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2881686-fifa-20-re-review-from-early-promise-to-defensive-borefest</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |author=Robert Ramsey |title=Huge FIFA 20 Patch 1.05 Finally Tries to Fix Career Mode, Out Now on PS4 |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/10/huge_fifa_20_patch_1_05_finally_tries_to_fix_career_mode_out_now_on_ps4 |website=Push Square |accessdate=19 October 2019 |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\nIn early October 2019, it was reported that some players' personal information was exposed to other gamers. Some players' that signed up to the Fifa 20 Global Series found a completed registration form with other people's information. The error exposed email addresses and birth dates of players. According to EA the problem affected about 1,600 people.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fifa 20 error exposes players' details |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-49933683 |website=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=5 October 2019 |date=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\" | 2019\n| [[Gamescom]]\n| Best Sports Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Mercedes Milligan |title=Gamescom Award 2019 Nominees Revealed |url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/events/gamescom-award-2019-nominees-revealed/ |website=[[Animation Magazine]] |accessdate=26 November 2019 |date=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2019 Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Stephen Tailby |title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards |website=Push Square |accessdate=26 November 2019 |date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Fun & Serious Game Festival|Titanium Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Best Sports/Racing Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |title=Titanium Awards 2019 |url=https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/ |website=[[Fun & Serious Game Festival]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121193654/https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/ |archivedate=21 November 2019 |url-status=live |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Game Awards 2019]]\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Jeremy Winslow |title=The Game Awards 2019 Nominees Full List |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-nominees-full-list/1100-6471564/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=26 November 2019 |date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2020\n| [[Guild of Music Supervisors Awards]]\n| Best Music Supervision in a Video Game\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Shirley Halperin |title=\u2018Euphoria,\u2019 \u2018Marvelous Mrs. Maisel\u2019 Among Guild of Music Supervisors Awards Nominees |url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/guild-of-music-supervisors-awards-nominees-nominations-full-list-1203461469/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=17 January 2020 |date=9 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=James Patrick Herman |title=Guild of Music Supervisors Awards: Regina Spektor, \u2018Euphoria\u2019 Among Winners (Full List) |url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/guild-of-music-supervisors-awards-winners-full-list-1203496186/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=7 February 2020 |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[23rd Annual D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Sports Game of the Year\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Andy Chalk |title=Control and Death Stranding get 8 nominations each for the 2020 DICE Awards |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/control-and-death-stranding-get-eight-nominations-each-for-the-2020-dice-awards/ |website=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=17 January 2020 |date=13 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Eric Van Allen |title=Untitled Goose Game Wins Top Bill at the 2020 D.I.C.E. Awards |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/untitled-goose-game-wins-top-bill-at-the-2020-dice-awards |website=[[Eurogamer|USgamer]] |accessdate=14 February 2020 |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[NAVGTR Awards]]\n| Game, Franchise Sports\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |title=2019 Nominees |url=https://navgtr.org/2019-nominees/ |website=[[NAVGTR Awards|National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] |accessdate=19 January 2020 |date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.ea.com/games/fifa/fifa-20 Official website]\n\n{{Football video games by Electronic Arts}}\n\n[[Category:2019 video games]]\n[[Category:Association football video games]]\n[[Category:Women's association football video games]]\n[[Category:EA Sports games]]\n[[Category:FIFA (video game series)]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Romania]]\n[[Category:Video games that support DirectX 12]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Frostbite (game engine) games]]\n[[Category:Sports video games with career mode]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Piemonte Calcio|a defunct Italian football club|Piemonte F.C.|the club Piemonte Calcio is based on|Juventus}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = FIFA 20\n| image = FIFA 20 Standard Edition Cover.jpg\n| caption = {{Nowrap|[[PS4]] cover art featuring [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid\u2019s]] [[Eden Hazard]]}}\n| developer = [[EA Vancouver]]<br/>[[Electronic Arts#Studios|EA Romania]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.ea.com/games/fifa/fifa-20 | title=FIFA 20 - Soccer Video Game | website=EA.com | accessdate=2019-06-19| date=20 September 2018 }}</ref>\n| publisher = [[EA Sports]]\n| composer = Nafrom\n| series = [[FIFA (video game series)|''FIFA'']]\n| engine = [[Frostbite (game engine)|Frostbite 3]]\n| platforms = {{ubl|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| released = 27 September 2019\n| genre = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''FIFA 20''''' is a [[association football|football]] [[simulation video game|simulation]] [[video game]] published by [[Electronic Arts]] as part of the ''[[FIFA (video game series)|FIFA series]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/e3-2019-star-wars-jedi-fallen-order-apex-legends-fifa-20-the-sims-4-and-everything-announced-at-ea-play/|title=E3 2019: Star Wars Jedi: Fallen Order, Apex Legends, The Sims 4 and everything announced at EA Play|last=Sherr|first=Ian|date=8 June 2019|work=[[CNET]]|access-date=31 July 2019|last2=Serrels|first2=Mark}}</ref> It is the 27th installment in the ''FIFA'' series, and was released on 27 September 2019 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], and [[Nintendo Switch]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2019-fifa-20-announced-with-release-date-volta-/1100-6467435/|title=E3 2019: FIFA 20 Announced With Release Date, Volta Mode|last=Dayus|first=Oscar|date=12 June 2019|work=[[GameSpot]]|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>    \n\n[[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] winger [[Eden Hazard]] was named the new cover star of the Regular Edition, with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] defender [[Virgil van Dijk]] on the cover of the Champions Edition.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/fifa-20-cover-stars-are-eden-hazard-and-virgil-van-dijk|title=FIFA 20 cover stars are Eden Hazard and Virgil Van Dijk|last=Donovan|first=Imogen|date=29 July 2019|work=VideoGamer|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> Former [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] and Real Madrid midfielder [[Zinedine Zidane]] was later named as the cover star for the Ultimate Edition.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/7/fifa-20-zinedine-zidane-ultimate-edition-cover-fut-icon|title=Zinedine Zidane to Cover 'FIFA 20 Ultimate Edition'|last=Stanley|first=Jack|date=30 July 2019|work=HYPEBEAST|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe game features ''VOLTA'' ''Football'' for the first time, a new mode that provides a variance on the traditional 11v11 gameplay and focuses on small-sided [[Street football|street]] and [[futsal]] games.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-06-08-confirmed-fifa-20-has-a-fifa-street-mode-called-volta-football|title=Confirmed: FIFA 20 has a FIFA Street mode called Volta Football|last=Yin-Poole|first=Wesley|date=8 June 2019|work=[[Eurogamer]]|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> The mode is believed to be focused on the former [[FIFA Street (2005 video game)|''FIFA Street'']] series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/fifa-20-has-a-fifa-street-style-mode-called-volta-ea-confirms/|title=FIFA 20 has a FIFA Street-style mode called Volta, EA confirms|last=Horti|first=Samuel|date=8 June 2019|work=[[PC Gamer]]|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Features == \nGameplay changes to ''FIFA 20'' focus primarily on a new feature titled ''VOLTA Football''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gfinityesports.com/article/2057/fifa-20-volta-football-gameplay-information-volta-story-mode-customisation-and-more-from-ea-sports-new-game|title=FIFA 20: VOLTA Football Gameplay Information, Volta Story Mode, Customisation And More From EA Sports New Game|last=Trout|first=Chris|date=8 August 2019|work=[[Gfinity|Gfinity Esports]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> The mode, which translates to 'return' in Portuguese, focuses on street football rather than the traditional matches associated with the FIFA series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/volta-the-return-of-fifa-street-why-ea-is-bringing-back/ex4l81kxxtc412dv0sqc5e70q|title=Volta: The return of FIFA Street & why EA is bringing back iconic game mode for FIFA 20|last=Thomas|first=Josh|date=6 August 2019|work=[[Goal (website)|Goal.com]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> It includes several options to play in three versus three, four versus four and five versus five matches, as well as with professional [[futsal]] rules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.futsalfocus.net/volta-football-futsal-ea-sports/|title=Futsal included in the new Volta Football by EA Sports|date=9 June 2019|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref> The mode will incorporate the same engine, but places emphasis on skill and independent play rather than tactical or team play.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/fifa-20-street-mode-volta-football-ps4-xbox-features-update-latest-a9047101.html|title=Fifa Street is back \u2013 here\u2019s what it looks like|date=8 August 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, players have the option to customise their player by gender, clothing, shoes, hats and tattoos.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.futuregamereleases.com/2019/06/fifa-20-volta-football-is-taking-the-fun-to-the-streets/|title=FIFA 20 Volta Football is taking the fun to the streets|last=Goodwin|first=David|date=8 June 2019|work=Future Game Releases|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Following the completion of the three-part series ''\"The Journey\"'' in ''[[FIFA 19]]'', players can now have a similar storyline mode in ''VOLTA Football'', which would be played with the player's own character.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nChanges were also made to the traditional 11 versus 11 mode to encourage more one-on-ones and off-the-ball space creation. New penalty and free-kick mechanics were implemented and updates were made to the ball physics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2019/06/fifa-20-trailer-volta-football-street|title=Here's the First FIFA 20 Trailer and Details on 'Volta Football' Street Mode|last=Segev|first=Tom|date=10 June 2019|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nVOLTA Football includes 17 locations, with each providing a unique experience. As well as a generic warehouse and parking lot, players can also compete in [[Amsterdam]], [[Barcelona]], [[Berlin]], [[Buenos Aires]], [[Cape Town]], [[Lagos]], [[London]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Mexico City]], [[Miami]], [[New York City]], [[Paris]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Rome]] and [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/gaming/volta-football-fifa-20-news-16722870|title=Fifa 20: Volta Football latest including skill moves, story mode, locations and customisation|last=Bliss|first=Nathan|date=27 August 2019|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nCommentary is once again provided by [[Martin Tyler]] and [[Alan Smith (footballer, born 1962)|Alan Smith]] and alternating with [[Derek Rae]] and [[Lee Dixon]] for all competitions, with [[Alan McInally]] providing in-game score updates. \n\n=== Pro Clubs ===\n\nPro clubs is a game mode in FIFA 20 where players can create personalised pros and compete in a squad against other squads online. The objective is to rise up the Divisions, starting in Division 10 and climbing to compete for the Division 1 title.\n\n=== Ultimate Team ===\nUltimate Team features 88 icon players, including 15 new names. [[Carlos Alberto Torres|Carlos Alberto]], [[John Barnes (footballer)|John Barnes]], [[Kenny Dalglish]], [[Didier Drogba]], [[Michael Essien]], [[Garrincha]], [[Pep Guardiola]], [[Kak\u00e1]], [[Ronald Koeman]], [[Andrea Pirlo]], [[Ian Rush]], [[Hugo S\u00e1nchez]], [[Ian Wright]], [[Gianluca Zambrotta]] and [[Zinedine Zidane]] all feature as icons for the first time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6423022-fifa-20-ultimate-team-to-include-brand-new-icons-including-ian-wright-andrea-pirlo-didier-drogba|title=FIFA 20: Ultimate Team to Include Brand New Icons Including Ian Wright, Andrea Pirlo & Didier Drogba|last=Gott|first=Tom|date=31 July 2019|work=90min|access-date=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo new game modes \u2013 King of the Hill and Mystery Ball \u2013 are also incorporated in Ultimate Team following their previous inclusion in kick-off mode.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gfinityesports.com/article/2033/breaking-fifa-20-ultimate-team-new-house-rules-fut-friendlies-icons-king-of-the-hill-mystery-ball-and-more-revealed-by-ea|title=FIFA 20 Ultimate Team: New House rules, FUT Friendlies, ICONS, King of the Hill, Mystery Ball, and more revealed by EA|last=Pusinelli|first=Alastair|date=31 July 2019|work=[[Gfinity|Gfinity Esports]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Mystery Ball gives the attacking side boosts to passing, shooting, dribbling, speed or all attributes, adding unpredictability to every match.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://realsport101.com/fifa/fifa-20-ultimate-team-what-is-the-new-mystery-ball-mode-fut-friendlies-house-rules-kick-off-cover-star-release-demo/|title=FIFA 20 Ultimate Team: What is the new Mystery Ball mode?|last=Pusinelli|first=Alastair|date=1 August 2019|work=RealSport|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> King of the Hill sees players fight for possession in a randomly generated zone on the pitch to boost the amount the next goal is worth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://realsport101.com/fifa/fifa-20-ultimate-team-house-rules-fut-friendlies-king-of-the-hill-mysteryball/|title=FIFA 20 Ultimate Team: New House rules, FUT Friendlies, ICONS, King of the Hill, Mystery Ball, and more revealed by EA|last=Musa|first=Talal|date=31 July 2019|work=RealSport|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Ultimate Team also includes a new dedicated kit supporting Premier League's no room for racism campaign.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://copa90.com/en/fifa20/ea-launches-no-room-for-racism-kit|title=FIFA20: EA SPORTS Launches New No Room For Racism Kit |accessdate=23 October 2019|website=Copa90}}</ref>\n\n=== Career Mode ===\nCareer Mode, following feedback from the community, saw some major updates - mainly to the manager mode.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thesixthaxis.com/2019/08/07/fifa-20s-career-mode-football-manager/|title=FIFA 20's Career Mode will have some major changes|last=Suddi|first=Aran|date=7 August 2019|work=The Sixth Axis|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> New additions include fully interactive press conferences and player conversations, an improved player morale system which can affect the team or individual players stats, performance levels and stance with the manager. The ability to fully customise the manager\u2019s appearance and gender, a new dynamic player potential system, live news screenshots, league oriented UI and new negotiation environments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ea.com/en-gb/games/fifa/fifa-20/news/pitch-notes-fifa-20-career-mode-deep-dive|title=Pitch Notes \u2013 FIFA 20 Career Mode Deep Dive|last=|first=|date=10 July 2019|website=[[EA Sports|EA Sports FIFA]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Licenses ===\nThe game will feature more than 30 official leagues, over 700 clubs and over 17,000 players. Included for the first time is the Romanian [[Liga I]] and its 14 teams, as well as [[United Arab Emirates|Emirati]] club [[Al Ain FC|Al Ain]], who were added following extensive requests from the fans in the region.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://realsport101.com/fifa/fifa-20-new-league-finally-announced-as-ea-fight-back-at-pes-2020-release-date-demo-beta-career-mode-ultimate-team-fut-online-cover-star/|title=FIFA 20: New league finally announced as EA fight back at PES 2020|last=Pusinelli|first=Alastair|date=27 August 2019|work=RealSport|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395302780414|title=UAE's Al Ain FC sets sights on EA SPORTS FIFA 20 Debut|last=|first=|date=18 August 2019|work=Emirates News Agency|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nJuventus, Boca Juniors and River Plate are not featured after they signed exclusive partnership deals with ''[[eFootball Pro Evolution Soccer 2020|eFootball PES 2020]],'' and instead are known as Piemonte Calcio, Buenos Aires and N\u00fa\u00f1ez.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-49008496|title=Juventus to be called Piemonte Calcio in Fifa after PES deal|last=Gerken|first=Tom|date=16 July 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> The game would retain the players' likenesses, but the official badge and kits will be unavailable and instead feature custom designs produced by EA Sports and also lose their stadium licenses like the [[Juventus Stadium]], [[La Bombonera]] and [[El Monumental]]. [[Bayern Munich]] is featured in the game with their licensed players and kits but without their home stadium the [[Allianz Arena]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.futhead.com/news/fifa-20/2163/fut-20-juventus-pes-ea-loses-licensing/|title=Juventus is Piemonte Calcio: FIFA 20 won't have Juve's name, kit, badge|last=Zimmermann|first=Luke|date=16 July 2019|work=Futhead|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n''FIFA 20'' will retain the exclusive licenses to the [[UEFA Champions League]], [[UEFA Europa League]], and [[UEFA Super Cup]] first seen in ''FIFA 19''. The deal includes authentic broadcast packages, branding, and custom commentary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ea.com/games/fifa/fifa-20/leagues-and-clubs-authenticity|title=FIFA 20 Exclusive Licenses \u2013 All Leagues and Clubs|last=|first=|date=30 July 2019|website=[[EA Sports|EA Sports FIFA]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Additionally, the [[Copa Libertadores]], [[Copa Sudamericana]] and the [[Recopa Sudamericana]] is featured in the game via an update released on 13 March 2020.<ref> https://www.ea.com/games/fifa/fifa-20/conmebol-libertadores/</ref>\n\n=== Stadiums ===\nThere are 92 fully licensed stadiums from 15 countries in ''FIFA 20'', as well as 29 generic stadiums.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifauteam.com/fifa-20-stadiums/|title=FIFA 20 Stadiums|last=|first=|date=|website=FIFA U Team|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> [[Bramall Lane]] has been included following [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]'s promotion, ensuring that all [[Premier League]] teams have their respective stadiums.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/latest-blades-news/sheffield-united-this-is-what-bramall-lane-looks-like-on-fifa-20-as-blades-stadium-features-on-game-for-first-time-following-promotion-to-premier-league-492135|title=Sheffield United: THIS is what Bramall Lane looks like on FIFA 20 as Blades' stadium features on game for first time following promotion to Premier League|last=Hall|first=Danny|date=25 August 2019|work=[[Sheffield Star|The Star]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Three new Spanish stadiums have also been added \u2013 [[Estadio El Alcoraz]] (home of [[SD Huesca]]), [[Campo de F\u00fatbol de Vallecas|Estadio De Vallecas]] (home of [[Rayo Vallecano]]) and [[Estadio Jos\u00e9 Zorrilla]] (home of [[Real Valladolid]]).<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAs part of an extensive new licensing deal, 13 new stadiums across the [[Bundesliga]] and [[2. Bundesliga]] will be included. These include [[BayArena]] (home of [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen]]), [[Mercedes-Benz Arena (Stuttgart)|Mercedes-Benz Arena]] (home of [[VfB Stuttgart]]), [[Red Bull Arena (Leipzig)|Red Bull Arena]] (home of [[RB Leipzig]]) and [[Volkswagen Arena]] (home of [[VfL Wolfsburg]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/uk/fifa-20-bundesliga/|title=FIFA 20 Bundesliga tie-in adds 180 player faces and 13 new stadiums|last=Wilson|first=Ben|date=20 August 2019|work=[[GamesRadar+]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> Also added into the game is the [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais|Groupama Stadium]], home of [[Olympique Lyonnais]] in [[Ligue 1]]; [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]], home of [[New York Red Bulls]] in [[Major League Soccer]]; as well as the [[2020 UEFA Champions League Final]] venue [[Atat\u00fcrk Olympic Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.vgr.com/new-fifa-20-stadiums-champions-league-venue-ataturk-olympic-stadium/4 |title= New FIFA 20 Stadiums Revealed Including Champions League Venue Ataturk Olympic Stadium |last= Couden |first= Matt |date= 18 September 2019 |website= VGR.com|access-date= 20 October 2019}}</ref>\n2 new stadiums were added in 2020 when the [[Copa Libertadores]] was released in March. The stadium [[Estadio Libertadores de Am\u00e9rica]] of the Argentinian club [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Independiente]] is now available, as well as the stadium [[Estadio Presidente Juan Domingo Per\u00f3n]] of the Argentinian club [[Racing Club de Avellaneda]]<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ea.com/en-gb/games/fifa/fifa-20/conmebol-libertadores?utm_campaign=fifa20_hd_ww_ic_soco_twt_fifa20-copa-tw-2192020&utm_source=twitter&utm_medium=social&cid=62570&ts=1582210710811 |title= CONMEBOL LIBERTADORES |website= EA.com|access-date= 3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n\n=== Demo/EA Access ===\nThe FIFA 20 demo was released on 10 September 2019 and includes 6 playable teams which can be played on the UEFA Champions League kick-off mode \u2013 [[Borussia Dortmund]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]],  [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]], [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/fifa-20-demo-release-date-time-and-how-to-play-now-on-ps4-pc-and-xbox-one|title=FIFA 20 demo: release date, time and how to play now on PS4, PC and Xbox One|last=Hood|first=Vic|date=10 September 2019|work=Techradar|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> and a demo of the new ''VOLTA Football'' mode.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportbible.com/football/gaming-news-take-a-bow-fifa-20-demo-to-be-released-on-september-12-teams-revealed-20190829|title=FIFA 20 Demo To Be Released On September 12: Game Modes, Playable Teams Leaked|last=Kenmare|first=Jack|date=29 August 2019|work=[[LADbible|Sport Bible]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> The demo is available for [[PS4]], [[Xbox One]] and PC.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.thesixthaxis.com/2019/09/10/fifa-20-demo-download-link-ps4-xb1-pc/|title=The FIFA 20 demo is now out, download link here|accessdate=10 September 2019|website=tsa}}</ref>\n\nThe game was released through the [[EA Access]] subscription on 24 September 2019, which also offers a free 10 hour trial.\n\n=== Covers ===\n''FIFA 20'' features three cover stars across all regional editions. [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] winger [[Eden Hazard]] was named the new cover star of the Regular Edition, with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] defender [[Virgil van Dijk]] on the cover of the Champions Edition.<ref name=\":1\" /> Former Real Madrid and  midfielder [[Zinedine Zidane]] was later named as the cover star for the Ultimate Edition.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Legacy Edition ===\nWhilst the Xbox One, PS4 and PC versions will have all of the new features, the Nintendo Switch version will instead be a ''Legacy Edition'', with updated kits, rosters and minor updates, but without the new ''VOLTA Football'' mode or any of the other new features.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-06-09-ea-explains-fifa-2020s-legacy-version-for-nintendo-switch|title=EA explains FIFA 2020's \"Legacy\" version for Nintendo Switch|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=9 June 2019|website=[[Eurogamer]]|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> ''FIFA 20'' was not released on [[Xbox 360]] or [[PlayStation 3]], making ''[[FIFA 19]]'' the final game in the series to be released on those platforms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/fifa-20-release-dates-price-new-features-pre-order-news/1ad4wgp9n4xw21c7fgyuqg3dmr|title=FIFA 20: Release dates, price, new features & pre-order news|last=|first=|date=30 July 2019|work=[[Goal (website)|Goal.com]]|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = XONE: 79/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |title=FIFA 20 for Xbox One Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/fifa-20 |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref><br />PS4: 79/100<ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web  |title=FIFA 20 for PlayStation 4 Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/fifa-20|website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref><br />NS: 43/100<ref name=\"MCNS\">{{cite web |title=FIFA 20: Legacy Edition for Switch Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/fifa-20-legacy-edition |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n| GI = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Matthew Kato |title=FIFA 20 Review \u2013 A Well-Worn Institution |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/review/fifa-20/fifa-20-review-a-well-worn-institution |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Oscar Dayus |title=FIFA 20 Review |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/fifa-20-review-premier-league/1900-6417313/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.8/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Simon Cardy |title=FIFA 20 Review |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/09/19/fifa-20-review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=26 November 2019 |date=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n| NLife = {{Rating|4|10}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Chris Scullion |title=FIFA 20 review |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/nintendo-switch/fifa_20 |website=[[Nintendo Life]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Goal (website)|Goal]]''\n| rev1Score = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Ronan Murphy |title=FIFA 20 review: Flawed release but dependable fun for football fans |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/fifa-20-review-flawed-release-but-dependable-fun-for/1rm4tkqr1o55210wxuld7t75y1 |website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Our Culture Mag]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Modestas Mankus |title=Review: FIFA 20 |url=https://ourculturemag.com/2019/10/06/review-fifa-20/ |website=[[Our Culture Mag]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Gamer Network|Push Square]]''\n| rev3Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web |author=Robert Ramsey |title=FIFA 20 Review (PS4) |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/reviews/ps4/fifa_20 |website=Push Square |accessdate=19 October 2019 |date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Talksport]]''\n| rev4Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Oliver Dawnay  |title=FIFA 20 review |url=https://talksport.com/football/608862/fifa-20-gameplay-volta-ultimate-team/ |website=[[Talksport]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[TechRadar]]''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Jordan Oloman  |title=FIFA 20 review |url=https://www.techradar.com/uk/reviews/fifa-20-review |website=[[TechRadar]] |accessdate=24 September 2019 |date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news |author=David Gorman |title=Fifa 20: Intriguing new game modes marred by shallow gameplay |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/games/game-reviews/fifa-20-intriguing-new-game-modes-marred-by-shallow-gameplay-1.4039019 |newspaper=[[The Irish Times]] |accessdate=18 October 2019 |date=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''FIFA 20'' received \"generally favourable\" reviews for the PS4<ref name=\"MCPS4\"/> and Xbox One<ref name=\"MCXONE\"/> versions of the game from critics, while the Nintendo Switch version received \"generally unfavorable\" reviews from critics,<ref name=\"MCNS\"/> according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].\n\nDespite changing some of the mode's features, upon release, the game's Career Mode was criticised for being riddled with bugs including computer-controlled opposition managers picking unusually weak teams,<ref>{{cite news |author=Andrew Griffin |title=FIFA 20 PLAYERS COMPLAIN THAT MAJOR \u2018BUG\u2019 RUINS CAREER MODE |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/fifa-20-bug-career-mode-patch-feature-teams-update-a9121571.html |newspaper=[[The Independent (newspaper)|The Independent]] |accessdate=2 October 2019 |date=26 September 2019}}</ref> players changing positions seemingly at random, and unexplained ratings changes.<ref>{{cite web |author=Christopher Groux |title='FIFA 20' #FIXCAREERMODE TRENDS AMIDST BUGS & EA'S RESPONSE DISAPPOINTS |url=https://www.newsweek.com/fifa-20-fixcareermode-trend-bugs-glitch-ea-response-disappoints-1461941 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=2 October 2019 |date=28 September 2019}}</ref> The criticism has been described as \"issues that either turn its take on realism into a bit of a joke or break the game entirely\", with claims that EA is attempting to cover up or downplay the game's flaws.<ref>{{cite web |author=Liam Croft |title=EA Tries to Cover Up FIFA 20's Broken Career Mode by Deleting Forum Posts |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/ea_tries_to_cover_up_fifa_20s_broken_career_mode_by_deleting_forum_posts |website=Push Square |accessdate=5 October 2019 |date=27 September 2019}}</ref> The \"#FixCareerMode\" hashtag trended for several days on [[Twitter]] in the [[United Kingdom]], with fans hoping to draw attention to the issues in the mode.<ref>{{cite web |author=Wesley Yin-Poole |title=Why FIFA 20 #FixCareerMode is trending |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-09-27-why-fifa-20-fixcareermode-is-trending |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=2 October 2019 |date=27 September 2019}}</ref> On 16 October 2019, EA responded by releasing a new patch for the game which fixed various issues that were reported to be present.\nIn a re-review of the game by the Bleacher Report, (it originally awarded the game a 7.5/10 rating), it was described as a 'defensive borefest', going on to criticise the game as frustrating and unbalanced; citing server issues, frustrating game mechanics such as the slow communication between players and the overpowering of AI defending mechanic (a criticism shared by various players online), as well as a general lack of 'fun challenges and rewards' in the popular 'Ultimate Team' mode. Bleacher Report then gave an updated score of 6/10. This view was even shared by former world No. 1 FIFA player 'Fnatic Tekzz', who said a pro event, \"Nobody enjoys playing it.\" Many professional players online have deemed FIFA 20 as one of the most frustrating editions in the history of the franchise, citing the clunky gameplay and balancing issues. \n<ref>https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2881686-fifa-20-re-review-from-early-promise-to-defensive-borefest</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |author=Robert Ramsey |title=Huge FIFA 20 Patch 1.05 Finally Tries to Fix Career Mode, Out Now on PS4 |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/10/huge_fifa_20_patch_1_05_finally_tries_to_fix_career_mode_out_now_on_ps4 |website=Push Square |accessdate=19 October 2019 |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\nIn early October 2019, it was reported that some players' personal information was exposed to other gamers. Some players' that signed up to the Fifa 20 Global Series found a completed registration form with other people's information. The error exposed email addresses and birth dates of players. According to EA the problem affected about 1,600 people.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fifa 20 error exposes players' details |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-49933683 |website=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=5 October 2019 |date=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\" | 2019\n| [[Gamescom]]\n| Best Sports Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Mercedes Milligan |title=Gamescom Award 2019 Nominees Revealed |url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/events/gamescom-award-2019-nominees-revealed/ |website=[[Animation Magazine]] |accessdate=26 November 2019 |date=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2019 Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Stephen Tailby |title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards |website=Push Square |accessdate=26 November 2019 |date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Fun & Serious Game Festival|Titanium Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Best Sports/Racing Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |title=Titanium Awards 2019 |url=https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/ |website=[[Fun & Serious Game Festival]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121193654/https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/ |archivedate=21 November 2019 |url-status=live |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Game Awards 2019]]\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Jeremy Winslow |title=The Game Awards 2019 Nominees Full List |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-nominees-full-list/1100-6471564/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=26 November 2019 |date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2020\n| [[Guild of Music Supervisors Awards]]\n| Best Music Supervision in a Video Game\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Shirley Halperin |title=\u2018Euphoria,\u2019 \u2018Marvelous Mrs. Maisel\u2019 Among Guild of Music Supervisors Awards Nominees |url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/guild-of-music-supervisors-awards-nominees-nominations-full-list-1203461469/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=17 January 2020 |date=9 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=James Patrick Herman |title=Guild of Music Supervisors Awards: Regina Spektor, \u2018Euphoria\u2019 Among Winners (Full List) |url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/guild-of-music-supervisors-awards-winners-full-list-1203496186/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=7 February 2020 |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[23rd Annual D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Sports Game of the Year\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Andy Chalk |title=Control and Death Stranding get 8 nominations each for the 2020 DICE Awards |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/control-and-death-stranding-get-eight-nominations-each-for-the-2020-dice-awards/ |website=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=17 January 2020 |date=13 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Eric Van Allen |title=Untitled Goose Game Wins Top Bill at the 2020 D.I.C.E. Awards |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/untitled-goose-game-wins-top-bill-at-the-2020-dice-awards |website=[[Eurogamer|USgamer]] |accessdate=14 February 2020 |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[NAVGTR Awards]]\n| Game, Franchise Sports\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |title=2019 Nominees |url=https://navgtr.org/2019-nominees/ |website=[[NAVGTR Awards|National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] |accessdate=19 January 2020 |date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.ea.com/games/fifa/fifa-20 Official website]\n\n{{Football video games by Electronic Arts}}\n\n[[Category:2019 video games]]\n[[Category:Association football video games]]\n[[Category:Women's association football video games]]\n[[Category:EA Sports games]]\n[[Category:FIFA (video game series)]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Romania]]\n[[Category:Video games that support DirectX 12]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Frostbite (game engine) games]]\n[[Category:Sports video games with career mode]]\n", "name_user": "Tomh2004", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIFA_20"}
{"title_page": "George Cockings", "text_new": "'''George Cockings''' (died 6 February 1802) was an English writer.\n\n==Career==\nCockings began his professional career working for the British government in [[Boston]], USA. On his return to [[England]], he became the registrar of the Society of Arts, Manufactures, and Commerce at [[Adelphi, London#Adelphi Buildings|the Adelphi]]. He died on 6 February 1802, after holding that post for thirty years. {{sfn|Knight|1887}}\n\nHis American experiences led him to write poems and dramas, \"which, in respect of construction and literary style, are of the feeblest order.\"{{sfn|Knight|1887}} Some of these obtained a measure of success, and went through three or four editions in America and England. {{sfn|Knight|1887}}\n\nHis writings include ''The Conquest of Canada, or the Siege of Quebec'' (1766)'' ''an historical tragedy in five acts \"a contemptible production without either form or significance;\"{{sfn|Knight|1887}} \"Benevolence and Gratitude\", a poem, London (1772), \"War, an Heroic Poem, from the Taking of Minorca by the French to the Reduction of the Havannah\", a 28-page poem supporting British generals (1760),<ref name=dbcal>Burt, Daniel S., [https://books.google.com/books?id=VQ0fgo5v6e0C ''The Chronology of American Literature: America's literary achievements from the colonial era to modern times''], [[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]], 2004, {{ISBN|978-0-618-16821-7}}, retrieved via Google Books</ref> ''Poems on several Subjects,'' London (1772), \"Arts, Manufactures, and Commerce\" a poem, London (1766).{{sfn|Knight|1887}}\n''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Cockings, George|first=John Joseph|last=Knight|authorlink=Joseph Knight (critic)|volume=11}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cockings, George}}\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1802 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century English poets]]\n\n\n{{England-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''George Cockings''' (died 6 February 1802) was an English writer.\n\n==Career==\nCockings began his professional career working for the British government in [[Boston]], USA. On his return to [[England]], he became the registrar of the Society of Arts, Manufactures, and Commerce at [[Adelphi, London#Adelphi Buildings|the Adelphi]]. He died on 6 February 1802, after holding that post for thirty years. {{sfn|Knight|1887}}\n\nHis American experiences led him to write poems and dramas, \"which, in respect of construction and literary style, are of the feeblest order.\"{{sfn|Knight|1887}} Some of these obtained a measure of success, and went through three or four editions in America and England. {{sfn|Knight|1887}}\n\nHis writings include ''The Conquest of Canada, or the Siege of Quebec'' (1766)'' ''an historical tragedy in five acts \"a contemptible production without either form or significance;\"{{sfn|Knight|1887}} \"Benevolence and Gratitude\", a poem, London (1772), \"War, an Heroic Poem, from the Taking of Minorca by the French to the Reduction of the Havannah\", a 28-page poem supporting British generals (1760),<ref name=dbcal>Burt, Daniel S., [https://books.google.com/books?id=VQ0fgo5v6e0C ''The Chronology of American Literature: America's literary achievements from the colonial era to modern times''], [[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]], 2004, {{ISBN|978-0-618-16821-7}}, retrieved via Google Books</ref> ''Poems on several Subjects,'' London (1772), \"Arts, Manufactures, and Commerce\" a poem, London (1766).{{sfn|Knight|1887}}\n''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Cockings, George|first=John Joseph|last=Knight|authorlink=Joseph Knight (critic)|volume=11}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cockings, George}}\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1802 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century English poets]]\n\n\n{{England-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Cockings"}
{"title_page": "Jim Frey", "text_new": "{{About|the [[Major League Baseball]] [[manager (baseball)|manager]]|the author of [[A Million Little Pieces]]|James Frey|other people of this name|James Frey (disambiguation)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2014}}\n{{More footnotes|date=December 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Jim Frey\n|image= Jim Frey (manager) - Kansas City Royals.jpg\n|caption= Frey in 1980\n|position=[[Manager (baseball)|Manager]] \n|bats=Left\n|throws=Left\n|birth_date={{birth date|1931|5|26}}\n|birth_place=[[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2020|4|12|1931|5|26}}\n|teams=\n'''As Manager'''\n*[[Kansas City Royals]] (1980\u20131981)\n*[[Chicago Cubs]] (1984\u20131986)\n}}\n\n'''James Gottfried Frey''' (May 26, 1931 - April 14, 2020) was a former [[manager (baseball)|manager]] and [[coach (baseball)|coach]] in [[Major League Baseball]]. He led the [[Kansas City Royals]] to their first [[American League]] championship in 1980, in his first year with the team. In the [[1980 World Series|World Series]], they lost to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]], who won their first [[World Series]] championship.\n\n==Early career==\nFrey, a lifelong friend of [[Don Zimmer]] (they were teammates at [[Western Hills High School (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Western Hills High School]] in [[Cincinnati]]), never reached the major leagues as a player. A left-handed-batting and -throwing outfielder, he spent much of his career in the [[farm system]]s of the [[History of the Boston Braves|Boston/Milwaukee Braves]] and the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], then joined the [[Baltimore Orioles]] as a [[scout (sports)|scout]] and [[minor league baseball|minor league]] manager. He was promoted to the Orioles' coaching staff under [[Earl Weaver]] in [[1970 in baseball|1970]], and coached on three [[American League]] pennant winners and one [[1970 World Series|World Series]] champion through [[1979 in baseball|1979]] before his hiring by the Royals.\n\n==Kansas City Royals==\nA week after the end of the [[1979 World Series]] on October 24, Frey was named to succeed [[Whitey Herzog]] as manager of the Kansas City Royals.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1928&dat=19791023&id=nGEgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xWUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1241,5249849&hl=en \"Jim Frey Signs Year Contract To Manage Royals,\" ''The Associated Press'', Thursday, October 25, 1979.]</ref> He led the Royals to a 97-65 mark and the [[American League West Division]] title in 1980; then, in the [[1980 American League Championship Series]], the Royals defeated their long-time postseason nemesis, the [[New York Yankees]] in three straight games to capture the AL title. (The Yanks had defeated [[Whitey Herzog]]'s Royals for three consecutive seasons (1976\u201378) in the ALCS). But Frey's Royals dropped the [[1980 World Series|World Series]] to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] in six games.\n\nDuring the [[1981 Major League Baseball strike|strike-marred 1981 season]] in which the Royals finished the first half with a 20&ndash;30 record, Frey was criticized widely for not taking full advantage of a team built for speed and for failing to motivate his players by Kansas City vice president/general manager [[Joe Burke (baseball)|Joe Burke]]. Frey was relieved of his duties on August 31 despite the 10&ndash;10 ballclub leading the second-half [[American League West]] standings. His replacement was [[Dick Howser]] who had lost his managerial job with the Yankees after the previous year's ALCS. Frey's record in just less than two seasons as Royals manager was 127&ndash;105.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1981/09/01/royals-fire-frey-hire-howser-to-manage-club/309e2e68-178d-40a6-8dca-cb0c8948f709/ Dougherty, Kerry. \"Royals Fire Frey, Hire Howser to Manage Club,\" ''The Washington Post'', Tuesday, September 1, 1981]</ref>\n\n==Chicago Cubs==\nFrey then returned to the coaching ranks with the [[New York Mets]] for 1982\u201383. Frey was hired by the [[Chicago Cubs]] for the 1984 season, and again struck paydirt as the Cubs won the division title, earning their first post-season appearance since [[1945 World Series|1945]].  During the clubhouse celebration following the division-clinching in [[Pittsburgh Pirates|Pittsburgh]], Frey declared, \"The monkey's off our back!\"\n\nThe Cubs won the first two games against the San Diego Padres in the [[National League Championship Series]] at [[Wrigley Field]], before they went to San Diego needing to win just one of the next three games. The Cubs lost the next three games, and many critics blamed Frey for mishandling the pitching staff. Still, the 1984 Cubs are revered among Cubs fans.\n\nAfter a trying 1985 season in which the entire five-man starting rotation simultaneously spent time on the disabled list, the Cubs sputtered in 1986. Frey was fired two months into the season and replaced by [[John Vukovich]]. The next year, Frey surfaced as a color commentator on the Cubs' WGN Radio broadcasts.\n\nIn December 1987, the Tribune Co. hired Frey to replace his old boss, general manager [[Dallas Green (baseball)|Dallas Green]], who had resigned two months earlier. Frey hired his lifelong friend, Zimmer, to manage the team, and immediately made his presence felt. Within weeks of his hire, he dealt relief pitcher [[Lee Smith (baseball)|Lee Smith]] to Boston for journeyman [[Al Nipper]] and [[Calvin Schiraldi]], who was best known for playing a part in the Red Sox' [[1986 World Series]] collapse. Frey also traded the popular [[Keith Moreland]] to San Diego for closer [[Goose Gossage]], who had played a big part on the San Diego team that eliminated the Cubs four years earlier. Neither move worked, and the Cubs were without a closer.\n\nSo Frey made a bold move in the winter of 1988, trading budding star [[Rafael Palmeiro]] and young pitcher [[Jamie Moyer]] to the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] for a number of players, including [[Mitch Williams (baseball)|Mitch Williams]]. The trade paid off for the Cubs in 1989 as Williams saved 36 games, the Cubs won a division title and Moyer and Palmeiro struggled in Texas. But Williams had just one more forgettable year for the Cubs before being traded to Philadelphia in 1991, and Palmeiro and Moyer went on to have productive careers.\n\nAfter a disappointing 1990 season, Frey was active on the free agent market, acquiring former Toronto Blue Jay and 1987 American League MVP [[George Bell (outfielder)|George Bell]], former Cincinnati Reds starting pitcher [[Danny Jackson]] and former [[Houston Astros]] closer [[Dave Smith (NL pitcher)|Dave Smith]]. Jackson and Smith flopped in their roles in 1991, and Zimmer was fired \u2013 apparently on orders from [[Tribune Co.]] CEO [[Donald Grenesko]] in May 1991. [[Jim Essian]], a former journeyman catcher and [[Iowa Cubs]] manager, replaced Zimmer for the remainder of the season. Frey was reassigned within the organization after the 1991 season, replaced by former [[Chicago White Sox]] general manager [[Larry Himes]].  He is currently Vice Chairman of the [[Somerset Patriots]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.baseball-reference.com/managers/freyji99.shtml Baseball Reference \u2013 Major League Managerial Record]\n{{baseballstats | brm=frey--001jam}}\n*[http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/1245e7ca SABR Project Biography]\n*[http://www.purapelota.com/lvbp/mostrar.php?id=freyjam001 Venezuelan League Batting Statistics]\n\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{s-sports}}}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Baltimore Orioles|Baltimore Orioles Hitting Coach]] | before=[[Charley Lau]] | years=1970\u20131977| after= [[Frank Robinson]]}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Baltimore Orioles|Baltimore Orioles Bullpen Coach]] | before=[[Charley Lau]] | years=1970\u20131975| after= [[Cal Ripken Sr.]]}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Baltimore Orioles|Baltimore Orioles First Base Coach]] | before=[[George Staller]] | years=1976\u20131979| after= [[Frank Robinson]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Charlie Fox]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Chicago Cubs|Chicago Cubs Manager]]|years=1984\u20131986}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[John Vukovich]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Dallas Green (baseball)|Dallas Green]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Chicago Cubs|Chicago Cubs General Manager]]|years=1988\u20131991}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Larry Himes]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Texas League Player of the Year}}\n{{1970 Baltimore Orioles}}\n{{Chicago Cubs managers}}\n{{Kansas City Royals managers}}\n{{NL Managers of the Year}}\n{{Sporting News Manager of the Year Award}}\n{{Chicago Cubs general managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frey, Jim}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Crackers players]]\n[[Category:Austin Senators players]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles coaches]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles scouts]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs executives]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs managers]]\n[[Category:Columbus Jets players]]\n[[Category:Evansville Braves players]]\n[[Category:Fort Worth Cats players]]\n[[Category:Hartford Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Indios de Oriente players]]\n[[Category:Industriales de Valencia players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Braves players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals managers]]\n[[Category:L\u00e1cteos de Pastora players]]\n[[Category:Leones del Caracas players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball bullpen coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first base coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball general managers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball hitting coaches]]\n[[Category:Manager of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball managers]]\n[[Category:New York Mets coaches]]\n[[Category:Omaha Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Paducah Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Rochester Red Wings players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Toledo Sox players]]\n[[Category:Tulsa Oilers (baseball) players]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the [[Major League Baseball]] [[manager (baseball)|manager]]|the author of [[A Million Little Pieces]]|James Frey|other people of this name|James Frey (disambiguation)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2014}}\n{{More footnotes|date=December 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Jim Frey\n|image= Jim Frey (manager) - Kansas City Royals.jpg\n|caption= Frey in 1980\n|position=[[Manager (baseball)|Manager]] \n|bats=Left\n|throws=Left\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1931|5|26}}\n|birth_place=[[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2020|4|12|1931|5|26}}\n|teams=\n'''As Manager'''\n*[[Kansas City Royals]] (1980\u20131981)\n*[[Chicago Cubs]] (1984\u20131986)\n}}\n\n'''James Gottfried Frey''' (May 26, 1931 - April 14, 2020) was a former [[manager (baseball)|manager]] and [[coach (baseball)|coach]] in [[Major League Baseball]]. He led the [[Kansas City Royals]] to their first [[American League]] championship in 1980, in his first year with the team. In the [[1980 World Series|World Series]], they lost to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]], who won their first [[World Series]] championship.\n\n==Early career==\nFrey, a lifelong friend of [[Don Zimmer]] (they were teammates at [[Western Hills High School (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Western Hills High School]] in [[Cincinnati]]), never reached the major leagues as a player. A left-handed-batting and -throwing outfielder, he spent much of his career in the [[farm system]]s of the [[History of the Boston Braves|Boston/Milwaukee Braves]] and the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], then joined the [[Baltimore Orioles]] as a [[scout (sports)|scout]] and [[minor league baseball|minor league]] manager. He was promoted to the Orioles' coaching staff under [[Earl Weaver]] in [[1970 in baseball|1970]], and coached on three [[American League]] pennant winners and one [[1970 World Series|World Series]] champion through [[1979 in baseball|1979]] before his hiring by the Royals.\n\n==Kansas City Royals==\nA week after the end of the [[1979 World Series]] on October 24, Frey was named to succeed [[Whitey Herzog]] as manager of the Kansas City Royals.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1928&dat=19791023&id=nGEgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xWUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1241,5249849&hl=en \"Jim Frey Signs Year Contract To Manage Royals,\" ''The Associated Press'', Thursday, October 25, 1979.]</ref> He led the Royals to a 97-65 mark and the [[American League West Division]] title in 1980; then, in the [[1980 American League Championship Series]], the Royals defeated their long-time postseason nemesis, the [[New York Yankees]] in three straight games to capture the AL title. (The Yanks had defeated [[Whitey Herzog]]'s Royals for three consecutive seasons (1976\u201378) in the ALCS). But Frey's Royals dropped the [[1980 World Series|World Series]] to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] in six games.\n\nDuring the [[1981 Major League Baseball strike|strike-marred 1981 season]] in which the Royals finished the first half with a 20&ndash;30 record, Frey was criticized widely for not taking full advantage of a team built for speed and for failing to motivate his players by Kansas City vice president/general manager [[Joe Burke (baseball)|Joe Burke]]. Frey was relieved of his duties on August 31 despite the 10&ndash;10 ballclub leading the second-half [[American League West]] standings. His replacement was [[Dick Howser]] who had lost his managerial job with the Yankees after the previous year's ALCS. Frey's record in just less than two seasons as Royals manager was 127&ndash;105.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1981/09/01/royals-fire-frey-hire-howser-to-manage-club/309e2e68-178d-40a6-8dca-cb0c8948f709/ Dougherty, Kerry. \"Royals Fire Frey, Hire Howser to Manage Club,\" ''The Washington Post'', Tuesday, September 1, 1981]</ref>\n\n==Chicago Cubs==\nFrey then returned to the coaching ranks with the [[New York Mets]] for 1982\u201383. Frey was hired by the [[Chicago Cubs]] for the 1984 season, and again struck paydirt as the Cubs won the division title, earning their first post-season appearance since [[1945 World Series|1945]].  During the clubhouse celebration following the division-clinching in [[Pittsburgh Pirates|Pittsburgh]], Frey declared, \"The monkey's off our back!\"\n\nThe Cubs won the first two games against the San Diego Padres in the [[National League Championship Series]] at [[Wrigley Field]], before they went to San Diego needing to win just one of the next three games. The Cubs lost the next three games, and many critics blamed Frey for mishandling the pitching staff. Still, the 1984 Cubs are revered among Cubs fans.\n\nAfter a trying 1985 season in which the entire five-man starting rotation simultaneously spent time on the disabled list, the Cubs sputtered in 1986. Frey was fired two months into the season and replaced by [[John Vukovich]]. The next year, Frey surfaced as a color commentator on the Cubs' WGN Radio broadcasts.\n\nIn December 1987, the Tribune Co. hired Frey to replace his old boss, general manager [[Dallas Green (baseball)|Dallas Green]], who had resigned two months earlier. Frey hired his lifelong friend, Zimmer, to manage the team, and immediately made his presence felt. Within weeks of his hire, he dealt relief pitcher [[Lee Smith (baseball)|Lee Smith]] to Boston for journeyman [[Al Nipper]] and [[Calvin Schiraldi]], who was best known for playing a part in the Red Sox' [[1986 World Series]] collapse. Frey also traded the popular [[Keith Moreland]] to San Diego for closer [[Goose Gossage]], who had played a big part on the San Diego team that eliminated the Cubs four years earlier. Neither move worked, and the Cubs were without a closer.\n\nSo Frey made a bold move in the winter of 1988, trading budding star [[Rafael Palmeiro]] and young pitcher [[Jamie Moyer]] to the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] for a number of players, including [[Mitch Williams (baseball)|Mitch Williams]]. The trade paid off for the Cubs in 1989 as Williams saved 36 games, the Cubs won a division title and Moyer and Palmeiro struggled in Texas. But Williams had just one more forgettable year for the Cubs before being traded to Philadelphia in 1991, and Palmeiro and Moyer went on to have productive careers.\n\nAfter a disappointing 1990 season, Frey was active on the free agent market, acquiring former Toronto Blue Jay and 1987 American League MVP [[George Bell (outfielder)|George Bell]], former Cincinnati Reds starting pitcher [[Danny Jackson]] and former [[Houston Astros]] closer [[Dave Smith (NL pitcher)|Dave Smith]]. Jackson and Smith flopped in their roles in 1991, and Zimmer was fired \u2013 apparently on orders from [[Tribune Co.]] CEO [[Donald Grenesko]] in May 1991. [[Jim Essian]], a former journeyman catcher and [[Iowa Cubs]] manager, replaced Zimmer for the remainder of the season. Frey was reassigned within the organization after the 1991 season, replaced by former [[Chicago White Sox]] general manager [[Larry Himes]].  He is currently Vice Chairman of the [[Somerset Patriots]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.baseball-reference.com/managers/freyji99.shtml Baseball Reference \u2013 Major League Managerial Record]\n{{baseballstats | brm=frey--001jam}}\n*[http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/1245e7ca SABR Project Biography]\n*[http://www.purapelota.com/lvbp/mostrar.php?id=freyjam001 Venezuelan League Batting Statistics]\n\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{s-sports}}}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Baltimore Orioles|Baltimore Orioles Hitting Coach]] | before=[[Charley Lau]] | years=1970\u20131977| after= [[Frank Robinson]]}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Baltimore Orioles|Baltimore Orioles Bullpen Coach]] | before=[[Charley Lau]] | years=1970\u20131975| after= [[Cal Ripken Sr.]]}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Baltimore Orioles|Baltimore Orioles First Base Coach]] | before=[[George Staller]] | years=1976\u20131979| after= [[Frank Robinson]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Charlie Fox]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Chicago Cubs|Chicago Cubs Manager]]|years=1984\u20131986}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[John Vukovich]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Dallas Green (baseball)|Dallas Green]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Chicago Cubs|Chicago Cubs General Manager]]|years=1988\u20131991}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Larry Himes]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Texas League Player of the Year}}\n{{1970 Baltimore Orioles}}\n{{Chicago Cubs managers}}\n{{Kansas City Royals managers}}\n{{NL Managers of the Year}}\n{{Sporting News Manager of the Year Award}}\n{{Chicago Cubs general managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frey, Jim}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Crackers players]]\n[[Category:Austin Senators players]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles coaches]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles scouts]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs executives]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs managers]]\n[[Category:Columbus Jets players]]\n[[Category:Evansville Braves players]]\n[[Category:Fort Worth Cats players]]\n[[Category:Hartford Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Indios de Oriente players]]\n[[Category:Industriales de Valencia players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Braves players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals managers]]\n[[Category:L\u00e1cteos de Pastora players]]\n[[Category:Leones del Caracas players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball bullpen coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first base coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball general managers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball hitting coaches]]\n[[Category:Manager of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball managers]]\n[[Category:New York Mets coaches]]\n[[Category:Omaha Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Paducah Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Rochester Red Wings players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Toledo Sox players]]\n[[Category:Tulsa Oilers (baseball) players]]\n", "name_user": "Kbreit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove age from birth date area", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Frey"}
{"title_page": "Quranism", "text_new": "{{Quran}}\n{{short description|Islamic view that holds the Quran to be the only authentic source of Islamic faith}}\n{{Expand Arabic|\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646\u064a\u0648\u0646|date=March 2016}}\n[[File:OpeningKoran.jpg|thumb|Opening page of the Quran; [[illuminated manuscript]] from [[Istanbul]], [[1867]]]]\n\n'''Quranism''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646\u064a\u0629}}; ''al-Qur'\u0101niyya'') comprises views that [[Islam]]ic law and guidance should only be based on the [[Qur'an]], thus [[Criticism of Hadith|opposing the religious authority, reliability, and/or authenticity]] of [[hadith]] literature.<ref name=\"The Quranists\">>{{cite journal |last=Musa |first=Aisha Y. |date=2010 |title=The Qur'anists |journal=Religion Compass |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=12\u201321 |doi=10.1111/j.1749-8171.2009.00189.x}}</ref> Quranists believe that God's message in the Quran is clear and complete as it is, and that it can therefore be fully understood without referencing the hadith. Quranists affirm that the hadith literature which exists today is [[apocrypha]]l, as it had been written three centuries after the death of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]]; thus, it cannot have the same status as the Quran. \n\nIn matters of faith, jurisprudence, and legislation, Quranists differ from [[ahl al-Hadith]], which today comprises the [[Sunnis]], and to some limited extent, the [[Ibadis]] and [[Shias]], and which first emerged during the 2nd/3rd Islamic centuries of the Islamic era (late 8th and 9th century CE) as a movement of Hadith scholars who considered the Quran and Hadith to be the only legislative authority in matters of law and creed.<ref name=ODI>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Ahl al-Hadith|editor=John L. Esposito|encyclopedia=The Oxford Dictionary of Islam|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|year=2014|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195125580.001.0001/acref-9780195125580-e-72|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n''Quran alone-Islam'' is similar to movements in [[Abrahamic religions]] such as the [[Karaite Judaism|Karaite]] movement in [[Judaism]] and the ''[[Sola scriptura]]'' view of [[Protestantism|Protestant]] [[Christianity]].<ref>{{cite book |last= Aziz Ahmad |first=Aziz |authorlink=Aziz Ahmad (novelist) |date=1967 |title=Islamic Modernism in India and Pakistan 1857\u20131964 |location=London |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=14\u201315}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\nAdherents of Quranic Islam are referred to as ''Quranists'' ({{lang-ar|\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0648\u0646|Qur\u0101niyy\u016bn}}), or ''People of the Quran'' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0647\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646|\u2019Ahl al-Qur\u2019\u0101n}}).<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook\">{{cite book |first1=Yvonne Y. |last1=Haddad |first2=Jane I. |last2=Smith |title=The Oxford Handbook of American Islam |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5y_cBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA150 |date=3 November 2014 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-986264-1 |pages=150\u2013153}}</ref> This should not be confused with [[#Ahle Quran|Ahle-e-Quran]], which is an organisation formed by Abdullah Chakralawi. Quranists may also refer to themselves simply as ''Muslims'', ''Submitters'', or ''reformists''.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook\" />\n\n==Doctrine==\n===Scriptural basis===\n{{Verse translation|lang=ar|italicsoff=y|rtl1=y|\n\u062a\u0650\u0644\u0652\u0643\u064e \u0621\u064e\u0627\u064a\u064e\u0670\u062a\u064f \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0647\u0650 \u0646\u064e\u062a\u0652\u0644\u064f\u0648\u0647\u064e\u0627 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0643\u064e \u0628\u0650\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0642\u0650\u0651 \u06d6 \u0641\u064e\u0628\u0650\u0623\u064e\u0649\u0650\u0651 \u062d\u064e\u062f\u0650\u064a\u062b\u064d\u06ed\n\u0628\u064e\u0639\u0652\u062f\u064e \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0647\u0650 \u0648\u064e\u0621\u064e\u0627\u064a\u064e\u0670\u062a\u0650\u0647\u0650\u06e6 \u064a\u064f\u0624\u0652\u0645\u0650\u0646\u064f\u0648\u0646\u064e\n|attr1=Quran ([[Surah]] [[Al-Jathiya]], 45:6)\n|These are the verses of God which We recite to you in truth. Then in what statement [Hadith] after (rejecting) God and His verses will they believe?}}\n\nQuranists believe that the Quran is the sole source of religious law and guidance in Islam and reject the authority of sources outside of the Quran like [[Hadith]] and [[Sunnah]]. \nOther Quranic verses cited in support of the idea that the Quran is clear, complete, and that it can be fully understood without recourse to the hadith and sunna:<ref name=\"The Quranists\"/> \n*{{cite quran|7|52|s=ns|b=n}} {{cite quran|10|37|s=ns|b=n}} {{cite quran|6|114|s=ns|b=n}} which say the Quran is \"detailed\" or \"fully explained\"; \n*{{cite quran|6|115|s=ns|b=n}} \"complete\", \"perfect\", or \"fulfilled\";\n*{{cite quran|12|111|s=ns|b=n}} \"detailed explanation of all things\";\n*{{cite quran|6|38|s=ns|b=n}} which says that \"we have not neglected in the book a thing\".<ref name=\"Rizvi-114\">{{cite book |last1=Rizvi |first1=Ali A. |title=The Atheist Muslim |date=2016 |publisher=St. Martin's Press |page=114}}</ref> \n\nTherefore, they use the Quran itself to interpret the Quran:<ref>Jens Zimmermann, ''Hermeneutics: A Very Short Introduction'', Oxford University Press, 2015, pg. 90</ref>\n\n===Hadith and Tafsir===\n<blockquote>\". . . .a literal and holistic analysis of the text from a contemporary perspective and applying the exegetical principle of ''tafsir al-qur'an bi al-qur'an'' (explaining the Qur'an with the Qur'an) and the jurisprudential principle ''al-asl fi al-kalam al-haqiqah'' (the fundamental rule of speech is literalness), without refracting that Qur'anic usage through the lens of history and tradition.\"<ref>Mahmoud Ayoub, ''Contemporary Approaches to the Qur'an and Sunnah'', International Institute of Islamic Thought (IIIT), 2012, pg. 27</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis method of interpreting the Quran is different from the method favored by most [[Sunni]] and [[Shia Islam|Shia]] exegetes, known as ''[[Tafsir|tafsir bi-al-ma'thur]]'' (interpreting the Quran with narrations, i.e., hadiths). In contrast to Quranists, Sunnis do not believe that the Quran is fully detailed. They believe that, \"the Qur'an needs the Sunnah more than the Sunnah needs the Qur'an (''inna l-Quran ahwaju ila l-sunna mina l-sunna ila l-Quran'')\".<ref>Jane Dammen McAuliffe, ''Encyclopaedia of the Qur'an, Vol. 5'', Brill, 2006, pg. 165</ref> This methodological difference has led to considerable divergence between Quranists and [[Sunni Islam|Sunnis]] and [[Shia Islam|Shia]] in matters of [[Schools of Islamic theology|theology]] and [[Sharia|law]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n[[Syed Ahmad Khan]] argued that, while the Quran remained socially relevant, reliance on hadith limits the vast potential of the Quran to a particular cultural and historical situation.<ref>Daniel W. Brown Rethinking Tradition in Modern Islamic Thought Cambridge University Press {{ISBN|9780521653947 }} p. 65</ref>\n\nThe extent to which Quranists reject the authenticity of the Hadith and Sunnah varies,<ref name=\"Voss\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.masjidtucson.org/publications/books/sp/1996/apr/page1.html |title=Identifying Assumptions in the Hadith/Sunnah Debate |last=Voss |first=Richard Stephen |date=April 1996 |volume=12 |issue=4 |journal=Monthly Bulletin of the International Community of Submitters |access-date=5 December 2013}}</ref> but the more established groups have thoroughly criticised the authenticity of the Hadith and reject it for many reasons. The most common view being the Quranists who say that Hadith is not mentioned in the Quran as a source of [[Islamic theology]] and practice, was not recorded in written form until a century after the death of Muhammad,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.uncw.edu/bergh/par246/L21RHadithCriticism.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311144448/http://people.uncw.edu/bergh/par246/L21RHadithCriticism.htm |archivedate=2007-03-11 }}</ref> and contain internal errors and contradictions.<ref name=\"The Quranists\"/><ref name=\"Voss\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe Quranist ideology dates back to the time of [[Muhammad]], who prohibited the writing of hadiths.<ref name=\"Musa 2008\">{{cite book |last=Musa |first=Aisha Y. |date=2008 |title=Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on The Authority Of Prophetic Traditions in Islam |publisher=Palgrave |isbn=978-0-230-60535-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Aisha Musa\">Aisha Y. Musa, ''Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam,'' Palgrave Macmillan, 2008, pp.25-29</ref> One of Muhammad's companions and successor [[Umar]], also prohibited the writing of hadith and destroyed existing collections during his rule as [[Caliph]].<ref name=\"Aisha Musa\"/> When Umar appointed a governor to [[Kufa]], he told him: \"You will be coming to the people of a town for whom the buzzing of the Qur'an is as the buzzing of bees. Therefore, do not distract them with the Hadiths, and thus engage them. Bare the Qur'an and spare the narration from God's messenger (peace and blessing be upon him)!\"<ref name=\"Aisha Musa\"/>.\n\nThe centrality of the Quran in the religious life of the Kufans that Umar described was quickly changing, however. A few decades later, a letter was sent to the [[Ummayad]] [[caliph]] [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan]] regarding the Kufans: \"They abandoned the judgement of their Lord and took hadiths for their religion; and they claim that they have obtained knowledge other than from the Koran . . . They believed in a book which was not from God, written by the hands of men; they then attributed it to the Messenger of God.\"<ref>Aisha Y. Musa, ''Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam,'' Palgrave Macmillan, 2008, pp. 37-38</ref>\n\nIn the following years, the taboo against the writing and following of hadiths had receded to such an extent that the Ummayad leader [[Umar II]] ordered the first official collection of Hadith. [[Abu Bakr ibn Muhammad ibn Hazm]] and [[Ibn Shihab al-Zuhri]], were among those who wrote Hadiths at Umar II's behest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.uncw.edu/bergh/par246/L21RHadithCriticism.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311144448/http://people.uncw.edu/bergh/par246/L21RHadithCriticism.htm |archivedate=2007-03-11 }}</ref>\n\nDespite the trend towards hadiths, the questioning of their authority continued during the [[Abbasid]] dynasty and existed during the time of Al-Shafi'i, when a group known as \"Ahl al-Kalam\" argued that the prophetic example of Muhammad \"is found in following the Quran alone\", rather than Hadith.<ref name=DWBRTMIT1996:15-6>[[#DWBRTMIT1996|Brown, ''Rethinking tradition in modern Islamic thought'', 1996]]: p.15-16</ref><ref>excerpted from Abdur Rab, ''ibid'', pp.&nbsp;199\u2013200.</ref> Later, a similar group, \nAhl al-Taw\u1e25\u012bd wa l-\u02bfAdl, \"people of monotheism and justice\", known as the [[Mu'tazilite]]s by their opponents, also viewed the transmission of the Hadith as not sufficiently reliable.<ref>Sabine Schmidtke, ''The Oxford Handbook of Islamic Theology,'' Oxford University Press, 2016, pp. 264-265</ref> The Hadith, according to them, was mere guesswork, conjecture, and [[bidah]] (innovation), while the Quran was complete and perfect, and did not require the Hadith or any other book to supplement or complement it.<ref>Azami, M. A., ''Studies in Hadith Methodology and Literature'', Islamic Book Trust, Kuala Lumpur, 92; cited in Akbarally Meherally, ''Myths and Realities of Hadith \u2013 A Critical Study'', (published by Mostmerciful.com Publishers), Burnaby, BC, Canada, 6; available at  http://www.mostmerciful.com/Hadithbook-sectionone.htm; excerpted from Abdur Rab, ibid, p. 200.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Abassid]] dynasty, the poet, theologian, and jurist, [[Ibrahim an-Nazzam]] founded a [[madhhab]] called the Nazzamiyya that rejected the authority of Hadiths and relied on the Quran alone.<ref>{{cite book |last=Abdul-Raof |first=Hussein |date=2012 |title=Theological Approaches to Quranic Exegesis: A Practical Comparative-Contrastive Analysis |location=London |publisher=Routledge |pages=33\u201334 |isbn=978-0-41544-958-8}}</ref> His famous student, [[Al-Jahiz]], was also critical of those who followed Hadith, referring to his Hadithist opponents as ''al-nabita'' (\"the contemptible\").<ref>{{cite book |last=Zaman |first=Muhammad Qasim |date=1997 |title=Religion and Politics Under the Early 'Abbasids: The Emergence of the Proto-Sunni Elite |location=[[Leiden]] |publisher=[[E.J. Brill]] |page=55 |isbn=978-9-00410-678-9}}</ref> A contemporary of An-Nazzam, [[Al-Shafi'i]], tried to refute the arguments of the Quranists and establish the authority of Hadiths in his book ''Kitab Jima'a l-'Ilm''.<ref name=\"Musa 2008\"/> And [[Ibn Qutaybah]] tried to refute An-Nazzam's arguments against Hadith in his book [[The Interpretation of Conflicting Narrations|''Ta'wil Mukhtalif al-Hadith'']].<ref>{{cite book |last=Juynboll |first=G. H. A. |date=1969 |title=The Authenticity of the Tradition Literature: Discussions in Modern Egypt |location=Leiden |publisher=E. J. Brill |pages=77\u201380}}</ref>\n\nIn South Asia during the 19th century, the Ahle Quran movement formed partially in reaction to the [[Ahle Hadith]] whom they considered to be placing too much emphasis on Hadith.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite book |last=Brown |first=Daniel W. |date=1996 |title=Rethinking Tradition in Modern Islamic Thought |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |pages=38\u201341 |isbn=978-0-52157-077-0}}</ref> Many Ahle Quran adherents from South Asia were formerly adherents of Ahle Hadith but found themselves incapable of accepting certain hadiths.<ref name=\"Brown\"/> \n\nIn Egypt during the early 20th century, the ideas of Quranists like Muhammad Tawfiq Sidqi grew out of [[Salafism]] i.e. a rejection of [[taqlid]].<ref name=\"Brown\"/> Muhammad Tawfiq Sidqi of Egypt \"held that nothing of the Hadith was recorded until after enough time had elapsed to allow the infiltration of numerous absurd or corrupt traditions.\"<ref>Sidqi, Muhammad Tawfiq, ''Al-Islam huwa al-Qur'an wahdahu,'' ''al-Manar'' 9 (1906), 515; cited in {{cite book|last1=Brown |first1=Daniel W.|title=Rethinking tradition in modern Islamic thought |date=1996 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0521570778|pages=88\u201389 |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/116836545/Rethinking-Traditions-in-Modern-Islamic-Thought-Daniel-w-Brown |accessdate=10 May 2018}} </ref> Muhammad Tawfiq Sidqi wrote an article titled ''Al-Islam Huwa ul-Qur'an Wahdahu'' ('Islam is the Qur'an Alone) that appeared in the Egyptian journal ''Al-Manar'', which argues that the Quran is sufficient as guidance: \"what is obligatory for man does not go beyond God's Book. If anything other than the Qur'an had been necessary for religion,\" Sidqi notes, \"the Prophet would have commanded its registration in writing, and God would have guaranteed its preservation.\"<ref>Musa, Aisha Y., ''Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam'', Palgrave Macmillan, New York, 2008, p.6.</ref>\n\n==Contemporary times==\n[[File:Islam branches and schools.svg|thumb|Diagram showing the branches of [[Sunnism]], [[Shiaism]], [[Ibadism]], [[Quranism]], [[Non-denominational Muslim]]s, [[Ahmadiyya]] and [[Sufism]].]]\n\nIn the 21st century, Quranist beliefs have spread in various countries. However, in countries that have incorporated some aspects of Sunni law, adherents have faced opposition. For example, a Saudi scholar, Hassan Farhan al-Maliki, was arrested numerous times for promoting political reform and a return to the Quran.<ref>Kamel Abderrahmani, [http://www.asianews.it/news-en/The-reform-of-Islam-and-the-Koranists,-persecuted-in-Saudi-Arabia-45322.html The reform of Islam and the Koranists, persecuted in Saudi Arabia], asianews.com, Accessed February 15, 2019</ref> [[Saudi Arabia]] began its prosecution of the researcher in the Specialized Criminal Court in Riyadh, which was specially established in January 2009 to handle cases of \"terrorism and national security.\"<ref>[https://www.esohr.org/en/?p=2169</ref> In 2019, the public prosecution, which is directly linked to the Saudi king, leveled charges almost entirely related to Maliki's religious views and has requested that the court sentence him based on \"extremist interpretations\" of Islam.<ref>[https://www.esohr.org/en/?p=2169</ref> And in [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]], Quranists have been arrested for their beliefs.<ref>Ahmed Subhy Mansour, [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/23/opinion/23iht-edmansour.1.19632638.html Egypt persecutes Muslim moderates], nytimes.com, Accessed February 15, 2019</ref><ref>Zeinab Mohammed Salih, [http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/dec/16/sudan-charges-25-death-penalty-apostasy-sharia-law Sudan threatens 25 Muslims with death on charges of apostasy], theguardian.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> \n\nThe spread of Quranist beliefs in [[Russia]] has provoked the anger of the Sunni establishment. The [[Russian Council of Muftis]] issued a [[fatwa]] against Quranism and those it said were its leaders in Russia.<ref>\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043c \u0411\u0430\u0442\u044b\u0440, [https://www.business-gazeta.ru/blog/375729 \u00ab\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u043c\u0443\u0444\u0442\u0438\u0435\u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0445\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u044b \u0432\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0432 \u0434\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0430\u00bb \u041f\u043e\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043d\u0435\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u00ab\u0411\u0418\u0417\u041d\u0415\u0421 Online\u00bb], business-gazeta.ru, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref> However, one of the purported Quranist leaders mentioned in the fatwa, the Russian philosopher Taufik Ibrahim, pointed out that his beliefs were more in line with the [[Jadid]] tradition, although there is some overlap between the two groups in Russia.<ref>Renat Bekkin, [https://realnoevremya.com/articles/3134-interview-with-islamic-scholar-taufik-ibragim Taufik Ibragim: ''Muslims in Russia are not ready for debates yet, unfortunately''], realnoevremy.com, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref> \n\nIn [[Turkey]], Quranists have responded on social media to criticism by the [[Diyanet]] on their Quranist beliefs.<ref>Alper Bilgili, [http://www.patheos.com/blogs/altmuslim/2018/04/quran-hadiths-or-both-where-quranists-and-traditional-islam-differs/  Quran, Hadiths or Both? Where Quranists and Traditional Islam Differs,], patheos.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref>\n\nIn [[South Africa]], an Oxford educated Islamic scholar, Taj Hargey, established the Open Mosque. As the name implies, Hargey intended the mosque to be more open to demographics traditionally shunned by Sunni and Shia mosques, like women. Hargey describes the principles of the mosque as, \"Quran-centric, gender equality, non-sectarian, inter-cultural and independent\".<ref>Gavin Haynes, [https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/vdpap8/open-mosque-taj-hargey-south-africa-934 Meet the British Muslim Who's Founded a Controversial Gay-Friendly Mosque: Dr Taj Hargey is a hardcore fundamentalist, in that he only follows the teachings of the Qur'an, and none of the other footnotes beloved of modern clerics.], vice.com, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref> Hargey has also criticized what he calls the \"toxic trio\" of hadith, sharia, and fatwas.<ref>Lizzie Stromme, [https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/740484/Hadith-Sharia-law-Fatawas-Toxic-trio-infected-Islam-Imam Hadith, Sharia law, Fatawas: 'Toxic trio' has infected and distorted Islam, Imam says], express.co.uk, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref>\n\nAccording to the Quranist website, Ahl al-Quran, Quranists make up a minority of Muslims, numbering only \"a few thousand\" as of 2008, compared to over one billion Muslims in total.<ref name=\"minority\">{{cite web |title=Who Are The Minority Among Muslims: The Quranists Or The Salafists? |url=http://www.ahl-alquran.com/English/show_article.php?main_id=13594 |website=ahl al-quran |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=August 27 , 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Notable organizations==\n\n===Ahle Quran===\nAhle Quran is an organisation formed by Abdullah Chakralawi, who described the Quran as \"ahsan Hadith\", meaning most perfect hadith and consequently claimed it does not need any addition.<ref name=\"Aziz Ahmad\">A\u1e25mad (1967), pp.120-121.</ref> His movement relies entirely on the chapters and verses of the Quran. Chakralawi's position was that the Quran itself was the most perfect source of tradition and could be exclusively followed. According to Chakralawi, Muhammad could receive only one form of revelation ([[wahy]]), and that was the Quran. He argues that the Quran was the only record of divine wisdom, the only source of Muhammad's teachings, and that it superseded the entire corpus of hadith, which came later.<ref name=\"Aziz Ahmad\"/> Ahle Quran is one of the main Quranist movements in Pakistan along with ''Ahlu Zikr''.<ref name=\"seyed\">Dolatabad, Seyed Ali Hosseini, Hossein Naseri Moghadam, and Ali Reza Abedi Sar Asiya. \"Pillars, proofs and requirements of the Quran-Sufficiency Theory, along with its criticism.\" International Journal of Humanities and Cultural Studies (IJHCS) ISSN 2356-5926 (2016): 2303-2319.</ref>\n\n===Izgi Amal===\n{{main|Izgi Amal}}\nThis is a Quranist organization in [[Kazakhstan]] whose Cyrillic name, \"\u0406\u0437\u0433\u0456 \u0430\u043c\u0430\u043b\", may be transliterated into the Latin script as ''\u0130zgi amal''. It has an estimated 70 to 80 thousand members. Its leader, Aslbek Musin, is the son of the former Speaker of the [[Mazhilis|Majlis]], [[Aslan Musin]].<ref>[http://www.nm2000.kz/news/2009-11-27-22877/ \u041b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0438 \u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043c (\u041d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u043e. \u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u0441 \u0410\u0441\u043b\u0431\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043c \u041c\u0443\u0441\u0438\u043d\u044b\u043c)], nm2000.kz, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref><ref>\u0422\u0430\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0442 \u0410\u0434\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432, [http://www.contur.kz/node/517 \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0442\u044b: \u044d\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0449\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u00ab\u0410\u043a \u041e\u0440\u0434\u044b\u00bb \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0443], contur.kz, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref>\n\n=== Kala Kato===\n{{main|Kala Kato}}\n[[Kala Kato]] is a Quranist movement whose adherents reside mostly northern Nigeria,<ref name=\"Sa'isu\">Isa Sa'isu, [https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/kala-kato-meet-group-with-yet-another-perception-of-islam.html Kala-Kato: Meet group with yet another perception of Islam], dailytrust.com.ng, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> with some adherents residing in Niger.<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2009/127248.htm International Religious Freedom Report 2009], state.gov, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> Kala Kato means a \"man says\" in the [[Hausa language]], in reference to the sayings, or hadiths, posthumously attributed to Muhammad. Kala Kato accept only the Quran as authoritative and believe that anything that is not Kala Allah, which means what \"God says\" in the Hausa language, is Kala Kato.<ref>Aminu Alhaji Bala, [http://saspjournals.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/SJAHSS-35B1034-1039.pdf Qur\u2019anists\u2019 Deviant Da'wah as Reflected in Their Trends of Tafsir in Northern Nigeria], saspjournal.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref>\n\n===Malaysian Quranic Society===\nThe Malaysian Quranic Society was founded by Kassim Ahmad. The movement holds several positions distinguishing it from Sunnis and Shias such as a rejection of the status of hair as being part of the awrah; therefore exhibiting a relaxation on the observance of the hijab, which according to Quranists is not in the Quran.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/17894/ |title=Malay intellectual Kassim Ahmad dies |website=The Malaysian Insight |accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Quran Sunnat Society===\nThe Quran Sunnat Society is a Quranist movement in India. The movement was behind the first ever woman to lead mixed-gender [[Jumu'ah|congregational prayers]] in India.<ref>Ziya Us Salam, [https://frontline.thehindu.com/the-nation/i-follow-the-quran/article10074190.ece 'I follow the Quran'], frontline.thehindu.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> It maintains an office and headquarters within Kerala.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/30/muslim-woman-receives-death-threats-leading-prayers-kerala-india |title=Muslim woman receives death threats after leading prayers in Kerala |first=Amrit |last=Dhillon |date=30 January 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref> There is a large community of Quranists in Kerala.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Khan |first=Aftab Ahmad |title=Islamic Culture and the Modern World 2 |journal=Defence Journal |volume=20 |number=4 |date=2016 |page=49}}</ref> One of its leaders, Jamida Beevi, has also spoken out against India's [[Triple talaq in India|triple talaq]] law which is mostly based on the Sunni inspired [[Muslim personal law in India|Muslim Personal Law (Shariat) Application Act, 1937]].<ref>Jiby J Kattakayam, [https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/blogs/jibber-jabber/quran-has-capacity-to-reflect-and-absorb-changes-in-society-over-time-it-did-not-discriminate-between-men-and-women/ \u2018Quran has capacity to reflect and absorb changes in society over time \u2026 it did not discriminate between men and women\u2019], timesofindia.indiatimes.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> The most prominent predecessor to the Quran Sunnat Society in India was from the views put forth by Ahmed Khan in the 19th century.\n<ref>https://fanack.com/religions/quranists-islams-outcasts/</ref>\n\n===Submitters===\n\nIn the United States it was associated with [[Rashad Khalifa]], founder of the [[United Submitters International]]. The group popularized the phrase: The Quran, the whole Quran, and nothing but the Quran.<ref name=\"The Quranists\"/> After Khalifa declared himself the [[Messenger of the Covenant]], he was rejected by other Muslim scholars as an apostate of Islam. Later, he was assassinated in 1990 by a terrorist group. Those interested in his work believe that there is a mathematical structure in the Quran, based on the number 19. A group of Submitters in Nigeria was popularised by high court judge Isa Othman.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://www3.qeh.ox.ac.uk/pdf/nrn/WP2Alkali.pdf |title=Overview of Islamic actors in northern Nigeria |page=16 |author1=Muhammad Nur Alkali |author2=Abubakar Kawu Monguno |author3=Ballama Shettima Mustafa |date=January 2012 |publisher=Nigeria Research Network |accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Tolu-e-Islam===\n{{main|Tolu-e-Islam}}\nThe movement was initiated by [[Ghulam Ahmed Pervez]].<ref>Aisha Y. Musa, ''Hadith As Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam,'' Palgrave MacMillan, 2008, pg. 86</ref><ref>Aisha Y. Musa, [http://www.academia.edu/1035742/The_Quranists The Qur'anists], Academia.edu, Accessed April 7, 2019</ref><ref>Nadeem F. Paracha, [https://www.dawn.com/news/1132974 The rise and fall of a spiritual rebel], Dawn.com, Accessed April 7, 2019</ref><ref>Nadeem F. Paracha, [https://www.dawn.com/news/790958 Crazy diamonds \u2013 V], Dawn.com, Accessed April 7, 2019</ref> Ghulam Ahmed Pervez did not reject all hadiths; however, he only accepted hadiths which \"are in accordance with the Quran or do not stain the character of the Prophet or his [[Sahabah|companions]]\".<ref name=toluislam>{{cite web|url=http://www.tolueislam.com/|title=Bazm-e-Tolu-e-Islam|publisher=|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> The organization publishes and distributes books, pamphlets, and recordings of Pervez's teachings.<ref name=toluislam/> Tolu-e-Islam does not belong to any political party, [[non-denominational Islam|nor does it belong to any religious group or sect]].\n\n==Notable Quranists==\n\n*[[Kassim Ahmad]] (1933\u20132017) a Malaysian intellectual, writer, poet and an educator known for his rejection of the authority of hadiths.<ref>Mariam Mokhtar, [http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/opinion/2017/03/16/dont-let-the-hardliners-get-their-way/  Don\u2019t let the hardliners get their way], freemalaysiatoday.com, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref><ref>Predeep Nambiar, [http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/10/10/kassim-ahmad-died-a-beautiful-death-says-daughter/ Kassim Ahmad died a \u2018beautiful death\u2019, says daughter], freemalaysiatoday.com, February 16, 2019</ref> He was the founder of the Quranic Society of Malaysia.<ref>Gatut Adisoma, [http://www.masjidtucson.org/publications/books/sp/1993/oct/page4.html QURANIC SOCIETY OF MALAYSIA ESTABLISHED], masjidtuucson.org, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref> At the time of his death, he was working on a Malay translation of the Quran.<ref>[http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/son-regrets-kassim-ahmad-unable-to-complete-malay-translation-of-quran#83KyoWWA11spYbCk.97 Son regrets Kassim Ahmad unable to complete Malay translation of Quran], themalayonline.com, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref>\n*[[Rashad Khalifa]] (1935\u20131990), an Egyptian-American biochemist and Islamic reformer. In his book ''Quran, Hadith and Islam'' and his English translation of the Quran, Khalifa argued that the Quran alone is the sole source of Islamic belief and practice.<ref name=\"The Quranists\"/> However, he also claimed that parts of the Quran were fabricated, precluding him from being a strict Quranist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://submission.org/two_false_verses_deeper_look.html|title=Two False verses; A Deeper Look {{!}} Submission.org - Your best source for Submission (Islam)|website=submission.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Quran : the final testament|date=2000|publisher=Universal Unity|others=Khalifa, Rashad.|isbn=1881893030|edition=Rev. ed. 2|location=Fremont, CA.|pages=Appendix 24|oclc=42736348}}</ref>. He further declared that the Hadith and Sunna were 'Satanic inventions' under 'Satan's schemes'.<ref name=\"The Quranists\" /> In the face of widespread anger and hostility by the Muslim world,<ref name=\"The Quranists\" /> Khalifa was stabbed to death on 31 January 1990 by Glen Cusford Francis,<ref>{{Cite web |title=State of Arizona v. Francis, Glen Cusford |url=http://www.investigativeproject.org/case/632/state-of-arizona-v-francis |website=The Investigative Project on Terrorism |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> a member of the terrorist organization, [[Jamaat ul-Fuqra]].\n*[[Ahmed Subhy Mansour]] (born 1949), an Egyptian-American Islamic scholar.<ref name=\"ahl-alquran1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ahl-alquran.com/English/aboutus.php |title=About Us |website=Ahl-alquran.com |date= |accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> He founded a small group of Quranists, but was [[exile]]d from Egypt and is now living in the United States as a political refugee.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/05/12/AR2005051201788.html?noredirect=on |title=Muslims' Unheralded Messenger |first=Don |last=Oldenburg |date=13 May 2005 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Chekannur Maulavi]] (born 1936; disappeared 29 July 1993), a progressive Islamic cleric who lived in Edappal in Malappuram district of Kerala, India. He was noted for his controversial and unconventional interpretation of Islam based on the Quran alone. He disappeared on 29 July 1993 under mysterious circumstances and is now widely believed to be dead.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kumar |first=Girja |date=1997 |title=The Book on Trial: Fundamentalism and Censorship in India |location=New Delhi |publisher=Har Anand Publications |pages=34\u201335 |isbn=978-8-12410-525-2}}</ref>\n*[[Ahmad Rashad]] (born 1949), an American sportscaster (mostly with [[NBC Sports]]) and former professional football player. Ahmad Rashad studied the Arabic language and the Quran with his mentor, the late Rashad Khalifa.<ref>Murray Olderman, [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GrgdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Jl0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=1963%2C3707744 Rashad Made A Name For Himself. . . Twice.], ''The Pittsburgh Press'', Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref><ref>Ken Shouler, [https://www.cigaraficionado.com/article/catching-it-all-6084 Catching It All], cigaraficionado.com, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref><ref>Thomas Lifson, [https://www.americanthinker.com/blog/2013/11/valerie_jarrett_reportedly_dating_a_muslim.html  Valerie Jarrett reportedly dating a Muslim], americanthinker.com, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref>\n*[[Mohamed Talbi]] (1921\u20132017), a Tunisian historian and professor. He was the founder of the Association Internationale des Musulmans Coraniques (AIMC), or International Association of Quranic Muslims.<ref>Rachid Barnat, [http://www.kapitalis.com/afkar-2/15589-tunisie-islam-le-musulman-coranique-selon-mohamed-talbi.html Tunisie-Islam : Le \u00abmusulman coranique\u00bb selon Mohamed Talbi], kapitalis.com, Accessed February 16, 2019</ref><ref>Sadok Belaid, [http://www.leaders.com.tn/article/22458-in-memoriam-mohamed-talbi-1921-2017 In memorium: Mohamed Talbi (1921-2017) - (Album photos)], leaders.com, Accessed February 16, 2019</ref> \n*[[Edip Y\u00fcksel]] (born 1957), a [[Kurdish Americans|Kurdish American]] philosopher, lawyer, Quranist advocate, author of ''Nineteen: God's Signature in Nature and Scripture'', ''Manifesto for Islamic Reform'' and a co-author of ''Quran: A Reformist Translation''. He taught philosophy and logic at [[Pima Community College]] and medical ethics and criminal law courses at [[Brown Mackie College]].<ref name=\"Musa 2008\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Kenney |first1=Jeffrey T. |last2=Moosa |first2=Ebrahim |date=2013 |title=Islam in the Modern World |publisher=Routledge |page=21}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Karaite Judaism|Karaites]]\n* [[Liberalism and progressivism within Islam]]\n* [[Non-denominational Muslim]]\n* ''[[Sola Scriptura]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Aisha Y. Musa, ''Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam'', New York: Palgrave, 2008. {{ISBN|0-230-60535-4}}.\n* Ali Usman Qasmi, ''Questioning the Authority of the Past: The Ahl al-Qur'an Movements in the Punjab'', Oxford University Press, 2012. {{ISBN|0-195-47348-5}}.\n* Daniel Brown, ''Rethinking Tradition in Modern Islamic Thought'', Cambridge University Press, 1996. {{ISBN|0-521-65394-0}}.\n\n{{Quranism}}\n{{Religion topics}}\n\n[[Category:Quranism| ]]\n[[Category:Quranist Muslims]]\n[[Category:Islamic terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Quran}}\n{{short description|Islamic view that holds the Quran to be the only authentic source of Islamic faith}}\n{{Expand Arabic|\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646\u064a\u0648\u0646|date=March 2016}}\n[[File:OpeningKoran.jpg|thumb|Opening page of the Quran; [[illuminated manuscript]] from [[Istanbul]], [[1867]]]]\n\n'''Quranism''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646\u064a\u0629}}; ''al-Qur'\u0101niyya'') comprises views that [[Islam]]ic law and guidance should only be based on the [[Qur'an]], thus [[Criticism of Hadith|opposing the religious authority, reliability, and/or authenticity]] of [[hadith]] literature.<ref name=\"The Quranists\">>{{cite journal |last=Musa |first=Aisha Y. |date=2010 |title=The Qur'anists |journal=Religion Compass |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=12\u201321 |doi=10.1111/j.1749-8171.2009.00189.x}}</ref> Quranists believe that God's message in the Quran is clear and complete as it is, and that it can therefore be fully understood without referencing the hadith. Quranists affirm that the hadith literature which exists today is [[apocrypha]]l, as it had been written three centuries after the death of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]]; thus, it cannot have the same status as the Quran. \n\nIn matters of faith, jurisprudence, and legislation, Quranists differ from [[ahl al-Hadith]], which today comprises the [[Sunnis]], and to some limited extent, the [[Ibadis]] and [[Shias]], and which first emerged during the 2nd/3rd Islamic centuries of the Islamic era (late 8th and 9th century CE) as a movement of Hadith scholars who considered the Quran and Hadith to be the only legislative authority in matters of law and creed.<ref name=ODI>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Ahl al-Hadith|editor=John L. Esposito|encyclopedia=The Oxford Dictionary of Islam|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|year=2014|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195125580.001.0001/acref-9780195125580-e-72|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n''Quran alone-Islam'' is similar to movements in [[Abrahamic religions]] such as the [[Karaite Judaism|Karaite]] movement in [[Judaism]] and the ''[[Sola scriptura]]'' view of [[Protestantism|Protestant]] [[Christianity]].<ref>{{cite book |last= Aziz Ahmad |first=Aziz |authorlink=Aziz Ahmad (novelist) |date=1967 |title=Islamic Modernism in India and Pakistan 1857\u20131964 |location=London |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=14\u201315}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\nAdherents of Quranic Islam are referred to as ''Quranists'' ({{lang-ar|\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0648\u0646|Qur\u0101niyy\u016bn}}), or ''People of the Quran'' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0647\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646|\u2019Ahl al-Qur\u2019\u0101n}}).<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook\">{{cite book |first1=Yvonne Y. |last1=Haddad |first2=Jane I. |last2=Smith |title=The Oxford Handbook of American Islam |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5y_cBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA150 |date=3 November 2014 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-986264-1 |pages=150\u2013153}}</ref> This should not be confused with [[#Ahle Quran|Ahle-e-Quran]], which is an organisation formed by Abdullah Chakralawi. Quranists may also refer to themselves simply as ''Muslims'', ''Submitters'', or ''reformists''.<ref name=\"Oxford Handbook\" />\n\n==Doctrine==\n===Scriptural basis===\n{{Verse translation|lang=ar|italicsoff=y|rtl1=y|\n\u062a\u0650\u0644\u0652\u0643\u064e \u0621\u064e\u0627\u064a\u064e\u0670\u062a\u064f \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0647\u0650 \u0646\u064e\u062a\u0652\u0644\u064f\u0648\u0647\u064e\u0627 \u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u0652\u0643\u064e \u0628\u0650\u0671\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0642\u0650\u0651 \u06d6 \u0641\u064e\u0628\u0650\u0623\u064e\u0649\u0650\u0651 \u062d\u064e\u062f\u0650\u064a\u062b\u064d\u06ed\n\u0628\u064e\u0639\u0652\u062f\u064e \u0671\u0644\u0644\u064e\u0651\u0647\u0650 \u0648\u064e\u0621\u064e\u0627\u064a\u064e\u0670\u062a\u0650\u0647\u0650\u06e6 \u064a\u064f\u0624\u0652\u0645\u0650\u0646\u064f\u0648\u0646\u064e\n|attr1=Quran ([[Surah]] [[Al-Jathiya]], 45:6)\n|These are the verses of God which We recite to you in truth. Then in what statement [Hadith] after (rejecting) God and His verses will they believe?}}\n\nQuranists believe that the Quran is the sole source of religious law and guidance in Islam and reject the authority of sources outside of the Quran like [[Hadith]] and [[Sunnah]]. \nOther Quranic verses cited in support of the idea that the Quran is clear, complete, and that it can be fully understood without recourse to the hadith and sunna:<ref name=\"The Quranists\"/> \n*{{cite quran|7|52|s=ns|b=n}} {{cite quran|10|37|s=ns|b=n}} {{cite quran|6|114|s=ns|b=n}} which say the Quran is \"detailed\" or \"fully explained\"; \n*{{cite quran|6|115|s=ns|b=n}} \"complete\", \"perfect\", or \"fulfilled\";\n*{{cite quran|12|111|s=ns|b=n}} \"detailed explanation of all things\";\n*{{cite quran|6|38|s=ns|b=n}} which says that \"we have not neglected in the book a thing\"<ref name=\"Rizvi-114\">{{cite book |last1=Rizvi |first1=Ali A. |title=The Atheist Muslim |date=2016 |publisher=St. Martin's Press |page=114}}</ref> \n\nTherefore, they use the Quran itself to interpret the Quran:<ref>Jens Zimmermann, ''Hermeneutics: A Very Short Introduction'', Oxford University Press, 2015, pg. 90</ref>\n\n===Hadith and Tafsir===\n<blockquote>\". . . .a literal and holistic analysis of the text from a contemporary perspective and applying the exegetical principle of ''tafsir al-qur'an bi al-qur'an'' (explaining the Qur'an with the Qur'an) and the jurisprudential principle ''al-asl fi al-kalam al-haqiqah'' (the fundamental rule of speech is literalness), without refracting that Qur'anic usage through the lens of history and tradition.\"<ref>Mahmoud Ayoub, ''Contemporary Approaches to the Qur'an and Sunnah'', International Institute of Islamic Thought (IIIT), 2012, pg. 27</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis method of interpreting the Quran is different from the method favored by most [[Sunni]] and [[Shia Islam|Shia]] exegetes, known as ''[[Tafsir|tafsir bi-al-ma'thur]]'' (interpreting the Quran with narrations, i.e., hadiths). In contrast to Quranists, Sunnis do not believe that the Quran is fully detailed. They believe that, \"the Qur'an needs the Sunnah more than the Sunnah needs the Qur'an (''inna l-Quran ahwaju ila l-sunna mina l-sunna ila l-Quran'')\".<ref>Jane Dammen McAuliffe, ''Encyclopaedia of the Qur'an, Vol. 5'', Brill, 2006, pg. 165</ref> This methodological difference has led to considerable divergence between Quranists and [[Sunni Islam|Sunnis]] and [[Shia Islam|Shia]] in matters of [[Schools of Islamic theology|theology]] and [[Sharia|law]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n[[Syed Ahmad Khan]] argued that, while the Quran remained socially relevant, reliance on hadith limits the vast potential of the Quran to a particular cultural and historical situation.<ref>Daniel W. Brown Rethinking Tradition in Modern Islamic Thought Cambridge University Press {{ISBN|9780521653947 }} p. 65</ref>\n\nThe extent to which Quranists reject the authenticity of the Hadith and Sunnah varies,<ref name=\"Voss\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.masjidtucson.org/publications/books/sp/1996/apr/page1.html |title=Identifying Assumptions in the Hadith/Sunnah Debate |last=Voss |first=Richard Stephen |date=April 1996 |volume=12 |issue=4 |journal=Monthly Bulletin of the International Community of Submitters |access-date=5 December 2013}}</ref> but the more established groups have thoroughly criticised the authenticity of the Hadith and reject it for many reasons. The most common view being the Quranists who say that Hadith is not mentioned in the Quran as a source of [[Islamic theology]] and practice, was not recorded in written form until a century after the death of Muhammad,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.uncw.edu/bergh/par246/L21RHadithCriticism.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311144448/http://people.uncw.edu/bergh/par246/L21RHadithCriticism.htm |archivedate=2007-03-11 }}</ref> and contain internal errors and contradictions.<ref name=\"The Quranists\"/><ref name=\"Voss\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe Quranist ideology dates back to the time of [[Muhammad]], who prohibited the writing of hadiths.<ref name=\"Musa 2008\">{{cite book |last=Musa |first=Aisha Y. |date=2008 |title=Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on The Authority Of Prophetic Traditions in Islam |publisher=Palgrave |isbn=978-0-230-60535-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Aisha Musa\">Aisha Y. Musa, ''Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam,'' Palgrave Macmillan, 2008, pp.25-29</ref> One of Muhammad's companions and successor [[Umar]], also prohibited the writing of hadith and destroyed existing collections during his rule as [[Caliph]].<ref name=\"Aisha Musa\"/> When Umar appointed a governor to [[Kufa]], he told him: \"You will be coming to the people of a town for whom the buzzing of the Qur'an is as the buzzing of bees. Therefore, do not distract them with the Hadiths, and thus engage them. Bare the Qur'an and spare the narration from God's messenger (peace and blessing be upon him)!\"<ref name=\"Aisha Musa\"/>.\n\nThe centrality of the Quran in the religious life of the Kufans that Umar described was quickly changing, however. A few decades later, a letter was sent to the [[Ummayad]] [[caliph]] [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan]] regarding the Kufans: \"They abandoned the judgement of their Lord and took hadiths for their religion; and they claim that they have obtained knowledge other than from the Koran . . . They believed in a book which was not from God, written by the hands of men; they then attributed it to the Messenger of God.\"<ref>Aisha Y. Musa, ''Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam,'' Palgrave Macmillan, 2008, pp. 37-38</ref>\n\nIn the following years, the taboo against the writing and following of hadiths had receded to such an extent that the Ummayad leader [[Umar II]] ordered the first official collection of Hadith. [[Abu Bakr ibn Muhammad ibn Hazm]] and [[Ibn Shihab al-Zuhri]], were among those who wrote Hadiths at Umar II's behest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.uncw.edu/bergh/par246/L21RHadithCriticism.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311144448/http://people.uncw.edu/bergh/par246/L21RHadithCriticism.htm |archivedate=2007-03-11 }}</ref>\n\nDespite the trend towards hadiths, the questioning of their authority continued during the [[Abbasid]] dynasty and existed during the time of Al-Shafi'i, when a group known as \"Ahl al-Kalam\" argued that the prophetic example of Muhammad \"is found in following the Quran alone\", rather than Hadith.<ref name=DWBRTMIT1996:15-6>[[#DWBRTMIT1996|Brown, ''Rethinking tradition in modern Islamic thought'', 1996]]: p.15-16</ref><ref>excerpted from Abdur Rab, ''ibid'', pp.&nbsp;199\u2013200.</ref> Later, a similar group, \nAhl al-Taw\u1e25\u012bd wa l-\u02bfAdl, \"people of monotheism and justice\", known as the [[Mu'tazilite]]s by their opponents, also viewed the transmission of the Hadith as not sufficiently reliable.<ref>Sabine Schmidtke, ''The Oxford Handbook of Islamic Theology,'' Oxford University Press, 2016, pp. 264-265</ref> The Hadith, according to them, was mere guesswork, conjecture, and [[bidah]] (innovation), while the Quran was complete and perfect, and did not require the Hadith or any other book to supplement or complement it.<ref>Azami, M. A., ''Studies in Hadith Methodology and Literature'', Islamic Book Trust, Kuala Lumpur, 92; cited in Akbarally Meherally, ''Myths and Realities of Hadith \u2013 A Critical Study'', (published by Mostmerciful.com Publishers), Burnaby, BC, Canada, 6; available at  http://www.mostmerciful.com/Hadithbook-sectionone.htm; excerpted from Abdur Rab, ibid, p. 200.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Abassid]] dynasty, the poet, theologian, and jurist, [[Ibrahim an-Nazzam]] founded a [[madhhab]] called the Nazzamiyya that rejected the authority of Hadiths and relied on the Quran alone.<ref>{{cite book |last=Abdul-Raof |first=Hussein |date=2012 |title=Theological Approaches to Quranic Exegesis: A Practical Comparative-Contrastive Analysis |location=London |publisher=Routledge |pages=33\u201334 |isbn=978-0-41544-958-8}}</ref> His famous student, [[Al-Jahiz]], was also critical of those who followed Hadith, referring to his Hadithist opponents as ''al-nabita'' (\"the contemptible\").<ref>{{cite book |last=Zaman |first=Muhammad Qasim |date=1997 |title=Religion and Politics Under the Early 'Abbasids: The Emergence of the Proto-Sunni Elite |location=[[Leiden]] |publisher=[[E.J. Brill]] |page=55 |isbn=978-9-00410-678-9}}</ref> A contemporary of An-Nazzam, [[Al-Shafi'i]], tried to refute the arguments of the Quranists and establish the authority of Hadiths in his book ''Kitab Jima'a l-'Ilm''.<ref name=\"Musa 2008\"/> And [[Ibn Qutaybah]] tried to refute An-Nazzam's arguments against Hadith in his book [[The Interpretation of Conflicting Narrations|''Ta'wil Mukhtalif al-Hadith'']].<ref>{{cite book |last=Juynboll |first=G. H. A. |date=1969 |title=The Authenticity of the Tradition Literature: Discussions in Modern Egypt |location=Leiden |publisher=E. J. Brill |pages=77\u201380}}</ref>\n\nIn South Asia during the 19th century, the Ahle Quran movement formed partially in reaction to the [[Ahle Hadith]] whom they considered to be placing too much emphasis on Hadith.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite book |last=Brown |first=Daniel W. |date=1996 |title=Rethinking Tradition in Modern Islamic Thought |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |pages=38\u201341 |isbn=978-0-52157-077-0}}</ref> Many Ahle Quran adherents from South Asia were formerly adherents of Ahle Hadith but found themselves incapable of accepting certain hadiths.<ref name=\"Brown\"/> \n\nIn Egypt during the early 20th century, the ideas of Quranists like Muhammad Tawfiq Sidqi grew out of [[Salafism]] i.e. a rejection of [[taqlid]].<ref name=\"Brown\"/> Muhammad Tawfiq Sidqi of Egypt \"held that nothing of the Hadith was recorded until after enough time had elapsed to allow the infiltration of numerous absurd or corrupt traditions.\"<ref>Sidqi, Muhammad Tawfiq, ''Al-Islam huwa al-Qur'an wahdahu,'' ''al-Manar'' 9 (1906), 515; cited in {{cite book|last1=Brown |first1=Daniel W.|title=Rethinking tradition in modern Islamic thought |date=1996 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0521570778|pages=88\u201389 |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/116836545/Rethinking-Traditions-in-Modern-Islamic-Thought-Daniel-w-Brown |accessdate=10 May 2018}} </ref> Muhammad Tawfiq Sidqi wrote an article titled ''Al-Islam Huwa ul-Qur'an Wahdahu'' ('Islam is the Qur'an Alone) that appeared in the Egyptian journal ''Al-Manar'', which argues that the Quran is sufficient as guidance: \"what is obligatory for man does not go beyond God's Book. If anything other than the Qur'an had been necessary for religion,\" Sidqi notes, \"the Prophet would have commanded its registration in writing, and God would have guaranteed its preservation.\"<ref>Musa, Aisha Y., ''Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam'', Palgrave Macmillan, New York, 2008, p.6.</ref>\n\n==Contemporary times==\n[[File:Islam branches and schools.svg|thumb|Diagram showing the branches of [[Sunnism]], [[Shiaism]], [[Ibadism]], [[Quranism]], [[Non-denominational Muslim]]s, [[Ahmadiyya]] and [[Sufism]].]]\n\nIn the 21st century, Quranist beliefs have spread in various countries. However, in countries that have incorporated some aspects of Sunni law, adherents have faced opposition. For example, a Saudi scholar, Hassan Farhan al-Maliki, was arrested numerous times for promoting political reform and a return to the Quran.<ref>Kamel Abderrahmani, [http://www.asianews.it/news-en/The-reform-of-Islam-and-the-Koranists,-persecuted-in-Saudi-Arabia-45322.html The reform of Islam and the Koranists, persecuted in Saudi Arabia], asianews.com, Accessed February 15, 2019</ref> [[Saudi Arabia]] began its prosecution of the researcher in the Specialized Criminal Court in Riyadh, which was specially established in January 2009 to handle cases of \"terrorism and national security.\"<ref>[https://www.esohr.org/en/?p=2169</ref> In 2019, the public prosecution, which is directly linked to the Saudi king, leveled charges almost entirely related to Maliki's religious views and has requested that the court sentence him based on \"extremist interpretations\" of Islam.<ref>[https://www.esohr.org/en/?p=2169</ref> And in [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]], Quranists have been arrested for their beliefs.<ref>Ahmed Subhy Mansour, [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/23/opinion/23iht-edmansour.1.19632638.html Egypt persecutes Muslim moderates], nytimes.com, Accessed February 15, 2019</ref><ref>Zeinab Mohammed Salih, [http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/dec/16/sudan-charges-25-death-penalty-apostasy-sharia-law Sudan threatens 25 Muslims with death on charges of apostasy], theguardian.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> \n\nThe spread of Quranist beliefs in [[Russia]] has provoked the anger of the Sunni establishment. The [[Russian Council of Muftis]] issued a [[fatwa]] against Quranism and those it said were its leaders in Russia.<ref>\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043c \u0411\u0430\u0442\u044b\u0440, [https://www.business-gazeta.ru/blog/375729 \u00ab\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u043c\u0443\u0444\u0442\u0438\u0435\u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0445\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u044b \u0432\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0432 \u0434\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0430\u00bb \u041f\u043e\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043d\u0435\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u00ab\u0411\u0418\u0417\u041d\u0415\u0421 Online\u00bb], business-gazeta.ru, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref> However, one of the purported Quranist leaders mentioned in the fatwa, the Russian philosopher Taufik Ibrahim, pointed out that his beliefs were more in line with the [[Jadid]] tradition, although there is some overlap between the two groups in Russia.<ref>Renat Bekkin, [https://realnoevremya.com/articles/3134-interview-with-islamic-scholar-taufik-ibragim Taufik Ibragim: ''Muslims in Russia are not ready for debates yet, unfortunately''], realnoevremy.com, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref> \n\nIn [[Turkey]], Quranists have responded on social media to criticism by the [[Diyanet]] on their Quranist beliefs.<ref>Alper Bilgili, [http://www.patheos.com/blogs/altmuslim/2018/04/quran-hadiths-or-both-where-quranists-and-traditional-islam-differs/  Quran, Hadiths or Both? Where Quranists and Traditional Islam Differs,], patheos.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref>\n\nIn [[South Africa]], an Oxford educated Islamic scholar, Taj Hargey, established the Open Mosque. As the name implies, Hargey intended the mosque to be more open to demographics traditionally shunned by Sunni and Shia mosques, like women. Hargey describes the principles of the mosque as, \"Quran-centric, gender equality, non-sectarian, inter-cultural and independent\".<ref>Gavin Haynes, [https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/vdpap8/open-mosque-taj-hargey-south-africa-934 Meet the British Muslim Who's Founded a Controversial Gay-Friendly Mosque: Dr Taj Hargey is a hardcore fundamentalist, in that he only follows the teachings of the Qur'an, and none of the other footnotes beloved of modern clerics.], vice.com, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref> Hargey has also criticized what he calls the \"toxic trio\" of hadith, sharia, and fatwas.<ref>Lizzie Stromme, [https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/740484/Hadith-Sharia-law-Fatawas-Toxic-trio-infected-Islam-Imam Hadith, Sharia law, Fatawas: 'Toxic trio' has infected and distorted Islam, Imam says], express.co.uk, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref>\n\nAccording to the Quranist website, Ahl al-Quran, Quranists make up a minority of Muslims, numbering only \"a few thousand\" as of 2008, compared to over one billion Muslims in total.<ref name=\"minority\">{{cite web |title=Who Are The Minority Among Muslims: The Quranists Or The Salafists? |url=http://www.ahl-alquran.com/English/show_article.php?main_id=13594 |website=ahl al-quran |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=August 27 , 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Notable organizations==\n\n===Ahle Quran===\nAhle Quran is an organisation formed by Abdullah Chakralawi, who described the Quran as \"ahsan Hadith\", meaning most perfect hadith and consequently claimed it does not need any addition.<ref name=\"Aziz Ahmad\">A\u1e25mad (1967), pp.120-121.</ref> His movement relies entirely on the chapters and verses of the Quran. Chakralawi's position was that the Quran itself was the most perfect source of tradition and could be exclusively followed. According to Chakralawi, Muhammad could receive only one form of revelation ([[wahy]]), and that was the Quran. He argues that the Quran was the only record of divine wisdom, the only source of Muhammad's teachings, and that it superseded the entire corpus of hadith, which came later.<ref name=\"Aziz Ahmad\"/> Ahle Quran is one of the main Quranist movements in Pakistan along with ''Ahlu Zikr''.<ref name=\"seyed\">Dolatabad, Seyed Ali Hosseini, Hossein Naseri Moghadam, and Ali Reza Abedi Sar Asiya. \"Pillars, proofs and requirements of the Quran-Sufficiency Theory, along with its criticism.\" International Journal of Humanities and Cultural Studies (IJHCS) ISSN 2356-5926 (2016): 2303-2319.</ref>\n\n===Izgi Amal===\n{{main|Izgi Amal}}\nThis is a Quranist organization in [[Kazakhstan]] whose Cyrillic name, \"\u0406\u0437\u0433\u0456 \u0430\u043c\u0430\u043b\", may be transliterated into the Latin script as ''\u0130zgi amal''. It has an estimated 70 to 80 thousand members. Its leader, Aslbek Musin, is the son of the former Speaker of the [[Mazhilis|Majlis]], [[Aslan Musin]].<ref>[http://www.nm2000.kz/news/2009-11-27-22877/ \u041b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0438 \u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043c (\u041d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u043e. \u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u0441 \u0410\u0441\u043b\u0431\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043c \u041c\u0443\u0441\u0438\u043d\u044b\u043c)], nm2000.kz, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref><ref>\u0422\u0430\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0442 \u0410\u0434\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432, [http://www.contur.kz/node/517 \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0442\u044b: \u044d\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0449\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u00ab\u0410\u043a \u041e\u0440\u0434\u044b\u00bb \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0443], contur.kz, Accessed March 4, 2019</ref>\n\n=== Kala Kato===\n{{main|Kala Kato}}\n[[Kala Kato]] is a Quranist movement whose adherents reside mostly northern Nigeria,<ref name=\"Sa'isu\">Isa Sa'isu, [https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/kala-kato-meet-group-with-yet-another-perception-of-islam.html Kala-Kato: Meet group with yet another perception of Islam], dailytrust.com.ng, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> with some adherents residing in Niger.<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2009/127248.htm International Religious Freedom Report 2009], state.gov, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> Kala Kato means a \"man says\" in the [[Hausa language]], in reference to the sayings, or hadiths, posthumously attributed to Muhammad. Kala Kato accept only the Quran as authoritative and believe that anything that is not Kala Allah, which means what \"God says\" in the Hausa language, is Kala Kato.<ref>Aminu Alhaji Bala, [http://saspjournals.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/SJAHSS-35B1034-1039.pdf Qur\u2019anists\u2019 Deviant Da'wah as Reflected in Their Trends of Tafsir in Northern Nigeria], saspjournal.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref>\n\n===Malaysian Quranic Society===\nThe Malaysian Quranic Society was founded by Kassim Ahmad. The movement holds several positions distinguishing it from Sunnis and Shias such as a rejection of the status of hair as being part of the awrah; therefore exhibiting a relaxation on the observance of the hijab, which according to Quranists is not in the Quran.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/17894/ |title=Malay intellectual Kassim Ahmad dies |website=The Malaysian Insight |accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Quran Sunnat Society===\nThe Quran Sunnat Society is a Quranist movement in India. The movement was behind the first ever woman to lead mixed-gender [[Jumu'ah|congregational prayers]] in India.<ref>Ziya Us Salam, [https://frontline.thehindu.com/the-nation/i-follow-the-quran/article10074190.ece 'I follow the Quran'], frontline.thehindu.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> It maintains an office and headquarters within Kerala.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/30/muslim-woman-receives-death-threats-leading-prayers-kerala-india |title=Muslim woman receives death threats after leading prayers in Kerala |first=Amrit |last=Dhillon |date=30 January 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref> There is a large community of Quranists in Kerala.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Khan |first=Aftab Ahmad |title=Islamic Culture and the Modern World 2 |journal=Defence Journal |volume=20 |number=4 |date=2016 |page=49}}</ref> One of its leaders, Jamida Beevi, has also spoken out against India's [[Triple talaq in India|triple talaq]] law which is mostly based on the Sunni inspired [[Muslim personal law in India|Muslim Personal Law (Shariat) Application Act, 1937]].<ref>Jiby J Kattakayam, [https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/blogs/jibber-jabber/quran-has-capacity-to-reflect-and-absorb-changes-in-society-over-time-it-did-not-discriminate-between-men-and-women/ \u2018Quran has capacity to reflect and absorb changes in society over time \u2026 it did not discriminate between men and women\u2019], timesofindia.indiatimes.com, Accessed February 10, 2019</ref> The most prominent predecessor to the Quran Sunnat Society in India was from the views put forth by Ahmed Khan in the 19th century.\n<ref>https://fanack.com/religions/quranists-islams-outcasts/</ref>\n\n===Submitters===\n\nIn the United States it was associated with [[Rashad Khalifa]], founder of the [[United Submitters International]]. The group popularized the phrase: The Quran, the whole Quran, and nothing but the Quran.<ref name=\"The Quranists\"/> After Khalifa declared himself the [[Messenger of the Covenant]], he was rejected by other Muslim scholars as an apostate of Islam. Later, he was assassinated in 1990 by a terrorist group. Those interested in his work believe that there is a mathematical structure in the Quran, based on the number 19. A group of Submitters in Nigeria was popularised by high court judge Isa Othman.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://www3.qeh.ox.ac.uk/pdf/nrn/WP2Alkali.pdf |title=Overview of Islamic actors in northern Nigeria |page=16 |author1=Muhammad Nur Alkali |author2=Abubakar Kawu Monguno |author3=Ballama Shettima Mustafa |date=January 2012 |publisher=Nigeria Research Network |accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Tolu-e-Islam===\n{{main|Tolu-e-Islam}}\nThe movement was initiated by [[Ghulam Ahmed Pervez]].<ref>Aisha Y. Musa, ''Hadith As Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam,'' Palgrave MacMillan, 2008, pg. 86</ref><ref>Aisha Y. Musa, [http://www.academia.edu/1035742/The_Quranists The Qur'anists], Academia.edu, Accessed April 7, 2019</ref><ref>Nadeem F. Paracha, [https://www.dawn.com/news/1132974 The rise and fall of a spiritual rebel], Dawn.com, Accessed April 7, 2019</ref><ref>Nadeem F. Paracha, [https://www.dawn.com/news/790958 Crazy diamonds \u2013 V], Dawn.com, Accessed April 7, 2019</ref> Ghulam Ahmed Pervez did not reject all hadiths; however, he only accepted hadiths which \"are in accordance with the Quran or do not stain the character of the Prophet or his [[Sahabah|companions]]\".<ref name=toluislam>{{cite web|url=http://www.tolueislam.com/|title=Bazm-e-Tolu-e-Islam|publisher=|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> The organization publishes and distributes books, pamphlets, and recordings of Pervez's teachings.<ref name=toluislam/> Tolu-e-Islam does not belong to any political party, [[non-denominational Islam|nor does it belong to any religious group or sect]].\n\n==Notable Quranists==\n\n*[[Kassim Ahmad]] (1933\u20132017) a Malaysian intellectual, writer, poet and an educator known for his rejection of the authority of hadiths.<ref>Mariam Mokhtar, [http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/opinion/2017/03/16/dont-let-the-hardliners-get-their-way/  Don\u2019t let the hardliners get their way], freemalaysiatoday.com, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref><ref>Predeep Nambiar, [http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/10/10/kassim-ahmad-died-a-beautiful-death-says-daughter/ Kassim Ahmad died a \u2018beautiful death\u2019, says daughter], freemalaysiatoday.com, February 16, 2019</ref> He was the founder of the Quranic Society of Malaysia.<ref>Gatut Adisoma, [http://www.masjidtucson.org/publications/books/sp/1993/oct/page4.html QURANIC SOCIETY OF MALAYSIA ESTABLISHED], masjidtuucson.org, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref> At the time of his death, he was working on a Malay translation of the Quran.<ref>[http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/son-regrets-kassim-ahmad-unable-to-complete-malay-translation-of-quran#83KyoWWA11spYbCk.97 Son regrets Kassim Ahmad unable to complete Malay translation of Quran], themalayonline.com, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref>\n*[[Rashad Khalifa]] (1935\u20131990), an Egyptian-American biochemist and Islamic reformer. In his book ''Quran, Hadith and Islam'' and his English translation of the Quran, Khalifa argued that the Quran alone is the sole source of Islamic belief and practice.<ref name=\"The Quranists\"/> However, he also claimed that parts of the Quran were fabricated, precluding him from being a strict Quranist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://submission.org/two_false_verses_deeper_look.html|title=Two False verses; A Deeper Look {{!}} Submission.org - Your best source for Submission (Islam)|website=submission.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Quran : the final testament|date=2000|publisher=Universal Unity|others=Khalifa, Rashad.|isbn=1881893030|edition=Rev. ed. 2|location=Fremont, CA.|pages=Appendix 24|oclc=42736348}}</ref>. He further declared that the Hadith and Sunna were 'Satanic inventions' under 'Satan's schemes'.<ref name=\"The Quranists\" /> In the face of widespread anger and hostility by the Muslim world,<ref name=\"The Quranists\" /> Khalifa was stabbed to death on 31 January 1990 by Glen Cusford Francis,<ref>{{Cite web |title=State of Arizona v. Francis, Glen Cusford |url=http://www.investigativeproject.org/case/632/state-of-arizona-v-francis |website=The Investigative Project on Terrorism |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> a member of the terrorist organization, [[Jamaat ul-Fuqra]].\n*[[Ahmed Subhy Mansour]] (born 1949), an Egyptian-American Islamic scholar.<ref name=\"ahl-alquran1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ahl-alquran.com/English/aboutus.php |title=About Us |website=Ahl-alquran.com |date= |accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> He founded a small group of Quranists, but was [[exile]]d from Egypt and is now living in the United States as a political refugee.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/05/12/AR2005051201788.html?noredirect=on |title=Muslims' Unheralded Messenger |first=Don |last=Oldenburg |date=13 May 2005 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Chekannur Maulavi]] (born 1936; disappeared 29 July 1993), a progressive Islamic cleric who lived in Edappal in Malappuram district of Kerala, India. He was noted for his controversial and unconventional interpretation of Islam based on the Quran alone. He disappeared on 29 July 1993 under mysterious circumstances and is now widely believed to be dead.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kumar |first=Girja |date=1997 |title=The Book on Trial: Fundamentalism and Censorship in India |location=New Delhi |publisher=Har Anand Publications |pages=34\u201335 |isbn=978-8-12410-525-2}}</ref>\n*[[Ahmad Rashad]] (born 1949), an American sportscaster (mostly with [[NBC Sports]]) and former professional football player. Ahmad Rashad studied the Arabic language and the Quran with his mentor, the late Rashad Khalifa.<ref>Murray Olderman, [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GrgdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Jl0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=1963%2C3707744 Rashad Made A Name For Himself. . . Twice.], ''The Pittsburgh Press'', Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref><ref>Ken Shouler, [https://www.cigaraficionado.com/article/catching-it-all-6084 Catching It All], cigaraficionado.com, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref><ref>Thomas Lifson, [https://www.americanthinker.com/blog/2013/11/valerie_jarrett_reportedly_dating_a_muslim.html  Valerie Jarrett reportedly dating a Muslim], americanthinker.com, Accsessed February 16, 2019</ref>\n*[[Mohamed Talbi]] (1921\u20132017), a Tunisian historian and professor. He was the founder of the Association Internationale des Musulmans Coraniques (AIMC), or International Association of Quranic Muslims.<ref>Rachid Barnat, [http://www.kapitalis.com/afkar-2/15589-tunisie-islam-le-musulman-coranique-selon-mohamed-talbi.html Tunisie-Islam : Le \u00abmusulman coranique\u00bb selon Mohamed Talbi], kapitalis.com, Accessed February 16, 2019</ref><ref>Sadok Belaid, [http://www.leaders.com.tn/article/22458-in-memoriam-mohamed-talbi-1921-2017 In memorium: Mohamed Talbi (1921-2017) - (Album photos)], leaders.com, Accessed February 16, 2019</ref> \n*[[Edip Y\u00fcksel]] (born 1957), a [[Kurdish Americans|Kurdish American]] philosopher, lawyer, Quranist advocate, author of ''Nineteen: God's Signature in Nature and Scripture'', ''Manifesto for Islamic Reform'' and a co-author of ''Quran: A Reformist Translation''. He taught philosophy and logic at [[Pima Community College]] and medical ethics and criminal law courses at [[Brown Mackie College]].<ref name=\"Musa 2008\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Kenney |first1=Jeffrey T. |last2=Moosa |first2=Ebrahim |date=2013 |title=Islam in the Modern World |publisher=Routledge |page=21}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Karaite Judaism|Karaites]]\n* [[Liberalism and progressivism within Islam]]\n* [[Non-denominational Muslim]]\n* ''[[Sola Scriptura]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Aisha Y. Musa, ''Hadith as Scripture: Discussions on the Authority of Prophetic Traditions in Islam'', New York: Palgrave, 2008. {{ISBN|0-230-60535-4}}.\n* Ali Usman Qasmi, ''Questioning the Authority of the Past: The Ahl al-Qur'an Movements in the Punjab'', Oxford University Press, 2012. {{ISBN|0-195-47348-5}}.\n* Daniel Brown, ''Rethinking Tradition in Modern Islamic Thought'', Cambridge University Press, 1996. {{ISBN|0-521-65394-0}}.\n\n{{Quranism}}\n{{Religion topics}}\n\n[[Category:Quranism| ]]\n[[Category:Quranist Muslims]]\n[[Category:Islamic terminology]]\n", "name_user": "BoogaLouie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDoctrine", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quranism"}
